narrative: 2015-04-01:	April 2015: developed sore throat and otalgia. |2015-06-19:	6/19/15: CT neck showed L tonsillar mass 2.7 x 2.3 cm with necrotic left level 2A lymph node 2.4 x 2.0 cm with additional borderline--enlarged left level 1B and level 3 lymph nodes. |2015-06-23:	6/23/15: Seen by Dr. Blair. |2015-06-27:	6/27/15: CT chest showed no specific evidence of metastatic disease with scattered subcentimeter supraclavicular LN. |2015-06-29:	6/29/15: Panendoscopy with Dr. Blair. |2015-06-30:	David R Martin is a 63Yrs male here for new diagnosis of HNC    Oncologic history:     April 2015: developed sore throat and otalgia. Seen by ENT in Jackson Park who noted L neck mass. 6/19/15: CT neck showed L tonsillar mass 2.7 x 2.3 cm with necrotic left level 2A lymph node 2.4 x 2.0 cm with additional borderline-enlarged left level 1B and level 3 lymph nodes. Visible large L tonsil mass. >4cm not invading BOT or nasopharynx. Palpable L level 2 LN. Path pending. Todays patient complaints are:  Minimal pain after panendoscopy yesterday. The patient still notes odynophagia with solids but not liquids. He has not had problems with maintaining oral intake. |2015-07-13:	7/13/15 -- 10/23/15: On OPTIMA clinical trial. |2015-07-13:	7/13/15: Started induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane. |2015-07-16:	David R Martin is a 63Yrs male with newly diagnosed T3N2b, p16+ left tonsillar SCC, who presents for C1D1 of induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane (on OPTIMA clinical trial). States he is feeling well today and denies any new issues since his last visit. Reports mild sore throat and left sided ear pain that is well controlled with ibuprofen q 2-3 days. He tolerates a regular diet PO and denies dysphagia. Reports good appetite. He has lost 6 lbs since 6/30 which he contributes to increasing his physical activity. States he is walking 2-3 miles daily. Denies fevers/chills/night sweats, fatigue, n/v/d/c, sob, cough, neuropathy. Oncologic history:   April 2015: developed sore throat and otalgia. Pathology p16+    7/13/15: Started induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane. On OPTIMA |2015-07-23:	David R Martin is a 63Yrs male with newly diagnosed T3N2b, p16+ left tonsillar SCC, who presents for C1D8 of induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane (on OPTIMA clinical trial). He currently reports the following:  Mild sore throat and left sided ear pain remains stable and is well controlled with ibuprofen q 2-3 days. Had tooth pulled last week. He reports lower energy since his first treatment, but is still able to walk 1.5 miles daily. Has lost 5 lbs over the past week. Reports decreased oral intake due to no appetite and altered taste. Feels constipated. Last BM 3 days ago. Denies fevers/chills/night sweats, n/v, sob, cough, neuropathy. |2015-07-31:	David R Martin is a 63Yrs male with newly diagnosed T3N2b, p16+ left tonsillar SCC, who presents for C1D15 of induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane (on OPTIMA clinical trial). Weight is stable and he is tolerating a regular diet. Energy level has improved and he continues to walk 1.5 miles daily. Todays patient complaints are:  + dysguesia, having to use more salt  + wt loss, not eating as much and continues to exercise/walk  + 2 loose stools/day since sat. He has lost 7 lbs since 8/4 which he contributes to poor appetite and altered taste. Tolerating a regular diet. Reports low energy last Friday which has since improved. He continues to be active and go on daily walks. |2015-08-17:	Todays patient complaints are:  + 2 loose stools/day per pt smells funny. Non-bloody/non-watery. No further epistaxis  Exercising. He is tolerating treatments well. Main complaint is occasional loose stools (1-2x per day). C.diff checked on 8/18 and negative. Denies fevers/chills or abdominal cramping. Sore throat and left ear pain have resolved with chemotherapy and he is no longer requiring any pain meds. Continues to report decreased appetite and altered taste. Has lost 3 lbs over the past week. Reports mild fatigue, but still able to go on walks. Has occasional numbness/tingling in his feet - not interfering with ADLs. Also reports intermittent blurred vision in right eye. Denies fevers/chills/night sweats, n/v, sob, cough. |2015-08-31:	Todays patient complaints are:  + 2 loose stools/day + watery approx 2 cups. Non-bloody. Feeling Lt headed and dizzy last 48 hrs. States drinking approx 1 gallon water daily. |2015-09-13:	David R Martin is a 63Yrs male with newly diagnosed T3N2b, p16+ left tonsillar SCC, who presents for C3D15 of induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane (on OPTIMA clinical trial). He was set up for daily home IVF after his visit last week, but refused fluids when Walgreens arrived. He then felt dizzy and lightheaded over the weekend and went to his local ER (Advocate Trinity Hospital). He received IVF and was discharged home the next day. Today he continues to report feeling dizzy and lightheaded. He is still having watery non-bloody stools (2-3x daily). Per pt, c.diff was again checked at Trinity Hospital over the weekend and was again negative. He denies fevers/chills or abdominal cramping. Reports nausea last night, but denies vomiting. He is eating well, but continues to report decreased appetite and altered taste. Weight stable over past week. |2015-09-15:	Todays patient complaints are:  Feeling better since transfusion  Fatigued over weekend, did not get tooth pulled as planned  Some loose stools. + Dysguesia |2015-09-22:	/  HPI 63 y/o male with T3N2b left tonsil SCC on Optima trial 14-0639 admitted for cycle 1/3 TFHX. narrative: 2007-07-01:	In the summer of 2007. |2008-01-01:	In January 2008. |2009-08-20:	where he underwent a. maxillectomy with orbital exenteration on 8/20/09 with Dr. |2013-05-01:	He was admitted to U of C in May 2013 for sinusitis -- he was evaluated by Dr. Elizabeth Blair with a flexible endoscopy and MRI which showed no evidence of disease. |2015-03-04:	Vernell Butler is a 40Yrs male with T4NxM0 squamous cell carcinoma of the ethmoid sinus, nasal cavity, and maxillary sinus. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and for further management of his disease. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. In the summer of 2007, he had increased problems with his sinuses and he was diagnosed with osteomyelitis and a sinus infection. He was placed on antibiotics and he began to heal over time. A biopsy was done in August of that summer that showed a tumor involving the maxillary and ethmoid sinuses in the nasal cavities. The pathology on the tumor was invasive keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. On imaging, the tumor involved the lacrimal sac, the medial orbit extending into the orbital contents invading clinically the extraocular muscles and extending into the skin in the region of the medial canthus. He received induction chemotherapy with cisplatin, docetaxel, 5-FU. On this chemotherapy he had tumor progression. In January 2008, he received concomitant chemotherapy and radiation with Taxol, 5-FU, hydroxyurea, and radiation therapy. He completed 2 out of 7 rounds of chemotherapy and was lost to followup. Complications of his treatment include some skin toxicity grade 1 and mucosis toxicity grade 1. He subsequently moved to Colorado for some amount of time, but developed pain in the area that made him concerned that his cancer was growing again. He moved back to Chicago and was seen at Rush University, where he underwent a  maxillectomy with orbital exenteration on 8/20/09 with Dr. Guy Joseph Petruzzelli with palliative intent. Since that time, he reports he has had minimal follow up for his malignancy. He remains with an open sinus - he put off being seen for a prosthesis at UIC because he was "scared". He finally saw them recently, and he was told that he will need a repeat surgery prior to fitting a prosthetic device. He was admitted to U of C in May 2013 for sinusitis - he was evaluated by Dr. Elizabeth Blair with a flexible endoscopy and MRI which showed no evidence of disease. He now presents to establish care again at U of C.  Currently, he states he is doing okay. He is concerned because he has developed new focal pain on the right side of his face and left maxillary sinus. He is dealing with dryness of his open sinuses and has begun using nasal saline spray with some relief. He often gets very congested with dry mucous and this causes pain as well. He denies any fevers or chills. Notably, these symptoms were similar to when he presented in 2013 and was seen by Dr. Blair. His last imaging was over a year ago. narrative: 2016-10-21:	Pt is a 57Yrs old female w/ |2016-10-26:	Brenda Burks is a 57Yrs female with newly diagnosed left tonsillar carcinoma. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and further evaluation. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. Ms Burks is a 57 y/o female who noticed a lump in her neck earlier this month. The mass was initially painless and she self treated with amoxicillin for a couple days. She noticed that it was growing and associated with pain. The pain was primarily present in the mass but also radiated to the left ear. She went to a local ED where she was evaluated and treated with IV Abx. It was recommended that she see an ENT physician and she was prescribed Clindamycin. She was admitted to the MICU here on 10/18 as she presented with fevers, a rapidly growing left neck mass with possible airway compromise due to lateral pharyngeal and supra glottic swelling. Strep was positive and she was started on Unasyn along with steroids. She was evaluated by ENT, Dr Gooi and a Flex Laryngoscopy was performed which revealed evidence of interval improvement in supraglottic swelling and prolapse over glottis, with good patency of airway. Ultrasound guided FNA completed with preliminary results reported as squamous cell carcinoma. She underwent direct laryngoscopy with biopsy on 10/21 which revealed SCC. PET/CT for staging purposes has not been completed yet. In clinic today, she states that she is feeling well. No shortness of breath, minimal pain on swallowing. No fevers/chills. She states that her weight has remained stable. No nausea/vomiting. She has been maintaining good oral intake. Denies fevers, chills, neck/mouth pain. Does endorse stable chest pressure with exertion which has been present for the last year. The pain is relived with rest. She also notes periods of palpitations. Denies presyncopal symptoms. She also notes a history of anxiety. He started experiencing odynophagia and left otalgia accompanied with 20 pound weight loss, which started 3-4 months ago. He endorses progressive difficulty eating solids, followed by liquids particularly in the past month. This led to an esophagoscopy due to concerns for achalasia or other esophageal process. It was here that they found a hypopharyngeal lesion was occurring and the patient was sent to Dr Stetson in ENT. CT scan soft tissue neck on 8/8/12 shows a large, mostly submucosal mass of the left hypopharynx. It extends outside of the thyroid and extends to near the cervical esophageal inlet. In addition, there was multiple lung lesions seen on the CT scan. Biopsy is c/w SCC. . narrative: 2015-08-01:	August 2015: First noticed a left neck mass and sore throat. |2015-08-19:	8/19/15: CT (OSH) demonstrated a 2.4 x 2.8 cm L JD necrotic lymph node and fullness of L tonsil "without discrete mass". |2015-08-25:	8/25/15: Evaluated by OSH ENT. |2015-08-26:	8/26/15: Patient underwent tonsil biopsy which demonstrated invasive SCC. |2015-09-09:	9/9/15: PET/CT (OSH) demonstrated hypermetabolic mass in L tonsillar fossa (2 x 2.5 cm) extending to base of tongue and hypermetabolic L level II lymph node (3 x 2.5 cm). |2015-10-06:	William Dustin is a 69Yrs male here for new diagnosis for HNC. No response with antibiotics    8/19/15: CT (OSH) demonstrated a 2.4 x 2.8 cm L JD necrotic lymph node and fullness of L tonsil "without discrete mass"    8/25/15: Evaluated by OSH ENT. Noted to have enlargement of L tonsil and 2 cm L JD mass on exam. 8/26/15: Patient underwent tonsil biopsy which demonstrated invasive SCC, non-keratinizing, p16+. Also underwent FNA of L neck mass which demonstrated "necrotic debris with inflammation" and "obscuring blood with inflammation"    9/9/15: PET/CT (OSH) demonstrated hypermetabolic mass in L tonsillar fossa (2 x 2.5 cm) extending to base of tongue and hypermetabolic L level II lymph node (3 x 2.5 cm). Also reports nausea, poor appetite, and decreased Po intake on Tues, Wed, Thurs. Nausea now resolved and he is eating better. Having infrequent BMs. Denies fevers/chills, fatigue, neuropathy. States calf pain has since resolved and swelling of left lower leg has improved. Intraoperative findings to guide local SBRT vs systemic therapy. - swallowing without dysphagia or odynophagia. - has significant dryness at all times that persists. - taste and appetite have been good. - continues complain of neuropathy in his fingers since chemotherapy but it is not limiting his function and is able to button buttons and tie shoes. |2014-05-21:	Bruce Buttle is a 57 yrs male with a hx of T3N2b p16+ L tonsillar cancer s/p chemoradiation completed 4/6/12 with subsequent R lung oligometastasis s/p SBRT completed 05/24/2013, then with progressed disease in lung on PET 3/2014, most recently s/p VATS wedge resection with findings of multiple parenchymal and pleural-based nodules. Per Dr. Fergusons note: there was "a conglomeration of metastatic disease posteriorly in the lower lobe, 2 isolated nodules adjacent to each other laterally in the lower lobe, additional possible pleural implants in the lower lobe, a nodule in the parenchyma near the fissure and interlobar artery, and at least 1 implant on the diaphragm. The 2 lateral nodules adjacent to each other were wedge excised in a single specimen and removed in a bag." Pathology confirmed these to be two foci of metastatic SCC. These were not all removed. He saw Dr. Haraf today in clinic. It was discussed with patient that there is no role for local therapy in the absence of any symptoms and especially given that not all lesions are visible on imaging. Since last clinic visit, patient reports:  - Energy/Functional status: working full-time. Energy level 90%, limited by fatigue. - Pain: none, not on narcotics. Mild finger numbers, which may be due to carpel tunnel. No numbness in toes. - Nutrition: eating well. Wt stable. Denies n/v. Continues to have mouth dryness. Has no change in taste. He denies SOB, CP, diarrhea, new pain, or any other acute medical changes. ONCOLOGIC HISTORY:   April 2012: He underwent induction cetuximab/taxol/cisplatin/everolimus followed by chemoradiation (TFH with BID WOWO XRT) for T3N2b p16+ L tonsillar SCC. 3/13/13: CT chest demonstrated new right hilar lymphadenopathy, measuring 1.3 cm in short axis. 3/22/13: PET/CT demonstrated enlarged right hilar lymphadenopathy with  increased FDG uptake and maximal SUV of 7.3. A micronodule in the right perihilar region has minimal uptake. Also, mild FDG uptake is noted in a new nodular density in posterior basal segment of right lower lobe with maximal SUV of 3.2. 4/8/13: Needle aspiration of 11R inferior lymph node revealed metastatic SCC with basaloid features, p16+. A RLL subpleural nodule increased in size from 9x8 mm to 10x9 mm, a pulmonary opacity in the R posterior costophrenic angle became more confluent and suspicious for tumor, and a 5 mm subpleural nodule in the RLL was also increased in size. PET CT also showed progression of moderately hypermetabolic subpleural lesions in the RLL. 12/10/13: He was seen in re-consultation in our department with Dr. Haraf. It was discussed that the toxicity of re-irradiation of the inferior RLL lesions in the prior treatment field would outweigh the benefits and that irradiation of the more superior lesion would be of little benefit if he had other sites of metastatic disease. We recommended evaluation for surgical resection or biopsy by Dr. Ferguson. He recommended either observation with repeat CT in 3 months of VATS biopsy for diagnosis and molecular markers. Mr. Buttle opted for repeat imaging. There was, however, continued increased growth in RLL subpleural nodules. The previous 10 x 9 mm nodule now measured 14 x 12 mm and the previous 5 mm nodule now measured 7 mm. 3/12/14: He was seen in follow-up by Dr. Vokes. A referral was made again  to Dr. Ferguson to discuss biopsy/excision for Foundation Medicine. He was re-referred to our clinic for discussion of SBRT options. |2014-07-02:	He had  CT scan showing his 2 nodules increased in size from previous visit in his lungs. Otherwise feeling well. |2014-02-26:	EGD/EUS was done 2/26/14 which showed obstructing 25--30 cm mid--esophageal mass and non--obstructing 36--39 cm distal mass. |2014-03-04:	HPI 62 y.o male with PMH significant particularly for T2 N2 supraglottic SCC s/o chemoradiotherapy (Cetux FHX) on 2010 who was doing well until 4 weeks ago he started experiencing symptoms of dysphagia/odynophagia. His dysphagia started with solid food and then he ended up not being able to swallow even liquids. He also noticed 20 Ibs weight loss over the past couple of months. He denies any hoarseness, melena, hematochezia, cough or dyspnea. Patient states that his oral intake has significantly decreased due to the dysphagia. The patient underwent work-up for his dysphagia started with esophagogram (1/27/14)which showed mid esophageal stricture concerning for malignancy. CT scan of chest/abdoman/pelvis was done on 2/12/14 and showed large mid-esophageal mass with subcarinal lymphadenopathy with no evidence of of mets to abdomen/pelvis. CT head was also done and showed no evidence of metastasis to brain or recurrence of his head neck tumor. EGD/EUS was done 2/26/14 which showed obstructing 25-30 cm mid-esophageal mass and non-obstructing 36-39 cm distal mass. Those two masses were biopsied. Multiple enlarged nodes were also noted in the subcarinal area. The EUS report states that there is invasion of the muscularis propria (at least T3 N2). Biopsies came back positive for in-situ and invasive SCC in both masses. Patient has PMH of SSS s/p pacemaker placement. Of note, patient had G-tube placed during the treatment for head-neck cancer. Family H: No family H of esophageal cancer or other malignancies. Social H: former smoker ( 1 Pack/day for 30 years. Quit 2009). Social alcohol. narrative: 2004-04-19:	4/19/04: Underwent partial left glossectomy. |2006-09-21:	9/21/06: Wide local excision of oral lesion with transposition of previously placed buccal mucosal flap --> squamous cell carcinoma. |2007-06-28:	6/28/07: Radical resection of left oropharyngeal/tonsil neoplasm --> squamous cell carcinoma. |2007-08-20:	8/20/07: Wide local excision of left oropharyngeal area due to close margin on previous surgery --> no malignancy. |2012-12-17:	12/17/12: Wide local excision of left oropharyngeal lesion --> squamous dysplasia. |2014-03-19:	3/19/14: Wide local excision of left oral lesion and laser ablation of palatal lesion --> superficially invasive squamous cell carcinoma. |2015-03-04:	3/4/15: Wide local excision of a tongue and palate lesion --> squamous cell carcinoma. |2015-10-28:	10/28/15: Ablation of abnormal left retromolar trigone lesion. |2016-05-02:	5/2/16: Laser ablation of intraoral squamous cell carcinoma in situ. |2018-05-22:	5/22/18: Recurrent disease with mapping showing involvement of invasive squamous cell carcinoma in the soft palate. |2018-06-15:	6/15/18: CT --> Extensive tumor involving the left had palate. |2018-06-15:	6/15/18: PET --> Hypermetabolic floor of mouth mass. |2018-06-27:	Cyraina Johnson Roullier is a 57Yrs female with recurrent oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma who presents today for treatment recommendations. Please review below for a detailed account of their oncology history:      1983: Diagnosed with left tongue squamous cell carcinoma s/p wide resection   1988: Noticed spot on left tongue s/p wide local excision -> squamous cell carcinoma  1995: Tongue mass s/p wide local excision -> squamous cell carcinoma  1996: Resection of another tongue lesion   2002: Underwent hemiglossectomy, floor of mouth resection, soft palate carcinoma resection   4/19/04: Underwent partial left glossectomy, resection of left buccogingival tissue, flap, and graft placement -> squamous cell carcinoma  9/21/06: Wide local excision of oral lesion with transposition of previously placed buccal mucosal flap -> squamous cell carcinoma  6/28/07: Radical resection of left oropharyngeal/tonsil neoplasm -> squamous cell carcinoma  8/20/07: Wide local excision of left oropharyngeal area due to close margin on previous surgery -> no malignancy   12/17/12: Wide local excision of left oropharyngeal lesion -> squamous dysplasia   3/19/14: Wide local excision of left oral lesion and laser ablation of palatal lesion -> superficially invasive squamous cell carcinoma  3/4/15: Wide local excision of a tongue and palate lesion -> squamous cell carcinoma  10/28/15: Ablation of abnormal left retromolar trigone lesion   5/2/16: Laser ablation of intraoral squamous cell carcinoma in situ  5/22/18: Recurrent disease with mapping showing involvement of invasive squamous cell carcinoma in the soft palate, tongue-retromolar trigone  junction, alveolar bridge, tongue-pharynx junction, and dorsal tongue  6/15/18: CT -> Extensive tumor involving the left had palate, bilateral soft palate, and bilateral palatine tonsils; crosses midline and extends to posterior aspect of the right oral cavity tongue; slightly enlarged right 2A lymph node; additional scattered bilateral cervical lymph nodes   6/15/18: PET -> Hypermetabolic floor of mouth mass, base of tongue, and multiple bilateral cervical lymph nodes extending into the medial supraclavicular lymph nodes     Overall, she is feeling well. She denies any pain. She has not had any significant issues eating or swallowing. Her speech has changed. She denies significant weight loss. |
Dx_: ['Extensive tumor', 'soft palate carcinoma', 'squamous cell carcinoma', 'intraoral squamous cell carcinoma', 'left tongue squamous cell carcinoma']

He was diagnosed in 1994, underwent radical prostatectomy, and has been on zoladex since 1994. Due to hematuria, he underwent XRT in 2000, but overall, has done well with the above regimen. He also continues on IV zometa for bone health. Today, he reports intermittent dizziness x 2-3 months. He denies headache. This occurs when he is lying flat, or when he is standing up. It lasts for about a minute and then subsides. He denies vertigo and denies low blood pressure. He also reports that he feels more tired than normal, and that there are days when he "tries to do everything" and then days when he "wants to sleep the whole day." Otherwise, he reports no new concerns. He continues his medications as prescribed. |2012-10-09:	Richard Michalak is a 67Yrs male here for follow-up of prostate cancer. He denies any recent fever, chills, CP, SOB, N/V, abdominal pain, D/C, blood in stool or urine, LE edema. He has a firm, approx 3 cm right cervical LN on exam today. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. He has been followed by Dr. Stadler since 1994 for prostate cancer. He has been on surveillance for three years with no detectable disease. In June, he was noted by Dr. Stadler to have a firm 3cm right cervical lymph node. He was referred to Dr. Agrawal. There was also an enlarged right level 3 LN of 1.2 cm and a 2.0 cm bot mass. Biopsies of tongue on 7/21 demonstrated SCC, p16+. The 2.5 cm mass was noted to extend to the midline and vallecula but no lateral pharyngeal wall involvement was seen. He notes he has lost 30 pounds in the past year, but mostly due to dietary changes and decreasing his drinking. He has no dysphagia, odynophagia, or pain. He remains active and takes dancing classes. If he did not have this diagnosis, he would not know he had cancer. narrative: 1999-04-01:	Vijayalakshmi Balakumar is a 70 yr old female with history of recurrent squamous cell carcinoma of the left lateral tongue status post chemoradiation and composite resection with free flap reconstruction completed in April 1999. |1999-04-01:	She first presented with T2N0M0 SCCA of the left lateral tongue and completed chemoradiation in 4/1999. |2000-03-01:	She had a local recurrence and underwent a wide local excision of the left lateral tongue in March 2000. |2000-03-01:	She then had a wide local excision of the left tongue with Dr. Nielsen for a recurrence in 3/2000. |2000-09-01:	In 9/2000 she developed another reuccrence and underwent composite resection of tongue and mandible. |2013-12-01:	Since December 2013. |2014-06-03:	She then presented to Dr. Blair at UChicago for a second opinion on 6/3/2014. |2014-06-09:	Vijayalakshmi Balakumar is a 70Yrs female with recurrent versus new primary squamous cell cancer of the tongue. She also reportedly developed right breast cancer shortly and underwent R mastectomy with axillary LND f/b unknown chemotherapy and tamoxifen. In  December, 2013 she visited a dentist due to a toothache. She was eventually referred to an oral surgeon over the coming months to preform tooth extractions. Then in May, 2014 she underwent extractions. At that time a biopsy of the right retromolar trigone was performed and showed invasive keratinizing moderately differentiated SCCA. She was evaluated at Loyola who reccommended total glossectomy, radical mandibulectomy, partial maxillectomy, and laryngectomy. Dr. Blair performed flexible laryngoscopy, revealing partial prolapse of residual BOT with extensive white thick coating (not extending to vallecula or pyriform sinus). She also underwent rigid oral endoscopy, which revealed extensive exophytic lesion involving the R FOM, R mandibular mucosa extending to RMT, and on into anterior maxillary surface. There were foul-smelling fibrinous debris present. There was symmetric elevation of the palate. There was no cervical/SCV lymphadenopathy. Initial recommendation was for surgery include mandibulectomy, partial or completion total glossectomy, resection  of retromolar trigone and possible resection of anterior maxilla. She presents to medical oncology today for establishment of care. Today, she notes slight fatigue and oral pain, but otherwise denies fevers, chills, night sweats, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, cough, or shortness of breath. She has lost a few pounds over the past few months. ECOG Performance Status:  1 |2014-06-26:	/ HPI  Vijayalakshmi Balakumar is a 70 year old female with history of recurrent squamous cell carcinoma of the left lateral tongue status post chemoradiation and composite resection with free flap reconstruction completed in April 1999. Several months later, she again recurred and returned to India for a composite resection of a left lateral tongue lesion with mandibulectomy and free flap reconstruction. Of note, the patient underwent a right mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection for breast cancer followed by chemotherapy. Since December 2013, the patient has been complaining of dental pain. She was evaluated by her dentist her performed a biopsy of the right retromolar trigone and dental extractions. The biopsy demonstrated invasive keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma, moderately differentiated. She was subsequently evaluated at Loyola who recommended total glossectomy, radical mandibulectomy, partial maxillectomy and laryngectomy. She presents to the University of Chicago for a second opinion. She currently lives with her family. Then developed T4N2M0 SCC/Lung cancer s/p chemo RT  With carbo/tax and consolidation with 3 cycles carbo/docetaxel (due to neuropathy) completed 8/25/10. CT scan improved RUL mass and LAD. Scheduled for repeat IR G-tube placement. Referred to Dr. Tobin. Return to clinic in 3 months with repeat scan. 7/20/11 - Pt c/o jaw pain, no other sxs. Continues to drink ETOH and tob use. Pt has caretaker currently but, is still functional. CT chest and abd dated 6/21 are stable. Will continue to observe, counseled on ETOH and tob cessation. With Jaw pain and buccal induration will plan CT H/N, trial of augmentin and refer to ENT. Refer to PCP. RTC 1 mos. Counseled on tob and alcohol cessation. Plan to RTC 6 mos with CT and labs./VV    8/17/11 - seen by Jasielec/Salgia. Jaw pain resolved. Seen by Dr. Stenson from ENT. CTneck and jaw Xray shows no evidence of recurrent head&neck cancer. Otherwise doing well. 10/19/11 -  Pt is "doing well"  Denies pain, wt stable. No GI complaints, neurologic complaints. C/O productive cough white spt stable over at least 2-3 mos. Of note pt smells of alcohol. Pt continues to eat by mouth. CT reviewed in tumor board and NED, axillary LAD not impressively enlarged and given pts personal hygeine, this is not unexpected. RTC 3 mos with CT and labs./VV  ADDENDUM:  Spoke with sister regarding hi ptn and low NA, could be multifactorial. Pt to reduce ETOH intake. Additionally, will get recheck of CMP, CBC, and blood r/o multiple myeloma in 1 mos./VV    11/16/11 Seen by Jasielec/Villaflor. Doing well. Continues to smoke and  drink alcohol daily. Appetite is good, weight stable. Denies pain anywhere, f/c/s, CP, SOB, abdominal pain. No palpable adenopathy on exam. CBC and CMP normal. UPEP, SPEP pending. Plan to repeat CTscan of neck, C/A in January. RTC after CTscans. MM w/u shows elevated IGA and possible paraprotein. Will plan to get BMBX and skeletal survey in future. CT head,Neck, Chest from 04/13/12 stable. Pt still smoking 2 packs of cigarettes a day and drinking Etoh daily. Brief acute intervention done in clinic today. Pt desires to quit smoking. Chantix prescription given, told to quit a week after starting. Referred to smoking cessation clinic. narrative: 1999-07-01:	In July 1999 and then February 2000. |2000-02-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2000-02-01:	He refused postoperative RT in February 2000 with his second recurrence. |2000-07-01:	In September of 2000. |2000-09-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2001-03-01:	He then received RT to the oral cavity and bilateral neck in March 2001 to 66.6 Gy. |2001-05-01:	A left modified radical neck dissection in May 2001 revealed +1/3 positive LNs. |2002-09-01:	The patient had a recurrence in September 2002 and was restarted on chemotherapy. |2003-08-01:	In August 2003. |2003-10-01:	evaluated in October 2003 in the department of Radiation Oncology. |2003-10-01:	The patient was evaluated in October 2003 in the department of Radiation Oncology. |2007-02-01:	Most recently in February 2007. |2007-05-01:	partial glossectomy and and free flap reconstruction in May 2007. |2007-05-01:	He then underwent partial glossectomy and and free flap reconstruction in May 2007. |2009-08-01:	In August 2009. |2012-12-03:	Donald Korenic is a 60yo male here for follow-up of ... In more detail, this is a 54-year-old gentleman with a history of oral tongue carcinoma with multiple recurrences and excisions. He initially presented in 1984 with oral tongue carcinoma and underwent partial glossectomy. In July 1999 and then February 2000, he developed recurrent, for which he underwent further partial glossectomies. In September of 2000, the patient developed a 6 cm left neck mass. He underwent cisplatin, 5-FU, and docetaxel chemotherapy with a partial response. In August 2003, he again had a floor of mouth recurrence invading the inner mandible. Biopsy revealed squamous cell carcinoma. At that time, he was offered radical surgery with the potential of adjuvant re-irradiation. The patient was not interested in re-irradiation at that time. He subsequently underwent wide local excision and multiple reconstructions for his recurrent cancer. Most recently in February 2007, the patient was found to have another recurrence. Mouth resection revealed invasive squamous cell carcinoma with a positive deep margin. There was in situ carcinoma at the superior margin. Multiple biopsies were taken of the dorsal tongue flap, buccal mucosa which were negative for carcinoma. The patient subsequently underwent reexcision of the tongue and was still found to have recurrent squamous cell carcinoma present within the muscle. He then underwent  partial glossectomy and and free flap reconstruction in May 2007. In August 2009, on a regular follow-up with Dr. Stenson, another oropharyngeal lesion was noticed. A wide local excision of the right oropharyngeal lesion and of the retromolar trigone lesion revealed a right tonsil squamous cell carcinoma. Most recently he presented to Dr. Stenson with 6 week history of dysphagia and mild odynophagia on 10.25.12. CT neck on 10.29.12 showed a new centrally necrotic enhancing mass in the right paratracheal region which extended from the level of the thyroid cartilage superiorly to the level of the upper esophagus inferiorly. The mass invaded the right neck strap muscles and right lobe of the thyroid gland anteriorly and enveloped at least 180 degrees of the right common carotid artery laterally. Medially, it invaded the wall of the trachea causing luminal narrowing and cartilage destruction, although the lumen was patent. The mass was inseparable from the esophagus which was distorted in appearance with obliterated lumen suggesting direct invasion. On 11.6.12, the patient had an FNA of the neck which was positive for SCC. On 11.12.12, he underwent radical resection of the right paratracheal tumor, ligation of the internal jugular vein and flexible esophagoscopy, as well a sternocleidomastoid flap. Pathology demonstrated the following:  A. Strap muscle; excision:   - Skeletal muscle, no tumor present. B. Right thyroid mass; excision:   - Keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma replacing thyroid tissue and   extending to the inked surface. - Perineural invasion present. - Three lymph nodes, no tumor present (0/3). C. Common esophageal wall; excision:   - Keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma extensively infiltrating skeletal   muscle. After review of the case on tumor board, it was decided that the patient is started on TFHX for 4.5 cycles (66Gys due to positive margins, R1  resection). He is here today for a regular follow up. He reports the following:  -dysphagia, present since surgery on 11.12.12. He finished a second course of tapering steroids yesterday (12.2.12) and he is scheduled to receive a trach and G-tube today. -neck tightness and occasional neck pain. -mild dyspnea on exertion, present since his last surgery. He otherwise reports relatively good energy levels, denies fevers/chills, and he is maintaining his weight. |2012-12-24:	/  HPI Recurrent HNC:  R paratracheal mass invading the trachea and the esophagus s/p surgical excision admitted for C1/5 TFHX    The history is provided by the patient. narrative: 2014-01-01:	The patient reports he developed loosening of his right lower teeth and jaw pain in January 2014. |2014-01-01:	He was diagnosed after he developed loosening of his right lower teeth and jaw pain in January 2014 . |2014-03-04:	dental extractions and an incisional biopsy of the mandible on 03/04/2014. |2014-03-04:	He was then referred to oral surgery who proceeded with further teeth extraction and also an incisional biopsy of the mandible on 03/04/2014. |2014-04-18:	He was then referred to Dr. Stenson on 04/18/2014. |2014-04-18:	He had a mandible xray on 04/18/2014 that showed a lytic defect of the right mandibular body. |2014-04-25:	He then had a CT neck soft tissue with contrast on 04/25/2014 that redemonstrated a lytic defect of the superior half of the right mandibular body extending from the incisors to the mesial margin of the socket for the first molar. |2014-04-25:	He also had a CT chest w/ contrast on 04/25/2014 that noted a 5 mm left lower lobe nodule (likely an intrapulmonary lymph node or granuloma). |2014-05-07:	and flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014 who now presents for further management. |2014-05-07:	bilateral neck dissections and submental island flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014. |2014-05-07:	and flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014. |2014-05-07:	dissections and submental island flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014. |2014-05-14:	He then had a flap debridement and reconstruction on 05/14/2014. |2014-05-14:	then had a flap debridement and reconstruction on 05/14/2014. |2014-06-22:	He has completed C4.5 of CRT between 6/22/2014 -- 8/15/2014 using 5--FU and hydrea. |2014-06-24:	/  HPI 65 y/o male with T4N0 right lower alveolus SCC admitted for cycle 1/4.5 TFHX. The history is provided by the patient. Accuracy of the patient data is good. |2014-06-25:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-06-26:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-06-27:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-07-01:	T4N0 cancer of the right lower alveolus. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Mr. Bilek is a 65yoM with newly diagnosed T4N0 right lower alveolus squamous cell carcinoma s/p mandibulectomy, bilateral neck dissections, and flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014 who now presents for further management. He was evaluated by a dentist who confirmed loose right lower teeth. He proceeded with dental teeth extraction. The pathology revealed squamous cell carcinoma. On her exam, his oral cavity revealed about a 3 x 1.5 to 2 cm ulcerative lesion at the extraction sites between the lateral incisors and the second lower molar. There was abnormal tissue along the labial gingiva of the remaining lateral and central incisors. It demonstrated infiltrative margins, and the lytic space was filled with soft tissue density containing an enhancing portion bulging medially. There was no significant clinical adenopathy. He proceeded with a composite resection/rim mandibulectomy, bilateral neck dissections and submental island flap reconstruction on 05/07/2014. |2014-11-12:	Jerry Culhane is a 62Yrs male with cT3N2b HPV+ right BOT SCC. The patient presents to the Head and Neck Medical Oncology Clinic for an initial consultation. Jerry Culhane is a 62 year old man with likely metastatic HPV+ SCC of right BOT. The lesion was noted to extend inferiorly into the right vallecula and base of the epiglottis and posteriorly with the oral pharyngeal wall. There was extension across midline floor of mouth and median raphae. There were also enlarged lymph node at level IIA on the right measuring 2.4 cm, with a suspicious 9 mm node inferior at level III. Initial staging NM Bone scan revealed disease confined to the oropharyngeal cavity and right neck. Due to a mild hearing dysfunction he reports is related to occupational exposure, he elected to receive definitive CRT with cetuximab and RT from 4/21/14-6/9/14. His cetuximab was initially dosed at 450 mg/m2 but was dose reduced to 250 mg/m2 due to severe mucositis and one cycle of chemotherapy was deferred due to severe mucositis. He reports that he did well initially after CRT. He had improvement in his energy level and was tolerating soft/pureed foods PO. He presented for post-treatment CT scan of the neck on 8/4/14 which showed his right tonsillar mass to be less "clearly discernable" and decreased size of the right level IIA lymph node. He received restaging PET scan 9/2/2014 which did not appreciate the previously identified hypermetabolic areas locate  in the right base of tongue and right cervical node. However, there was a new focus of uptake in the left tonsil with a SUV of 4.7. In addition, there was increased metabolic activity in the right yupper lobe with a SUV of 4.6 and surrounding GGO around this lesion with SUV of 2.2. As he was noting some SOB and new signs of aspiration, he was given a 7 day course of levaquin per his wife with improvement in his SOB. In early October he began to notice worsening dysphagia to both solids and liquids and increased fatigue. Around October 11th, he noticed acute onset of anterior neck swelling and reports that over the course of the month he was prescribed two Z-paks with improvement in the swelling although he does not feel his neck has returned to baseline. In addition, since that time, he has had worsening oral secretions described as thick, brownish-green in color. He is also concerned about episodes of hypotension leading to falls at home. He reports these episodes of hypotension usually occur when he is bending over to pick something up. He reports 4 non-traumatic falls over the past couple of months due to hypotension. On October 27th he had CT Chest wo and was noted to have 2-3 subcentimeter (largest reported to be 7mm) lesions in the LUL. He denies CP, SOB. No lesions were appreciated in the right lung. Overall, he feels that his functional status has declined over the past month. He notes more fatigue, feeling able to complete only 1-2 small activities per day. He continues to get in good nutrition via G tube and reports that he is maintaining stable weight, but has not returned to his pretreatment baseline weight of 185#. He is a never smoker. He has baseline hearing loss due to occupational exposures, but does not require a hearing aid. The patient also reports near resolution of his previous dysphagia after he started a course of fluconazole. Today we have discussed tem/cetux    Feeling "OK". + neck pain/stiffness, no stridor, no dysphagia  Energy OK  Appetite OK |2012-06-11:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 62Yrs male here for follow-up of his recurrent HNSCC/ BOT p16/HPV+. Generally feeling well. |2012-07-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-07-09:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 63Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent HNC on tem+cetux study. |2012-07-30:	Mr. Jeffrey Zickler is a 63yo male with recurrent metastatic R base of tongue SCC, enrolled on the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus study. He underwent surgical resection accompanied by a right-sided modified radical neck dissection with 4/10 positive lymph nodes, followed by MTX/vincristine/doxorubicin/cisplatin (it is a bit unclear why that  regimen was recommended, or the duration thereof). Between early and late 2010, he had 2 local R neck recurrences for which he underwent surgical resections. In between his two  recurrences, Mr. Zickler stated that he had a brief period of cetuximab, but did not seem to control his disease. Following the last of his surgeries, he developed bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy and underwent chemoradiation  with cisplatin every three weeks, between March and June of 2011. After completion of this treatment, he had no evidence of residual disease by a PET scan by fall of 2011. By February of 2012 on subsequent imaging, he had evidence of disease recurrence based on a PET CT, which showed significant uptake in bilateral level 3 cervical lymph nodes up to 1 cm, a soft tissue density that was PET-avid near the right laryngeal cartilage and pretracheal soft tissue nodule, as well as the left side of the trachea. The pretracheal area and both lymph nodes that were concerning were subjected to fine needle aspiration and were all consistent with squamous cell carcinoma. He was enrolled in the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus trial, and he is currently here for a regular follow up. He is C3D1 on ArmB (temsirolimus only). He had CTs on 7.23.12 with stable disease. He reports the following:   -significant headache with migraine-like features (photosensitivity), band-like distribution, present on Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday (Monday is temsirolimus infusion day). Started sumatriptan with relief provided only on Monday night and Tuesday, but pain is significant 10/10 throughout the day on Wednesday and Thursday and resolves on Thursday night. He is using naproxen (6-8 pills/day) on Wednesdays and Thursdays with no signficant relief. Tramadol and sumatriptan x2/week have caused deterioration of headache. -neuropathic neck pain: resolved on gabapentin 300mg TID. -overall improved neck swelling/nodules over the past 3 months.Notes intermittent neck swelling. -stable dysphagia. -mild nausea associated with headache controlled with 1 compazine / week. |2012-09-26:	He is C5D1 on ArmB (temsirolimus only). He had CTs on 9.17.12 with stable disease. He reports the following:   -resolution of headaches for the past 3 weeks, correlating with initiation of pregabalin. -persistent neck pain: on naproxen as needed and diclofenac cream. -generalized fatigue, stable. -R neck lesion: feels harder, causes difficulty with moving jaw to L.  -positional dyspnea with turning of the head to the L.      He was seen by ENT (Dr. Portugal) on 9.10.12 and fiberoptic laryngoscopy was performed for evaluation of positional dyspnea with neck turning, which showed a web of scar tissue on the epiglottis and the lateral pharyngeal walls (L>R), which appeared to osbstruct patient's airway with turning of the head to the L. |2012-11-26:	Mr. Jeffrey Zickler is a 63yo male with recurrent R base of tongue SCC, enrolled on the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus study. He underwent surgical resection accompanied by a right-sided modified radical neck dissection with 4/10 positive lymph nodes, followed by MTX/vincristine/doxorubicin/cisplatin (it is a bit unclear why that regimen was recommended, or the duration thereof). In between his two recurrences, Mr. Zickler stated that he had a brief period of cetuximab, but did not seem to control his disease. Following the last of his surgeries, he developed bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy and underwent chemoradiation with cisplatin every three weeks, between March and June of 2011. He has been on ArmB (temsirolimus only) and had CTs on 11.12.12 (C6D22) which showed locally progressive disease. CT chest was negative for metastatic disease. He reports the following:   -worsening tightness on R side of neck with occasional R neck wound bleeding x 2-3months. -persistence of headaches on Tuesdays/Wednesdays after Monday temsirolimus injection, which subsides on Thursdays. The pain is usually 4-5/10 controlled with naproxen 500mg daily the days of headache and pregabalin 150mg TID, but once per month, intensity increases to 10/10 and he uses meperidine 50mg once/week with some relief. He tried hydromorphone 2 weeks ago, but it caused rebound headaches. -recurrent mouth sores and pain, relieved significantly with viscous lidocaine. -mild positional dysphagia with turning of neck to L.  -improved sleep pattern with clonazepam (sleeps 6h/day). -maintaining weight. -positional dyspnea with turning of the head to the L [he was seen by ENT (Dr. Portugal) on 9.10.12 and fiberoptic laryngoscopy was performed for evaluation of positional dyspnea with neck turning, which showed a web of scar tissue on the epiglottis and the lateral pharyngeal walls (L>R), which appeared to obstruct patient's airway with turning of the head to the L]. |2012-12-24:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 63Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent HNC on tem + cetux |2013-01-14:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 63Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent HNC. |2013-01-28:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 63Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent SCCHN. |2013-02-04:	Jeffrey Zickler is a 63Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent HNC |2013-02-15:	Mr. Jeffrey Zickler is a 63yo male with recurrent metastatic R BOT SCC who recently progressed on the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus study, enrolled and starting C1D1 of HER3 mAb trial today. In more detail, he initially presented in March 2009 with an incidental right neck mass concerning for lymphadenopathy and endoscopy with revealed R base of tongue SCC (TxN2bM0) (HPV status unknown). He was enrolled in the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus trial, and he was initially on the temsirolimus only but progressed and was crossed-over to the temsirolimus/cetuximab arm. Unfortunately he progressed further in  01.13 and he was enrolled in the HER3 mAb phase I trial. Today is C1D1 of the HER3 mAb trial. He reports the following:   - "air hunger", worsening over the past 1 week. -persistent skin hand and feet fissures, which are painful and compromising daily activities. He applies occasionally takes naproxen as needed for pain control (worried to take demerol due to fear of drowsiness). - acneiform rash in abdomen, managed with local lidocaine cream and fluocinonide cream. -stable dysphagia, but still able to maintain po intake (refuses G-tube). - significant sleep difficulty due to positional problems with his neck. |2013-02-18:	Mr. Jeffrey Zickler is a 63yo male with recurrent metastatic R BOT SCC who recently progressed on the cetuximab +/- temsirolimus study, enrolled and starting C1D8 of HER3 mAb trial today. narrative: 2015-06-01:	The mass developed in June 2015 and was tender at that time; it also caused some difficulty swallowing. |2015-09-01:	Mr. Webb was referred to ENT at UCMC in mid September 2015 after experiencing growth of a R sided neck mass. |2015-09-30:	Donald Webb is a 61Yrs male with newly diagnosed R tonsillary mass. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and discussion of treatment. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. PCP ordered MRI neck which showed growth next to right palatine tonsil, with extension down to base of tongue and swelling of lymph nodes adjacent to area. MRI findings consistent with squamous cell carcinoma. Pt denies cigarette use, heavy alcohol use, or prior HPV infection. Today he is doing well in clinic but he and his wife are not sure why they are in clinic - they were told he was being worked up for cancer and that there "may be" a cancer but have no memory of being told anything definitive. He otherwise is feeling well - no pain at the site of the right neck mass. He has full range of motion in the neck as well as in the oral cavity. |2015-10-09:	Today he is doing well. He has qualified for the OPTIMA trial and has come by the clinic to enroll in the trial after reviewing the consent form we provided he and his wife during his last visit. He has a number of questions involving the scheduling of the treatment, duration of treatment, side effects of treatment, and when we can start the treatment. He is otherwise doing well with no major changes. narrative: 2016-04-01:	April 2016: He had dysphagia that worsened. |2016-05-23:	5/23/16: L neck FNA revealed SCC. |2016-06-03:	6/3/16: CT neck with contrast revealed irregular peripheral enhancement of L lateral neck mass (2.4 x 2.8 x 2.2 cm). |2016-06-07:	His pertinent oncologic history is as follows:    April 2016: He had dysphagia that worsened. He also noted a growing L neck mass. He did receive a course of antibiotics. Dr. Han noted 2cm exophytic mass at L BOT. Larynx and HPX were normal. L BOT biopsy revealed infiltrating moderately-differentiated SCC, p16+. CT CAP revealed no metastases. PET/CT revealed focal abnormal increased uptake in L tongue base with ill-defined left upper cervical chain LAD posterior and lateral to primary tongue carcinoma (2.3 x 1.7 cm). Additional asymmetric enlarged left lower cervical chain LN had increased uptake c/w additional nodal metastases. Comes to clinic doing well. PS 0    PAST MEDICAL, SURGICAL, SOCIAL, AND FAMILY HISTORY |2016-06-16:	Nicholas Villanueva is a 75Yrs male former smoker with T2N2b p16+ left BOT SCC, on OPTIMA trial, currently receiving induction chemotherapy with carboplatin/abraxane. He presents for C1D1 of induction chemotherapy. States he is feeling well and denies any changes since he was last seen. Reports left neck soreness, mild odynophagia, and intermittent left ear pain. Not requiring any pain medication at this time. He tolerates a regular diet PO and has a good appetite. Also reports good energy levels denies fatigue. Denies fevers/chills, n/v/d/c, neuropathy, dysphagia. |2016-06-21:	He presents for C1D8 of induction chemotherapy. Reports fatigue and feeling lightheaded Thursday through Saturday. Lightheadedness resolved after holding lisinopril. Left neck soreness and intermittent left ear pain has resolved. He continues have mild throat pain when swallowing, but feels this has improved. Has been eating less over the past week due altered taste and has lost 5 lbs. Notes 1 day of constipation that resolved after increasing fiber in his diet. He denies fevers/chills, n/v/d, neuropathy. |2016-06-30:	He presents for C1D15 of induction chemotherapy. He is feeling well today and thinks his cervical LAD has decreased. He has been eating better over the past week and reports improved appetite. Gained 3 lbs since last visit. Left neck soreness and intermittent left ear pain resolved after his first treatment of chemotherapy. Still has mild throat pain when swallowing, but improved. Having regular BMs after increasing fiber in his diet. Reports mild intermittent numbness in his toes. He denies fevers/chills, n/v, fatigue. |2016-07-07:	He presents for C2D1 of induction chemotherapy. He is feeling well today and thinks his cervical LAD has decreased since starting treatment. He continues to report a globus sensation, but denies any throat pain. He is eating well and has a good appetite. Gained 3 lbs since last week. Reports mild intermittent numbness in his feet. He denies fevers/chills, n/v. Energy improved. |2016-07-11:	He presents for C2D8 of induction chemotherapy. Presents with fatigue grade 2 after first week of cycles. Improves in the 2nd cycle. PS 1. |2016-07-19:	He presents for C2D15 of induction chemotherapy. Reports fatigue and watery diarrhea last Wednesday and Thursday, not associated with fevers/chills or abdominal pain. This has now resolved and he is feeling well today. Weight stable. He still reports globus sensation, but feels his cervical LAD has decreased since starting treatment. Denies any pain. Denies n/v, neuropathy. |2016-07-27:	He presents for C3D1 of induction chemotherapy. States he had a good week and is feeling well today. His energy level is a little lower since starting chemotherapy, but he is still active and able to run errands. Napping about 1 hour during the day. Also reports occasional tingling sensation in his feet. This is very mild and intermittent at this time and not affecting his ADLs. He is eating well and has gained 4 lbs since last week. Denies any pain, but still reports globus sensation. Notes significant improvement of left cervical LAD since starting treatment. Denies fevers/chills, n/v/d/c. |2016-08-01:	He presents for C3D8 of induction chemotherapy. Main issue over the past week was constipation despite taking miralax daily and drinking prune juice. He finally had a BM on Friday after adding pericolace BID to his regimen. He is now having regular BMs. Also reports decreased appetite and low energy last week which is now improving. He continues to experience intermittent tingling in his feet. States this is mild and not affecting ADLs. Occasionally feels lightheaded when changing positions. His weight is stable. Denies pain, fevers/chills, n/v. |2016-08-08:	He presents for C3D15 of induction chemotherapy. Accuracy of the patient data is good. |2014-03-26:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-03-27:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-03-28:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-03-28:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-04-13:	-- 4/13/14--4/18/14: patient rvg cycle 2/5 TFHX. |2014-04-15:	/  HPI 73 y/o male with recurrent BOT SCC T3N2b admitted for cycle 2/5 AFHX on protocol 12-1554. |2014-04-16:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-04-17:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-04-18:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-04-18:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-04-23:	William Steele is a 74Yrs male with recurrent invasive base of tongue SCC, T3N2b. Now status post cycle 2/5 AFHX with moderate acute toxicity. PS 1. Additional concerns include:  - improved from pneumonia. Breathing back to baseline. Has completed Augmentin. - low HR during cycle 2. Continues on amiodarone. Holding diltiazem, digoxin per cardiology. - low mood. Improving while at home. Off ativan. Continues zoloft. Holding ritalin and klonopin. To see Dr Tobin. - nutrition: using 6 cans GTF per day. Weight stable. Getting 10% calories PO. -pain: well controlled. Continues on hydrocodone-acetaminophen. Onc history:   Diagnosed in 2007 s/p chemo RT on epic trial. |2014-04-29:	/  HPI 73 y/o male with recurrent BOT SCC T3N2b admitted for cycle 3/5 AFHX on protocol 12-1554. |2014-04-30:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-05-01:	Mr. Steele is a 73 year old man with hx of hypothyroid, GERD, paroxysmal afib, and recurrent invasive base of tongue SCC, T3N2b admitted for chemoradiation cycle 3 of 5 TFHX on 12-1554 on 4/27, transferred to the oncology service for management of atrial fibrillation. In March he was discharged with amiodarone, digoxin, and diltiazem. During his admission for cycle 2/5 for TFHX, dig and dilt were held for hypotension and bradycardia. He was continued on BID amiodarone dosing. On admission for cycle 3, cardiology was consulted who recommended reducing amiodarone to 200 mg daily. On the evening of 4/30, was noted on telemetry to be having paroxyms of atrial fibrillation. Normotensive, asymptomatic. EKG at the time with sinus tachycardia to the 120s. Received one push of IV metoprolol 2.5 mg. EKG on 5/1 with sinus tachycardia. Oncologic history:   - 3/07: Had URI, noted growing mass in L side of neck. PCP prescribed Augmentin. No improvement, so referred to local ENT. Mass noted, biopsied and c/w poorly differentiated carcinoma of the L tonsil. - 3/2/07: panendoscopy revealed a 2.5 cm left tonsillar mass confined to the tonsillar fossa. The mass was biopsied, the pathology of which was consistent with poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma  - Started EPIC trial (induction with carboplatin, paclitaxel, cetuximab followed by randomized chemoradiation   - Within first week of treatment, developed pna, admitted to Hinsdale Hospital, admission requiring intubation, temporary tracheostomy, 5 month hospital stay   - 1/08: CT scan with NED   -  6/2009: transhyoid pharyngotomy for wide local excision, tracheostomy. Margins noted to be positive, and had re-excision. Then de-cannulated   - 10/2011: increasing L base of tongue lesion, panendoscopy negative for cancer however iopsy may have been too superficial   - 11/2011: PET scan with uptake in base of the tongue  - 1/2012: Underwent sx partial tongue resection  - 12/2013: New recurrence   - Most recent CT showed slight increase in mass at BOT. - 3/23/14-3/28/14: Received cycle 1/5 TFHX. Complicated by nausea and diarrhea. Controlled with Zofran and Compazine. C.dif negative. - Patient was admitted to OSH with pneumonia and rapid rate afib/flutter and was discharged home on augmetin, amniodarone, digoxin and diltiazem   - 4/13/14-4/18/14: patient rvg cycle 2/5 TFHX. He had bradycardia resulting in stopping his digoxin and diltiazem. He was also seen by psych due to depression and started on Zoloft, Ritalin and klonopin. SUBJECTIVE:  Not complaining of chest pain, palpitations, shortness of breath. Cannot tell when he is tachycardic or in an irregular rhythm. |2014-05-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-05-11:	Now status post cycle 3/5 AFHX with moderate acute toxicity. Patient still has sore mouth but denies fever and feels a bit stronger than after previous cycle. |2014-05-12:	/  HPI 73 y/o male with recurrent BOT SCC T3N2b admitted for cycle 4/5 AFHX on protocol 12-1554. The history is provided by the patient and the spouse. |2014-05-28:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-05-29:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-05-30:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-10-08:	Patient finished 5/5 AFHX with moderate acute toxicity but had residual tumor in June. Subsequently was admitted to Hinsdale Hospital for long admission for pneumonia, progressive weakness and A-fib. Pt was then discharged to hospice and has slowly regained strength. Formally still in hospice with weekly visits. Fed through GT. Has been gaining weight and strength and is able to walk. He has noted jerky arm and leg movements over several months, possible related to amiodarone. Pain is controlled. New recurrence 12/2013, treated with CT-XRT. |2014-10-10:	NO NEW INFORMATION|

D/W pt and wife if diffuse bone mets treatment would be palliative. Bone scan reviewedd in tumor board, unclear if true mets, may be arthritis, will continue to observe. narrative: 2008-01-12:	TFHX 1/12/08. |2011-05-17:	5/17/11 -- Pt comes to clinic with worsening anorexia and wt loss of 6 lbs over 3--4 mos with h/o cancer. |2011-07-12:	7/12/11 --. |2012-01-10:	1/10/12 -- PT doing well. |2012-07-01:	Had Egus dilation in June/July 2012 with EGD. |2012-07-02:	Darren Steeves is a 47Yrs male here for follow-up of T4N0 Larynx SCC had resection at Mayo with subsequent rapid recurrence and now s/p TFHX 1/12/08  5/17/11 - Pt comes to clinic with worsening anorexia and wt loss of 6 lbs over 3-4 mos with h/o cancer. Physical exam new rhonchii R>L.  Needs CT h/n/c/a given tob hx. Also drinking wiskey- counseled on cessation. See ENT today, RTC approx 1 mos with CT and labs./VV  7/12/11 -  Pt tol po inc some solids. Still has xerostomia. Pt now off synthroid in 5 weeks, will see Dr. Blair to address. CXR clear, CT neck NED. Counseled on ETOH cessation. RTC 6 mos with CT H/N and cxr and labs./VV  1/10/12 - PT doing well, tol solids, wt stable. Continues to have xerostomia. Hypothyroid controlled continue cytomel and synthroid. CT - NED, RTC 6 mos with CT and labs. Pt will f/u with ENT for increased tx at trach site, no def evid of cancer./VV  . Todays patient complaints are:  Pt doing well, has had recent esophageal dilation and laryngeal dilation. Pt doing well. Dysphagia has improved following dilation. Breathing also improved. No new issues, continues to have xerostomia. Tol PO including solids, wt is stable. |2013-01-06:	Pt will f/u with ENT for increased tx at trach site, no def evid of cancer./VV  Had Egus dilation in June/July 2012 with EGD, no evid of Barretts. Todays patient complaints are:  Pt doing well, having some issues with breathing plan tracheal dilation tomorrow with Dr Blair. Tol PO, inc solids. Still with xerostomia. Wt stable to mildly increased. |2015-01-19:	Darren Steeves is a 49Yrs male here for follow-up of T4N0 Larynx SCC had resection at Mayo with subsequent rapid recurrence and now s/p TFHX 1/12/08     Todays patient complaints are:   Tolerating PO intake including solid foods such as meats, needs trach dilation and egus dilation  No problems with trach   Weight stable. Continues to drink 10 alcoholic drinks per week |2015-07-22:	Last esophageal dilation on 7/22/2015. |2016-01-26:	Darren Steeves is a 50Yrs male with history of T4N0 squamous cell carcinoma of the larynx with bilateral vocal cord paralysis, status post chemoradiation therapy 1/08, complicated by tracheal and esophageal stenosis and hypothyroidism. He is followed for cancer surveillance as well as his tracheal and esophageal stenosis, dysphagia, vocal cord paralysis, and hypothyroidism. He requires esophageal dilations q 6-8 months. Today reports increasing dysphagia for the past 3 weeks, and only mildly increased SOB with exertion. Currently patient takes all food PO but says takes forever to put anything down. Maintaining weight. Otherewise patient has no other complaints and denies any pain, new mass/lesion, and recent illness/fever. He is seen by Dr. Blair today, planned for DLE with Esophageal and Tracheal Dilation tomorrow (1/27/16) |2016-01-27:	planned for DLE with Esophageal and Tracheal Dilation tomorrow (1/27/16) |2016-03-08:	Pt comes to clinic today with c/o:  + dysphagia, with food getting stuck in throat, + throat pain. + Tol PO liquids and softs, but with increasing stricture is aspirating more. narrative: 2013-01-01:	Underwent surgery with Dr. Stenson May 1st 2013 to resect recurrent oral lesion. |2013-05-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2013-05-14:	Beulah Bentley is a 81 woman with recurrent tongue cancer s/p radiation and chemotherapy x6 weeks in Hobart IN in 2010, then recurrent and had total glossectomy with Dr. Stenson + free flap reconstruction, now with recurrence near right posterior alveolar ridge. Also has distant metastasis in lung at this point and is here in clinic to discuss treatment options, in particular options that may not be toxic given her age. Here to discuss treatment with MK3475, at least to authorize tissue pre-screening. |2013-06-04:	Here to discuss further details of potential treatment with MK3475, at authorize tissue pre-screening with PD-L1 tissue testing. Otherwise feeling well. States that she is not interested in an overly aggressive treatment that would make her feel poorly. |2013-07-16:	Also has distant metastasis in lung at this point and had tissue tested for PDL1 expression that returned positive. She is now here to sign consent for treatment on the MK3475 (lambrolizumab) study. Otherwise she continues to feel well. Some constipation with opioid use for which she uses Miralax. |

narrative: 2010-07-16:	Gersain Cisneros is a 35Yrs male here for follow--up of T4 N1 Oral tongue cancer treated with carbo taxol induction chemotherapy then 5/5 cycles of TFHX chemoradiotherapy completed in 7/16/2010. |2010-07-16:	induction with carbo/taxol f/b TFHX 7/16/10. |2011-06-14:	6/14/11-- current on EPOC prevention trial placebo vs erlotinib. |2012-05-20:	Gersain Cisneros is a 34Yrs male here for follow-up of T4N1 BOT SCC s/p induction with carbo/taxol f/b TFHX 7/16/10. 6/14/11- current on EPOC prevention trial placebo vs erlotinib. Pt comes to clinic today without new complaints. Cycle 12 today erlotinib vs placebo. Spanish translator |2012-07-05:	Gersain Cisneros is a 35Yrs male here for follow-up of T4 N1 Oral tongue cancer treated with carbo taxol induction chemotherapy then 5/5 cycles of TFHX chemoradiotherapy completed in 7/16/2010. Also has a history of a T1 oral tongue tumor that was previously excised. Afterwards treated on EPOC study with erlotinib/placebo (chemoprevention trial). Since then cancer free and feeling well. Excellent functional recovery, able to eat most foods. |2012-11-20:	Afterwards treated on EPOC study with erlotinib/placebo (chemoprevention trial) - completed ~6 months ago. Overall he has had a very good recovery post CRT. He still has some swallowing problems, but is able to eat most foods with appropriate effort. |2013-05-21:	Afterwards treated on EPOC study with erlotinib/placebo (chemoprevention trial) - completed ~12 months ago. Swallowing problems remain, still not eating meat by itself, only with water/liquid. Left side of tongue remains sore. |2013-11-05:	Afterwards treated on EPOC study with erlotinib/placebo (chemoprevention trial) - completed. Feeling well    Can eat virtually all foods although some effort required. Not spicy foods. Left side of tongue remains unchanged and mildly sore. Good appetite, weight stable. Good energy, works full time. |2014-11-04:	Feeling well    Now here for 4+ year f/u. Eating very well, and tolerates almost all foods. Not spicy foods (not eating any). Left side of tongue still mildly sore. |2015-11-02:	Now here for 5+ year f/u. |
Dx_: ['SCC', 'T1 oral tongue tumor', 'T4 N1 Oral tongue cancer']

narrative: 2013-07-26:	Angel Candelaria is a 76Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent dysplasia with a history of OSCC (verucous).Previously on EPOC with skin changes. |2016-11-17:	11/17/16 still oral sensitivity. |2017-05-09:	Seen in ENT clinic 5/9/2017 still local symptoms and applying fluticasone. |2017-06-09:	Seen in ENT clinic 6/9/2017 worsening verrucous lesion. |2017-07-03:	Recently with new recurrent HNSCC upper lip and resection with Dr. Blair 7/3/2017. |2017-07-03:	Then developed recurrent HNSCC upper lip and resection with Dr. Blair 7/3/2017. |2017-07-03:	7/3/2017t excision. |2017-08-25:	Started C1D1 of PATHWay/additional chemoprevention study on 8/25/17. |2017-08-31:	then CIS on biopsy/tooth 8/31/2017. |2017-08-31:	8/31/2017 Tooth biopsy. |2017-09-25:	Started C1D1 of PATHWay/additional chemoprevention study on 9/25/17. |2017-09-25:	Started PATHWay trials 9/25/2017. |2017-09-25:	Angel Candelaria is a 80Yrs male here for follow-up of multiple recurrent dysplasia with a history of OSCC (verucous). Previously on EPOC with skin changes from treatment. Recently with new recurrent HNSCC upper lip and resection with Dr. Blair 7/3/2017, then CIS on biopsy/tooth 8/31/2017. He presents today to start participation in the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient notes that he feels well overall but he's a little nervous about starting treatment. He notes occasional pain in his right upper jaw around the tooth biopsy which is improving--hasn't needed to take ibuprofen for pain for several weeks. He has to eat slowly and carefully, and he also moves the same way due to arthritis in his left knee. His energy is pretty good--able to perform his ADLs independently, and he notes occasional constipation. Otherwise, he denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting. Oncologic History (per ENT/Dr. Blair):  10/20/2015left verrucous upper lip lesion. Biopsy showed  "squamous mucosa with hyperkeratosis, chronic inflammation, and reactive atypia, negative for carcinoma." Pathology from biopsy performed at this visit showed squamous mucosa with hyperplasia, hyperkeratosis, extensive chronic inflammation, and mild atypia. No carcinoma. Seen in ENT clinic 5/9/2017 still local symptoms and applying fluticasone    Seen in ENT clinic 6/9/2017 worsening verrucous lesion     7/3/2017t excision. Path below - verrucous carcinoma/PVL    8/31/2017 Tooth biopsy  Carcinoma in-situ/PVL     Started C1D1 of PATHWay/additional chemoprevention study on 8/25/17. |2017-10-17:	Angel Candelaria is a 81Yrs male here for follow-up of multiple recurrent dysplasia with a history of OSCC (verucous). He presents today for C1D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient notes that he feels well today. His right upper jaw pain from his last biopsy has resolved, and he's eating a little better. He tolerated his first dose of PATHWay treatment well without diarrhea, shortness of breath, nausea, vomiting, fever, or chills. Has no trouble with his ADLs and his energy remains good. Notes his blood pressure is usually close to normal at home, but it get high whenever he gets here. He does complain of a rash around his left groin which he has had for a couple of months for which he was prescribed some sort of cream but has run out. |2017-11-06:	He presents today for C3D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient states that he's tolerating this treatment well without rash, shortness of breath, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea. He notes that his left groin rash has improved with the use of an anti-fungal cream, and he has been keeping a log of his blood pressures at home. He denies mouth pain and is eating well--weight remains stable. He continues to walk daily, sometimes by himself and sometimes with the dogs. He does have bilateral knee pain from his arthritis which is improved with the use of topical menthol patches. He does note constipation for the last few days for which his PCP prescribed suppositories. He does note that he had frequent urination during the night--had a recent cysto with Dr Malvar and may need a TURP. |2017-11-28:	He presents today for C4D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient states that he's had no side effects from this treatment. He has had continued problems with constipation and hemorrhoids, and he states he has a upcoming "procedure" to further explore the issue. He also notes a cold which started yesterday--has coughing, sore throat, and a runny nose but he denies fever or chills. Groin rash continues to improve with his anti-fungal cream. He notes that his arthritic knees always hurt more with the cold weather--has been using ibuprofen 600mg as needed but still trying to walk every day. Eating well without nausea, vomiting, or mouth pain. |2018-01-08:	He presents today for C6D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient states that he feels overall fine. He continues to have trouble with his knees due to arthritis--takes ibuprofen when it gets really bad. Appetite is good and he is eating well--no trouble chewing or swallowing. He has been given rectal suppositories to use for his hemorrhoids--he is to follow up with his doctor in three weeks for discussion of possible hemorrhoidectomy. Rash on his groin has now resolved. Energy is good--walks outside when the weather is nice enough. Denies nausea, vomiting, sob, chest pain, fever, chills, or new rash. |2018-01-30:	He presents today for C7D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient continues to tolerate his treatment well. Good appetite--eating well without trouble chewing or swallowing. Walking outside daily when it's warm enough. Bilateral knees still hurt from arthritis but he tries not to take ibuprofen unless it gets really bad. He saw ENT today--to follow up with 3 months. Still using rectal suppositories for his hemorrhoids which are improving, he thinks--to follow up with his doctor in another month to decide whether or not to do surgery. |2018-02-20:	He presents today for C8D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. He notes he is still struggling with his stools/hemorrhoids--to follow up with his GI doc on 2/26/18 to decide on surgical intervention. Energy has been a little down lately--has not been walking outside as much due to the snowy weather--trying to walk around the house and up and down the stairs for exercise. Appetite is good--eating well. |2018-02-26:	He notes he is still struggling with his stools/hemorrhoids----to follow up with his GI doc on 2/26/18 to decide on surgical intervention. |2018-04-03:	Then developed recurrent HNSCC upper lip and resection with Dr. Blair 7/3/2017, then CIS on biopsy/tooth 8/31/2017. He presents today for Cycle 10 D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. Patient notes that he's tolerating treatment well without rash, changes in vision, diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, or muscle aches. He has good appetite and reasonable energy--tries to walk outside when the weather is nice. Complains of bilateral knee pain due to arthritis (R>L) for which he takes ibuprofen occasionally--interested in other treatments. Had high blood pressure reading in clinic but has been keeping a daily log for the last month--systolic ranges from 128-150 and diastolic from 71-86 (patient notes PCP does not want to adjust his bp meds as his readings are pretty good at home). Notes he is not getting a hemorrhoidectomy after all--hemorrhoids have improved significantly. |2018-04-24:	He presents today for Cycle 11 D1 of the PATHWay study for chemoprevention/adjvuant to prevent recurrences. narrative: 2012-10-20:	unspecified site 10/20/2012. |2012-10-20:	S/P laryngectomy 10/20/2012 |2013-11-22:	not elsewhere classified 11/22/2013. |2013-12-18:	EBUS/TBNA was performed on 12/18/13. |2014-01-03:	Judith McCarthy is a 78Yrs female with 50 pack year history of smoking and history of laryngeal cancer treated in 2008 with chemotherapy and radiation therapy followed by salvage laryngectomy. She was undergoing her yearly surveillance with Dr. Stenson, CT scan 5 years s/p laryngectomy, and was found to have RLL lung mass and mediastinal adenopathy, not present a year prior. Subsequent PET scan was positive in the RLL, right hilum and subcarinal nodes. EBUS/TBNA was performed on 12/18/13, and pathology of RLL and level 7 demonstrated NSCLC/keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. RLL biopsy demonstrated squamous cell carcinoma, subcarinal nodes positive and left sided nodes non diagnostic on pathology but noted to be small on EBUS. In view of N2 disease, patient has now been referred to medical oncology for presumptive stage IIIA lung cancer (T2aN2Mx). She has baseline dyspnea which is unchanged. She has no cough, no hemoptysis. Her weight is stable and she has no fevers. She denies other systemic or cardiopulmonary symptoms. She states that she can walk 4 blocks before needing a rest. She does have moderate arthritis in the bilateral hands. She denies neuropathy. She is able to perform all her activities of daily living. She goes to church regularly, goes to bingo four times a week, continues to drive, and does her cooking, bathing, dressing, cleaning, laundry, and shopping without difficulty. She lives independently and has a son very involved in her care. With respect to her prior larynx cancer, she was treated at Munster Community Hospital. Her son states that chemoradiation was fairly tough  and she did require a feeding tube temporarily. Patient states that she prefers to avoid surgery for her lung cancer. She states that if she requires chemotherapy and radiation, she would prefer a location closer to home and potentially Munster Hospital again. Patient Active Problem List    Diagnosis Date Noted    Squamous cell lung cancer     Other diseases of lung, not elsewhere classified 11/22/2013    Malignant neoplasm of larynx, unspecified site 10/20/2012    S/P laryngectomy 10/20/2012 |

narrative: 2008-03-01:	3/2008 R lateral tongue surgery at University of Miami. |2009-04-03:	12/08 -- Glossectomy UCH then had TFHX completed 4/3/09. |2011-08-23:	8/23/11 -- Pt comes to clinic feel well. |2012-02-21:	2/21/12 -- Pt doing well. |2012-08-21:	Anita M Lahey is a 54Yrs female here for follow-up of Tongue SCC  3/2008 R lateral tongue surgery at University of Miami  Recurrence 8/08 then had surgery f/b radiation alone at University of Miami. 12/08 - Glossectomy UCH then had TFHX completed 4/3/09  8/23/11 - Pt comes to clinic feel well, mainly using G tube, some sm sips water. Wt stable. Very active with some fatigue. CT demonstrates NED, scans reviewed with pt. Labs wnl but demonstrate some dehydration will increase water intake. Also TSH pending. Will plan to f/u in 6 mos with CT and labs./VV  2/21/12 - Pt doing well, still mainly g-tube some sips water. Continues to have xerostomia. Gtube replaced. CT reviewed, NED. Labs stable, continues to be anemic but stable c/w thallesemia minor. RTC 6 mos with CT and labs./VV  . Todays patient complaints are:  Overall doing well,  G-Tube only, wt stable. Some small sips water. |2013-02-25:	Increased coughing with occ bleeding and chronic sinusitis, zpak recently given with some resolution. |2013-09-12:	*** |2013-09-13:	Todays patient complaints are:  Overall doing well,    Had a flare up of sores abscesses/cellulitis  on neck treated with antiobiotics and I&D, had diarrhea on abx, this has now all resolved now off of ciprofloxacin. G-Tube only, wt stable. |2014-07-18:	Anita M Lahey is a 56Yrs female here for follow-up of Tongue SCC  3/2008 R lateral tongue surgery at University of Miami  Recurrence 8/08 then had surgery f/b radiation alone at University of Miami. Todays patient complaints are:  Overall doing well,    Little fatigue, stagle. Had a flare up of sores  on neck treated with silvadine which helps. |2015-11-03:	Anita M Lahey is a 57Yrs female here for follow-up of Tongue SCC  3/2008 R lateral tongue surgery at University of Miami  Recurrence 8/08 then had surgery f/b radiation alone at University of Miami. Todays patient complaints are:  Overall doing well,    Having some issues with loose teeth/pins and trismus  Still PEG dependant, some sips of liquids. |

Today she reports she is doing much better. Reports mild frontal headache about 2x per week (lasting <1hr) relieved without medication. -Feels she is more sensitive to sounds now. Notes that everything sounds louder. -Occasionally feels short of breath. Denies chest pain, increased work of breathing, fevers/chills, cough. -Continues to report diarrhea 4-5 BM per day with some abdominal cramping. Followed by her PCP who has been adjusting her medications. Denies n/v. Weight has remained stable and she has stayed hydrated. -Tolerating regular diet without any difficulties.
