Cough continues to be productive, but sputum is now clear instead of yellow/green. Denies fevers/chills. States that her energy has been very low. Has also felt depressed. Tachycardic to 110s with bps 100s/70s. She was placed on a NRB with improvement in sats, startd on broad spectrum Abx and received 1 dose of narcan. She immediately regained her mental status and c/o R sided chest pain similar to before and SOB. C/o cough with green sputum for last week, unsure if having f/c or SOB at home    SIRS: concern for sepsis given tachycardia, leukocytosis and fever 38.2. Sources include urine, lungs  - follow up urine and blood cultures and appropriately narrow Abx  - cont Abx as above, would d/c bactrim (for previous UTI)  - send sputum culture, consider RVP, send WBC diffferential  - agree 2L IVF bolus, would monitor urine output, mental status and titrate fluids appropriately    Query question: Was SIRS/Sepsis present on admission? No, the condition was not present on admission and it developed during the inpatient stay. Anisha Chandiramani, M.D. Internal Medicine, PGY-1  Pager 3137 |

narrative: 2009-11-27:	1) He completed initially FHX on 11/27/09. |2009-11-27:	FHX 11/27/09. |2011-03-29:	Advised to have close f/u with ENT for surveillance as hyperbaric O2 may increase cancer growth on 3/29/11. |2011-03-29:	Advised to have close f/u with ENT for surveillance as hyperbaric O2 may increase cancer growth.-- VV 3/29/11. |2011-08-02:	CT from 08/02/11 with no evidence of disease. |2011-08-09:	08/09/11. |2011-12-06:	12/6/11 --. |2012-03-27:	3/27/12 --. |2012-08-13:	Ronald Hass is a 78Yrs male here for follow-up of Multifocal oral tongue SCC s/p FHX 11/27/09, Failed EPOC trial (erlotinib vs placebo) multiple recurrences/field cancerization with multiple resections. Last positive resection 10/10. Currently having teeth extractions and hyperbaric O2. Advised to have close f/u with ENT for surveillance as hyperbaric O2 may increase cancer growth.- VV 3/29/11  08/09/11, seen by Dr Nwizu/Villaflor. Patient recently got tooth extraction. Doing well. F/U ENT in 1 mos. RTC 4 mos with CT and labs./VV/TN  12/6/11 -  Pt doing well, tol PO inc solids, wt stable. No dysphagia and odynophagia. Continues to have xerostomia. Pt to discuss shingles vaccine with pcp. Will increase synthroid to 88 on m-->f and 100 on sat/sun. Reck tsh 4-6 weeks. reinstructed on neck exercises. RTC 4 mos with CT and labs./VV  3/27/12 -  Pt had recent surgery X3 to clear margins, some aspiration per recent OPM following surgery pt having problems with swallowing pills. Recommend PEG placement, family and pt would like to wait 1-2 weeks. CT reviewed I am concerned with R tongue nodule, will review with Portugal in tumor board. Will have get speech therapy to work with pt for swallowing. Labs pending. RTC 1 week with Amy Butler, if wt not increasing will PEG.. narrative: 2018-03-01:	3/2018: Began to develop left sided throat pain with pain on swallowing. |2018-04-12:	4/12/2018: Presented to ENT who saw an enlarged. |2018-04-19:	4/19/2018: CT Neck with Contrast showed significant asymmetric enlargement and uniform moderate enhancement of the left Palatine tonsil (3.3 x 2.8 x 3.7 cm). |2018-04-19:	4/19/2018: CT Neck with Contrast showed significant asymmetric enlargement. |2018-04-30:	4/30/2018:. |2018-04-30:	Stephen Shin is a 40Yrs male with no significant medical history with a  newly diagnosed P16+ left tonsillar cancer which appears to be cT2N0 currently who presents for a second opinion. Oncologic history is as below. Patient has pain when swallowing. Methylprednisolone  and ibuprofen helps with pain when swallowing and sore throat. He feels his voice is more hoarse. His appetite is mildly decreased and some mild weight loss of several pounds. Oncological History:  3/2018: Began to develop left sided throat pain with pain on swallowing. Patient had worsening difficulty in opening his mouth. 4/12/2018: Presented to ENT who saw an enlarged, firm tonsil with tenderness and erythema. narrative: 2010-02-03:	She was taken to the OR on 2/3/10 where she received both a ventral tongue biopsy. |2010-03-01:	Marlene Zimmermann is a 77Yrs female with h/o T1a lung adenocarcinoma in 3/2010 . |2010-03-25:	3/25/2010 underwent R lower lobectomy for T1aN0M0 Stg IA lung adenocarcinoma. |2010-03-25:	on 3/25/10 she was taken back to the OR for a completion lobectomy which was without residual tumor; LN 7 and 4R were negative for malignancy. |2010-05-19:	She received a re--excision and neck dissection of the floor of mouth squamous cell carcinoma on 5/19/10. |2010-06-30:	She received two additional re--excisions on 6/30/10 and 11/5/10. |2010-11-05:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2013-06-11:	6/11/2013 PET showed moderate uptake in the lingular lesion (SUV max 4). |2013-06-17:	6/17/13 biopsy of the ligula nodule showed some atypical glands. |2013-09-01:	9/2013 CT showed mild increase in size of lingula nodule. |2014-03-01:	3/2014 the lingular lesion was found to have increased in size from 19x8mm to 12x18 mm. |2014-03-04:	In 2014 she was noted on surveillance CT imaging 3/4/14 to have a lesion at the periphery of the left lingula. |2014-03-12:	CT guided needle biopsy 3/12/14 demonstrated well differentiated adenocarcinoma (lepidic and acinar patterns). |2014-03-19:	3/19/14 presented in multidisciplinary conference. |2014-03-19:	Marlene Zimmermann is a 77Yrs female with h/o T1a lung adenocarcinoma in 3/2010 s/p R lower lobectomy, now presenting with adenocarcinoma of lingula. 3/25/2010 underwent R lower lobectomy for T1aN0M0 Stg IA lung adenocarcinoma  In 2012, surveillance scans showed RUL and lingular nodules. These were followed over time, and remained relatively stable. 6/11/2013 PET showed moderate uptake in the lingular lesion (SUV max 4), which was new from prior. 6/17/13 biopsy of the ligula nodule showed some atypical glands, but no definitive malignancy. Continued surveillance. IR biopsy of the lesion revealed well-differentiated adenocarcinoma. The R lung nodule has remained unchanged. Recommended SBRT. Ms Zimmermann states that she's feeling relatively well. She denies any cough or shortness of breath at rest, though she does get some stable dyspnea on walking up stairs. She is able to walk 10-15 mins at a brisk pace on a treadmill. Energy level is good. Appetite is good, no weight loss. No fevers, chills, night sweats. She remains relatively active, lives alone, very independent. |2014-03-26:	PET/CT 3/26/14 was positive at the lingular nodule (SUV 6.2). |2014-04-07:	EBUS was performed 4/7/14. |2016-11-02:	CT Chest/Upper Abdomen 11/2/16 demonstrated multiple bilateral pulmonary nodules and micronodules. |2016-11-09:	Marlene Zimmermann is a 80Yrs female with NSCLC. The patient presents to the thoracic medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. The patient initially presented in 2010 with a ventral tongue mass as well as a right lower lobe nodule. She was taken to the OR on 2/3/10 where she received both a ventral tongue biopsy, a floor of mouth excision, and a right lower lobe wedge biopsy. Pathology from the floor of mouth lesion demonstrated in-situ and superficially invasive squamous cell carcinoma with positive margins; T1NX. The right lower lobe nodule demonstrated adenocarcinoma, 1.0x0.9x0.9cm, pT1NX, with involved margins. For her NSCLC, on 3/25/10 she was taken back to the OR for a completion lobectomy which was without residual tumor; LN 7 and 4R were negative for malignancy. She received a re-excision and neck dissection of the floor of mouth squamous cell carcinoma on 5/19/10. All LN were negative, though the floor of mouth lesion demonstrated in-situ squamous cell carcinoma extending to inked (new) margin. She received two additional re-excisions on 6/30/10 and 11/5/10, both of which demonstrated in-situ and infiltrating squamous carcinoma. In 2014 she was noted on surveillance CT imaging 3/4/14 to have a lesion at the periphery of the left lingula, which was progressively enlarging (12x18mm). EBUS was performed 4/7/14, which demonstrated negative 11L, 11R, 4R lymph nodes. She was not  a surgical candidate given poor PFTs (FEV1 1.34 L (83% pred), FVC 1.92 L (69% pred), DLCO 75%) and medical comorbidities including age, HTN, and COPD. She ultimately underwent definitive SBRT to 50 Gy in 5 fractions to the left lingular lesion. For example, a lingular lesion increased from 5 to 9mm, a RUL lesion 6x7mm from 4x6mm. The patient was referred to oncology for further evaluation. The patient reports she has some fatigue and chronic back pain, though all of these are stable from previously. She goes to the YMCA three times per week for exercise on the recumbent bike, treadmill, and water walk. She goes to lunch regularly with her friends. She does all the cooking and cleaning in her home. She does have chronic back pain for which she takes dilaudid 2mg PO daily. She denies weight loss, fatigue, cough, hemoptysis. She reports chronic dyspnea with exertion though this does not seem to limit her activities significantly. She also has neuropathy for which she takes lyrica. Patient Active Problem List   Diagnosis    Cancer of floor of mouth    Peripheral vascular disease    Lung nodule    Lesion of mouth    Lung cancer    History of endometrial cancer    History of skin cancer    Extremity atherosclerosis with intermittent claudication    Hypothyroidism    History of oral cancer    History of lung cancer    Emphysema/COPD    Neuropathy |2017-03-01:	Interval History:  No new complaints. Has chronic SOB but no worsening beyond baseline. Can walk on treadmill for 10 minutes a day. Lives alone, independent with ADLs/IADLs. No chest pain, nausea, fevers, chills, weight loss, or appetite changes. She has chronic neuropathy in her feet which is controlled with lyrica and does not interfere with balance or walking. She has chronic back pain for which she takes once daily dilaudid. Oncologic History:   The patient initially presented in 2010 with a ventral tongue mass as well as a right lower lobe nodule. She was not a surgical candidate given poor PFTs (FEV1 1.34 L (83% pred), FVC 1.92 L (69% pred), DLCO 75%) and medical comorbidities including age, HTN, and COPD. narrative: 2012-05-09:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic HNSCC currently receiving temsirolimus/cetuximab as part of a clinical trial (UCCC# 10-428). He is tolerating the treatment well and saw a dermatologist for management of nail/fingure abnormalities likely secondary to the treatment. CT scan show evidence of response to treatment. |2012-06-11:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs male here for follow-up of his metastatic HNSCC. He completed treatment with carbo/pemetrexed/cetuximab followed by cetuximab and then had disease progression (Lilly trial), then had progressive disease and now is on the combination of temsirolimus/cetuximab. His recent CT scan shows a PR with shrinkage of his lung nodule. He is feeling well and tolerating treatment well. His finger and toe nail lesions are healing with topical antibiotics as prescribed by dermatology. He would like to know whether the trach can be removed and he can eat by mouth. His G-Tube is working well. |2012-07-03:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic HNSCC, currently on temsirolimus/cetuximab study (combination arm). His recent CT scan confirms ~50% tumor shrinkage. He continues to feel well. NPO after recent swallowing study confirmed that he cannot eat food po and per ENT the tracheostomy should stay in place. |2012-07-10:	Still has finger/nail problems, but stable with application of topical antibiotics. |2012-07-20:	/  HPI hyperglycemia  The history is provided by the patient. Using topical antibiotics. |2012-12-14:	Had CT scans 12/14/12. |2012-12-18:	Had CT scans 12/14/12    Tolerating treatment well. |2013-01-16:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic HNSCC, previously treated on carbo/pemetrexed/cetuximab trial, then responded totemsirolimus/cetuximab study (combination arm) (initial response then prolonged stable disease but most recent CT scan with PD). Here to discuss treatment options. Facial swelling and fingernail problems/paronychia healing since discontinuing temsirolimus. Energy improving. He is here with one of his brothers, who recently moved here from California. Mr. Reynolds would like to leave the nursing home and move in with him. |2013-02-10:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs man with HNC metastatic to lungs. He is currently on temsirolimus/cetuximab study (combination arm), here for C11D1. H e continues to tolerate treatment and is largely asymptomatic. He Tolerates GTube Feeds, but is inquiring about eating po. No n/v/d. Fingernails continue to be affected by treatment. |2013-02-11:	He is currently on temsirolimus/cetuximab study (combination arm), here for C11D8. He Tolerates GTube Feeds well  His skin/nail changes are stable with topical treatments. |2013-02-26:	Here to discuss new treatment options. Recovering well, and hand/skin lesions are healing since off temsirolimus. Facial swelling also improving. Overall doing very well. He is here with nursing home representative. |2013-04-02:	Osborn Reynolds is a 72Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic HNSCC, previously treated on carbo/pemetrexed/cetuximab trial with prolonged response then SD. Subsequently treated on temsirolimus/cetuximab study (combination arm) (initial response then prolonged stable disease again). Doing very well now. |2013-06-18:	Today he continues to feel well, and denies any symptoms. He has not had a CT scan as was originally intended. |2013-07-12:	Most recent CT scans 7/12/2013 show PD with all disease being in the chest. |2013-08-20:	Screening for PDL1 expression was negative. He continues to feel well, and remains asymptomatic. |2013-08-27:	We discussed an alternative clinical trial using BKM120 a PI3K inhibitor in combination with cetuximab. narrative: 2014-04-01:	He initially noticed right neck mass (April 2014) and was subsequently noted to have swelling in right tonsil (Sept 2014). |2014-09-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-10-22:	Underwent scope exam on 10/22/14 which revealed right tonsillar enlargement without extension to tongue base. |2014-10-27:	CT neck on 10/27/14 revealed enhancement of the right tonsil which measures approximately 2.7 cm. |2014-10-31:	Underwent flow cytometric analysis of right sided LN on 10/31/2014. |2014-11-03:	Underwent biopsy of right tonsil on 11/3/2014. |2014-11-11:	Roy Hartwig is a 73Yrs male with HPV positive cT2N1 right tonsil squamous cell carcinoma with ipsilateral LN involvement. Was placed on keflex x 10 days without resolution. Neck swelling would "come and go" but never completely resolved. Non-tender. Denied difficulty swallowing, no hoarseness. No weight loss. Has had occasional hemoptysis, though is also on coumadin for atrial fibrillation. There was cystic enhancement of a jugulodigastric LN on the right measuring 1.9 cm. No other adenopathy seen. Overall concerning for malignant process. No monoclonal B lymphocyte population. No aberrant T lymphocyte phenotype. Results revealed invasive, poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma with focal keratinization. Tumor cells are strongly positive for p16. Was able to come off anticoagulation for procedure. He presents to our medical oncology clinic to discuss further work-up and recommendations for treatment. Has not had PET scan yet. No fevers, chills, sweats. Notes mild sensitivity and awareness of swallowing, but largely asymptomatic. Continues to have good energy and appetite. Denies cardiopulmonary symptoms. Denies GI symptoms. Denies neuropathy. Has history of cardiac ablations in the past for symptomatic atrial fibrillation, but not an issue anymore. Does have a pacemaker. Has been on coumadin without bleeding complications. Notes that he was previously in the Navy around the time of the Bay of Pigs. Functionally active and works on a farm, takes care of 22 horses. Former 5-7 pack year history of tobacco in his 20s, but has quit since then. PS 0. Today is C1D15. He feels right neck mass has significantly decreased (about 60%) since starting chemotherapy. He presents to clinic with ANC 740, platelets 63,000 and a temp of 100.0 in his left ear. Pt reports chills and states his temp was 100.6 last night. Over the past 2 days he has notes worsening sore throat, productive cough, myalgias, low energy, and no appetite. He denies rash, nasal congestion, abdominal pain, n/v/d/c, or dysuria. He  notes some bloody rhinorrhea, but denies epistaxis, headache, melena, hematochezia, or hematuria. ECOG PS 0. Pt now presents for follow up. On 12/10/14, C1D15 of induction chemo was held due to neutropenia. Pt also presented with chills, max temp of 100.6 the night before, productive cough, and sore throat. He was sent to the ER for further workup and treatment. Received 2g of IV cefepime. Had no fevers in the ER, and chest x-ray, blood cultures, U/A, and RVP all negative so pt was discharged home with 7 day course of Augmentin and Levofloxacin. Today he reports he is feeling much better. He has been taking his oral antibiotics as instructed and will receive his 3rd dose of neupogen in clinic today. Reports night sweats on 12/10, but denies any fevers, chills, or night sweats since. Productive cough and sore throat have significantly improved. Still notes clear/grey colored sputum and mild shortness of breath at times. Myalgias have resolved, but energy remains low. Reports loose stools (about 3x/day) over the past couple of days. States BMs are still somewhat formed, just softer. Denies abdominal cramping or liquid stools. He  feels right neck mass has significantly decreased in size (about 60%) since starting chemotherapy and is hoping he will be able to receive his chemotherapy next week. C1D15 dose missed due to neutropenia. C2D1 today, dose reduced for carboplatin and abraxane by 25% due to previous neutropenia per protocol. Last week (C1D15) the patient presented with febrile neutropenia, and an infectious work up at the ER was negative. He was discharged from the ER with a 7-day course of antibiotics. He denies further febrile episodes. C1D15 abraxane was skipped. The patient reports feeling overall well. The 2 R neck LNs that he described 2 weeks ago have regressed. He denies throat pain and dysphagia, and reports good appetite and adequate oral intake. The rest of the review of systems is unremarkable. No new issues  Continues with DOE and now more fatigue |2014-07-21:	HPI    Mr. Reckamp was first diagnosed with T3N2b squamous cell carcinoma of the right tonsil 2010. He underwent induction chemotherapy then concurrent chemoradiation (10-069) completed on 1/31/11. He was recently diagnosed with squamous cell carcinoma in left mainstem bronchus and mediastinal lymphadenopathy concerning for recurrence of HCN vs new primary lung cancer. This mass was biopsied and sent to FoundationOne for somatic tumor testing and this identified several abnormalities one of which was a truncating BRCA1 mutation. He has a strong family history of breast and ovarian cancer and thus there was concern re: germline nature of this variant. Of note, his sister who had both breast and ovarian cancer had at one point been tested and also carries a BRCA1 or BRCA2 mutation (report and details not available to the family yet at this time). He is currently undergoing radiation therapy for his current cancer (still debate per patient if was recurrence of H&N cancer or new primary). He denies personal history of other cancers. Had colonoscopy in 2010 that was normal. Had screening PSAs in the past without abnormalities    Mr. Reckamp came to visit today with 8 members of his family to discuss  this family history and role of genetic testing to aid in cancer prevention for the family. All grew up on a farm and had extensive sun exposure and sun burns (german/swedish ancestry)    ONC History   9/2010: He presented with a sore throat and right neck fullness. Exam revealed right neck LAD and enlargement/induration of the right tonsil. Biopsy of right neck LAD revealed metastatic SCCa. Pathology revealed invasive SCCa in the R tonsil (+ LVI) and focus of CIS in the L tonsil. Immunostaining for p16 was positive. He was staged T2N2b. 10/2010-1/2011: He underwent induction chemotherapy with cisplatin/paclitaxel followed by concurrent chemoradiation with cetuximab-FHX to a cumulative dose of 74 Gy in 1.5 Gy BID fractions. On EPIC trial. He was seen in routine follow-up by Drs. Haraf, Portugal, Cohen, and De Souza. There was however new subcarinal lymphadenopathy measuring up to 13-mm and new left interlobar lymphadenopathy. There was interval progression of peribronchial nodules in size and number, now with extrinsic compression of a subsegmental airway in the LLL, possibly representing endovascular or early lymphangitic metastatic disease. Nodular mucosa was found in the left mainstem bronchus. Three small non-obstructing nodules were found in the left lower lobe. There was mediastinal (subcarinal) LAD. LLL and left mainstem endobronchial biopsies were positive for poorly differentiated SCCa. Level 7 LN TBNA was positive for metastatic SCCa. There  was increased narrowing of the proximal left lower lobe bronchi from external compression by the tumor. A more focal left lung base opacity with abnormal increased SUV activity was new compared to recent previous chest CT, possibly representing contiguous tumor spread or infection. There was right paratracheal, subcarinal and left hilar lymphadenopathy with abnormal increased FDG activity and increase in size from previous chest CT exam indicating metastatic lymph node spread. narrative: 2011-07-22:	John Keeler is a 55Yrs male here for follow--up of T4N2B R tongue SCC completed induction on mtor study 10/5/11IRB 10069 completed CFHX 7/22/11. |2011-10-04:	-- 10/04/11: Seen by Dr Nwizu/Villaflor. |2012-01-01:	Pt given CDDP/Tax/re--RT--BID for hi risk disease completed 1/2012. |2012-04-03:	4/3/12 -- Pt doing well clinically. |2012-05-01:	5/2012 -- Contacted by OSH physician. |2012-05-24:	John Keeler is a 55Yrs male here for follow-up of T4N2B R tongue SCC completed induction on mtor study 10/5/11IRB 10069 completed CFHX 7/22/11. Patient with right cervical lymphadenopathy had a PET scan that revealed contralateral LAD with uptake and possible uptake in L apex, L neck. FNA contralateral LN came back as SCC, will go for resection with Dr Blair   - 10/04/11: Seen by Dr Nwizu/Villaflor. Patient underwent bilateral lymph node dissection, with path showing Right oral base of tongue; biopsy: - Superficial fragments of hyperplastic squamous mucosa, no tumor present. B. Right neck; dissection: Metastatic keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in one of three Level II lymph nodes (1/3). The largest tumor focus measures 2.5 cm. - Extranodal extension present. - Metastatic keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma in three of twelve Level III lymph nodes (3/12). - The largest tumor focus measures 0.5 cm. No extranodal extension present. C. Left neck; modified radical dissection- Two Level II lymph nodes, no tumor present (0/2). - Metastatic keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma (5.8 cm) involving soft tissue and skeletal muscle of Level III and Level IV   Pt discussed at conference, general consensus was that he had been completely resected, continue with surveillance. Pt however at a high risk of recurrence, also discussed that he has susp pulm nodule, will re-discuss him at conference again. Repeat CT scan in 2 months. Pt given CDDP/Tax/re-RT-BID for hi risk disease completed 1/2012. 4/3/12 - Pt doing well clinically, tol po, softs mainly/and liquids. Prelim review of PET shows activity in R hilum, will review in tumor board, pt will require a CT within next 4-6 weeks possible sooner depending on Tumor board review today, Traci will contact. RTC 4-6 weeks with CT and labs. Pt comes to clinic today with c/o *** |2012-07-02:	5/2012 - Contacted by OSH physician, pt with widely metastatic disease  with pulm mets and c/o pain. Pt did not return to clinic as advised, missed 2 previous appt. |
Dx_: ['SCC', 'no tumor', 'squamous cell carcinoma', 'Metastatic keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma']

narrative: 2012-09-19:	William Goncher is a 60Yrs male here for follow-up of T3 N0 larynx cancer treated on FHX who finished treatment in December 2011. Shortly thereafter he developed recurrence of disease, which was addressed by a salvage laryngectomy/neck dissection in April 2012 by Dr. Portugal. Of note, he had positive nodes at that time. Mr. Goncher was closely followed and his most recent CT showed disease recurrence locally in his neck. We ordered a PET-CT which confirmed this recurrence in addition to mediastinal disease. Mr. Gooncher is doing symptom wise, with good energy, no pain. Pt is currently receiving palliative chemo with carbo/5-FU/cetux, here for C5D8. Onc history:  Mr. Goncher initially presented with T3 N0 SCC larynx s/p FHX completed January 2012. Shortly thereafter developed recurrence of disease, s/p salvage laryngectomy/neck dissection with positive nodes 4/2012 with Dr. Portugal. CT scan 5/2012 revealed interval progression of L vocal cord mass with extension to supraglottis and infraglottis. S/p laryngectomy 5/2012     Pt had scans recently that showed stable disease. He feels well and relieved with scan results. Pt continues to have rash but denies pruritus, fever or pain. Appeitte stable, denies dysphagia or odynophagia. No n/v/d/c/f/c or mouth sores. Shortly after, he developed recurrence and underwent salvage laryngectomy/neck dissection with positive nodes in 5/2012 with Dr. Portugal. He has had recurrent metastatic disease and recently completed 5 cycles of palliative chemo with carboplatin, 5-FU, and cetuximab. Today, pt reports feeling well overall. He continues to have rash as a side effect from the chemotherapy, but denies pruritis or pain. He uses hydrocortisone cream for the rash. His appetite has been good and weight is stable. He denies dysphagia or sores in the mouth. Denies fevers, night sweats, n/v, diarrhea. |2013-01-28:	Pt is currently receiving palliative chemo with carbo/5-FU/cetux, here for C6D15. Had CRT in 10-11/2005 for tonsil cancer (done at ProVena/St. Mary's,  Bourbonnais). 6/2011 tongue cancer, found to have lung nodule (Dr. Warren at Rush, LN between lung and esophagus)  Started platinum, pemetrexed, cetuximab as part of clinical trial at UChicago  Followed by maintenance cetuximab locally (at Rush/Riverside Oncology with Dr. Veerapaneni) until  Sept 1, 2013, then noted to have progressive disease. Now returns here to evaluate for additional therapy. Overall feeling well, but notes mild swallowing problems. Good energy.l |2013-11-05:	10/22/13 came back here to evaluate for additional therapy - plan for re-irradiation since tumor relatively  localized and stable (saw Dr. Haraf). Reports marked worsening of swallowing - swallowing is like forcing food through "hole size of a pencil". Concerned about swallowing and speech, wants to start treatment. Concerned about nutrition. Got dehydraded and had to go to ER. |2013-11-22:	-- Pt was admitted to OSH 11/22/13 for febrile neutropenia and dc'd home 11/25. |2013-11-22:	Pt was admitted to OSH 11/22/13 for febrile neutropenia and dc'd home 11/25. |2013-12-13:	Richard A Dupuis is a 58Yrs male here for follow-up of recurrent tongue HNSCC. He is enrolled in IRB 121554, s/p induction phase. Pt was given neupogen x3d and abx. No further fever. Pt feeling well at present time. Has no c/o. |2013-12-31:	He is enrolled in IRB 121554 (Abraxane induction plus re-irradiation. Had PD on induction, now plan for hypofractionation. Eating well. Swallowing ok with small bites, and ample water supplementation. Had PD on induction and received hypofractionated RT per protocol (1/2/2014 - 1/29/2014). Pt here for 4w f/u. C/o solid-dysphagia and mild odynophagia. Is not taking analgesics. PO intake and weight stable. |2014-04-28:	04/28/14 1343. |2014-04-28:	Pt here for 12w f/u. Mainly complain of increasing post-nasal drip and cough for the past week. A week or so later she developed worsening upper airway symptoms including neck swelling and fever postoperatively. She needed a brief period of intubation and mechanical ventilation for airway protection. She did not require tracheostomy. She also had MR Coag-Neg Staph bacteremia unsure if from soft tissue source as she had epiglottitis radiographically. She did require steroids. She completed 5 days of IV vancomycin and was transition to oral clindamycin and ciproflacin but due to pill size she administers these through her G-tube and will finish a 10-day course next week (7/20/12) per ID recommendations. Since hospitalization, she feels better and is at 80% baseline. She reports improving fatigue. She eats well and takes only 2 cans per G tube and wondering when it can be removed. Her dysgeusia is improving and xerostomia not worse. She denies dyspnea. She is completing a steroid taper upon review. |2012-07-20:	She completed 5 days of IV vancomycin and was transition to oral clindamycin and ciproflacin but due to pill size she administers these through her G--tube and will finish a 10--day course next week (7/20/12) per ID recommendations. |2012-07-27:	Judith Brookens is a 66Yrs female here for follow-up of T1 N2c SCC uvula s/p 5/5 TFHX 5/11/12 . Recovering from epiglottitis earlier in June requiring hospitalization. Pt is now off all antibiotics and steroids. Pt using 2 cans 2Cal in G tube but eating well by mouth and taking virtually all meds by mouth without swallowing difficulty or odynophagia. Per her and her husband, she is able to take PO supplements such as Ensure/Boost and protein smoothies without difficulty (up to 2/day). Reports some thick secretions but able to clear. Denies worsening breathing. Appetite and energy improved. Has lost weight, however, on review. |2012-08-11:	She returns today because of irritative voiding symptoms. She reports having increased urinary frequency for past 1-2 days and now reports some irritation but no pain on urination, hematuria, or fevers/chills or abdominal pain. Despite our prior encounter's exhortations, she is still using 2 cans 2cal through her Gtube though is able to reportedly swallow without difficulty. Her weight has remained essentially stable since last visit. She reports some tongue burning sensation and has been off gabapentin for a few months. She has run out of her topical meds and Dilaudid for several weeks but has not notified us or the RN staff. |2012-08-17:	Today was her scheduled follow-up. She was last seen a week ago for dysuria with presumptive UTI, treated with Cipro x3 days. Final Urine cx showed no predominant organism. Her irritative voiding sx have resolved. She reports ongoing pain/discofmort of tongue, especially eating cold foods. She is using up to 3 cans 2Cal per G tube/day. She gets at least 2 cans Boost or Ensure per mouth daily but does not like the taste. She has been using viscous lidocaine and Dilaudid 2 mg prior to meals but states only gets about 10 min. Of relief prior to meals. She has maintained weight over the last few weeks. She denies emesis or diarrhea. She denies odynopahgia or dysphagia. She tried to fill rx for Magic or Grade I mouthwash but stated co-pay was too much. |2012-09-14:	Since her last visit, she reports ongoing oral/tongue discomfort dysesthesias. Assessment:  66Yrs male with HNSCC s/p LND and RT 1996, new primary  2011 with T3N1 now s/p resection and flap --> FHX completed 6/6 FHX 3/2/12 with RT completed 3/7/12. - Off, took for 6 months. Hemoptysis  Bronch Sept 16 did not identified source. Left Lung Abnormalities: Mucous, plugging the airway, was found in the   superior segment of the left lower lobe (B6). The mucous was copious,   clear, tenacious and thick. The underlying mucosa is normal. Suctioning   was performed and the airway was cleared. Right Lung Abnormalities: Old blood was found in the bronchus   intermedius and in the medial basal segment of the right lower lobe   (B7). The bleeding site was not identified. We reviewed with Dr. Frye   during the procedure. With careful suctioning all blood in the BI and B7   was removed completely. No underlying pathology was noted, no lesions,   and no recurrence or fresh bleeding was noted in any airway. The   procedure was terminated at that time. Impression:      - Hemoptysis with abnormal CXR   - A mucous plug was found in the superior segment of   the left lower lobe (B6). - Blood was present in the bronchus intermedius and in   the medial basal segment of the right lower lobe (B7). - Suctioning was performed. Anemia  Responded well to transfusion. No source of bleeding found, as above. Off xarelto. Reports L heel burning and paresthesias overnight, none now. Anorexia persists, however he continues to drink shakes and eat without difficulty. |2013-11-20:	Patient had reported hairline fracture with X-ray of right hips on 10/12/13    Patient underwent recent imaging 10/23 - 10/28/13:    Admitted with acute worsening R hip pain. Controlled initially with dilaudid PCA, transitioned to PO medications with the aid of the palliative consult service. Evaluated by orthopedics with no urgent procedure indicated, recommendation to follow up as outpatient. CT C/A/P demonstrated progression of disease. Had one episode fever In discussion with outpatient oncologist Dr. Vokes made referal to hospice services. Patient discharged to home with pain controlled and with plans to meet with local hospice services. Problem List   RLE pain 2/2 known metastasis - R LE pain is improving after titrating PCA. Baseline ambulation with cane, seen by PT and given rolling walker. Also with some new onset sacral pain without lesions seen on MRI. No prior or current evidence of fracture needing inpatient orthopaedic intervention. - ortho consulted, patient will f/u with them as OP (Dr. Haydon) for consideration of palliation, however need to discuss again now that hospice is the likely course   - pain medication as documented below   Squamous Cell CA of the Tonsils - Metastatic disease to lungs, liver, mesenteric LN, R hip. Hx of progression on carbo/taxol (completed 6 cycles  in 3/2013), was receiveing lambrolizumab (anti PD-1 agent). Repeat CT imaging (9/27 and now 10/25) shows progression in size of reference lesions and small, new small pulmonary micronodules, mesenteric LN, and +/- R kidney that represents disease progression per Dr. Vokes. He now recommends hospice care. - Family has decided not to go with Vitas Hospice and would like to pursue Advocate hospice, which is closer to their house. They are coming to discuss this with the patient and his wife today. Chest Wall Nodule - Nontender nodule, present for 4 months. Punch biopsy prior per derm which showed metastatic SCC on biopsy   - dermatology evaluated with no plans for resection   Constipation - Likely 2/2 narcotics - last bm 2d ago   - Cont pericolase 2 tabs bid, increasing miralax; dulcolax suppository as needed - patient has previously refused the suppository but will take it if miralax does not help   Anxiety/Depression - Continued on pta celexa and clonazepam scheduled and alprazolam prn. |

narrative: 2010-07-01:	At the end of 2010. |2013-03-29:	Wayne J Clark is a 51Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic SCCHN. |2013-05-13:	Wayne J Clark is a 52Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic HNSCC, p16+. Pt most recently progressed on cetuximab and enrolled in clinical trial (IRB 10428) randomized to temsirolimus. Here for C2D8. Eating well, good energy. No stomatitis. BS has been well controlled at home. No past medical history on file. |2013-05-20:	Wayne J Clark is a 52Yrs male here for follow-up of metastatic SCCHN. |2013-06-03:	began 6/3/13 and was stopped after PD on CT scan (increase of 22% in R liver lesion). |2013-07-08:	Mr. Wayne J Clark is a 52yo male here for follow-up of metastatic HPV+ R tonsilar SCC, who most recently progressed on cetuximab, enrolled in cetuximab/temsirolimus study (IRB 10428) randomized to only temsirolimus in 03.13, and then progressed with a new liver lesion (6.3.13) and was crossed-over to receive cetuximab/temsirolimus. Today, he is on C2D8. He reports the following:  - mouth sores x 1 week  - mouth pain, controlled on hydrocodone/acetaminophen 10/325mg q6h prn and G1MW  - loose stools (x1 per day), associated with metformin (recently started ~ 3 weeks ago) for hyperglycemia  - G1 fatigue at the end of each week  - good appetite  - decreasing facial and chest rash    Otherwise, he is eating well and has good energy levels. Brief oncologic history:  Mr. Clark was initially diagnosed with HPV+ R tonsilar stage IVA T2N2b SCC in 2009 and received cis/RT. At the end of 2010, he was found to have bilateral metastatic pulmonary nodules (biopsy proven) and a malignant pleural effusion for which he had pleuredesis. In 02.11, he was enrolled in the ECOG1305 docetaxel/cis/bevacizumab trial and had a CR. He was maintained on bevacizumab till 02.12, when he was found to have new bilateral pulmonary nodules. He was then started on cis/docetaxel and he was seen at UoC in 03.12. Cetuximab was added to this regimen. In 03.13, he was found to have progressive disease and he was enrolled in the cetux/temsirolimus study randomized to temsirolimus only, but he progressed in 06.13 and he was crossed-over to the cetuximab/temsirolimus arm. |2013-07-29:	He had CTs on 7.25.13 which revealed PD (increase by 22% by RECIST), mostly in the liver (R lobe liver lesion). Today, he is on C3D1. He reports the following:  - denies mouth pain. - loose stools (x1 per day), associated with metformin (recently started ~ 3 weeks ago) for hyperglycemia  - G1 fatigue at the end of each week  - good appetite  - new acneiform rash in LEs bilaterally    Otherwise, he is eating well and has good energy levels. |2013-08-26:	Mr. Wayne J Clark is a 52yo male here for follow-up of metastatic HPV+ R tonsilar SCC, who most recently progressed on the cetuximab/temsirolimus study (IRB 10428). He was screened for the PD1 trial with a liver biopsy which was performed on 8.7.13 at Aurora hospital; result of PDL1 came back negative. Following the liver biopsy, the patient developed RUQ pain and high-grade recurrent fevers (up to 103.4) with chills alternating with low-grade fevers which persisted for approximately 10 days. A CXR and blood cultures were drawn on 8.23.13 at his local oncologist's office (Dr. Davis) with reportedly negative results. He also received 2 u pRBCs for a "low" Hg. A RUQ US the day after the biopsy had shown a hematoma (per patient's narrative, record to be requested from Dr.Davis). Currently, he reports the following:  - last high-grade fever ~ 2 days ago. - recovering acneiform rash on his scalp, on minocycline. - good appetite, mild baseline fatigue. Otherwire, he denies lightheadedness, fatigue, SOB, coughing, diarrhea, abdominal pain, pain or erythema at Portacath site, melena/BRBPR/hematemesis. The patient qualifies for the BKM120/cetuximab trial and is planned for enrollment. He had baseline CTs today which unfortunately showed further progression of his lung and liver metastasis. He was then started on cis/docetaxel and he  was seen at UoC in 03.12. He had further progression on the combined arm and came off the trial in the end of 07.13. He was subsequently screened for the PD1 trial with a liver biopsy on 8.7.13 which was though negative. |2013-10-28:	Pt was enrolled in temsirolimus +/- cetux (IRB 10428) randomized to temsirolimus; received 2C and was found to have progression. He crossed arms and received cetux + torisel, began 6/3/13 and was stopped after PD on CT scan (increase of 22% in R liver lesion). Pt is currently enrolled in IRB 121972 with BMK120+cetux. He completed 2 cycles of therapy and is here to discuss CT-Scan results. |

narrative: 2012-03-01:	Edwin Brant is a 68Yrs male with 68yo male with original diagnosis of right tongue base cancer in March 2012. |2012-03-01:	Edwin Brant is a 68Yrs male with recent diagnosis of right tongue base cancer in March 2012. |2012-03-23:	This lesion was negative on PET done on 3/23/12. |2012-03-29:	CT of chest at the time of diagnosis in 3/29/12. |2012-04-02:	He underwent bronchoscopy/esophagoscopy/laryngoscopy and bilateral selective neck dissection on 4/2/12. |2012-04-06:	done on 4/6/12. |2012-06-22:	On 6/22/12 he was seen for a sore on the right side of his mouth. |2012-09-03:	He completed C1/6.5 FHX from 9/3/2012--9/8/2012. |2012-09-05:	/  HPI 68 y/o male with recurrent oropharyngeal(R post tongue) SCC admitted for cycle 1/6.5 FHX. The history is provided by the patient. Accuracy of the patient data is good. |2012-09-06:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-07:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-08:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-08:	/  HPI 68 y/o male with recurrent oropharyngeal (R post tongue) SCC admitted for cycle 1/6.5 FHX. |2012-09-12:	Indurated 1x2.5cm lesion at the right tongue base lesion that extended from slightly anterior to the circumvallate papilla to 2 cm posterior to this level. It did not involve the tonsil or the palatal glossal fold. It did not extend deep into the ventricle. Although visualization of the tumor was fair he underwent a transoral robotic surgery, done on 4/6/12. He was found to have a T1-T2 carcinoma of the right posterior tongue, size 2.2 x 1.8 x 0.4 cm. Right BOT showed In-situ and infiltrating non-keratinizing squamous carcinoma. The new lateral margin showed squamous mucosa with mild dysplasia, no tumor. Posterior lateral margin showed squamous mucosa, no tumor. Distance to nearest negative margin was 0.2 cm to posterior margin. It invaded submucosa and adjacent soft tissue without vascular and perineural invasion. He was staged pT2, NX. HPV/p16 was negative. On 6/22/12 he was seen for a sore on the right side of his mouth, which led to an oral biopsy in clinic. Right mouth: biopsies showed invasive nonkeratinizing, focally necrotizing squamous cell carcinoma and inflamed surface mucosa with mild dysplasia. He was scheduled to undergo floor of mouth resection. Retromolar trigone showed squamous mucosa and minor salivary gland, no tumor. Right pharynx resection demonstrated invasive keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. New tongue margin showed squamous mucosa, adenoid tissue and skeletal muscle, no tumor. Tumor size was 1.5 x 1.5 x 1.1 cm, single focus, invasive squamous cell carcinoma,  keratinizing, invading submucosa and adjacent soft tissue, with margins negative for tumor with nearest edge, deep margin at soft palate (superior) was 0.1 cm away from invasive carcinoma. Additionally, CT of chest at the time of diagnosis in 3/29/12, patient was also found to have a 1.2cm lobulated lesion in right upper lobe. In addition, he had chest imaging as part of his pre-operative work up for his knee replacements a few years ago, which showed pulmonary nodules bilaterally. Patient states he was followed with imaging at the time, which per patient showed regression and/or stability of those lesions. He also had a PET scan at the time which was negative. Initially referred to IR for percutaneous biopsy, but it was felt that given severe emphysematous changes, IR approach would be unadvisable. He completed C1/6.5 FHX from 9/3/2012-9/8/2012. He reports primary side effects of nausea and mouth pain. He noted nausea 2-3 days subsequent to discharge. He is taking TID compazine with moderate relief. He was unable to fill zofran due to insurance concerns. He also reports mouth pain on the roof of his mouth, for which he is taking G1MW. He denies oral ulcers. narrative: 2012-05-01:	He presented with hoarseness and sore throat in May 2012 which did not respond to antibiotics. |2012-05-01:	sore throat and difficulty breathing in May 2012 which did not respond to antibiotics. |2012-06-09:	CT of the HN (6/9/12) revealed a large infiltrating transglottic laryngeal tumor with occlusion of the airway. |2012-06-25:	He is started on therapy with induction chemotherapy on 6/25/12 using carboplatin and taxol. |2012-07-30:	Michael Delgado is a 54Yrs male with diagnosis of stage IVa, HPV-16+, T4 N0 SCC of larynx. In Mid-may, he started to have hemoptysis, saw an otolaryngologist Dr Keenan who referred him to Dr.Stenson, who did a biopsy and pathology showed SCC. CT of the HN (6/9/12) revealed a large infiltrating transglottic laryngeal tumor with occlusion of the airway, extra-laryngeal extension and infiltration of the adjacent soft tissue structures. CT of the chest did not reveal the endobronchial lesion, but showed only two nonspecific micronodules. No specific evidence to suggest pulmonary metastatic disease. He also developed stridor hence necessitating a trach tube. Treatment was held from C1D15 week 2/2 neutropenia which led to dose reduction of both carboplatin and taxol. Today, he is here for f/u. Overall, he is doing better. He breaths better and he feels the track tube is lose and not as tight from tumor effect. On last visit, he had bilateral LE swelling from too much salted ham intake. The swelling has been responding to conservative effect of stockings and leg elevations. Today swelling is decreased from last time. Of note, he has chronic le swelling that comes and goes. Per pt, he has had work-up in the past and the etiology of his leg swelling could not be ascertained. He denies numbness/tingling/n/v/f/sob/cp/abdominal pain. His appetite and energy are both good. |2012-08-13:	Mr. Michael Delgado is a 54yo male here for follow-up of T4N0 supraglottic laryngeal SCC, on C2D15 of induction carbo/taxol. In more detail, Mr. Delgado is a 54yo male with diagnosis of stage IVa, p16+, T4N0 supraglottic SCC diagnosed in 06.12. He initially presented with hoarseness, sore throat and difficulty breathing in May 2012 which did not respond to antibiotics. In mid May, he started having hemoptysis and saw an otolaryngologist (Dr Keenan) who referred him to Dr.Stenson. On 6.8.12, the patient had panendoscopy, tracheostomy for stridor and biopsy showed SCC. Triple endoscopy showed a mostly submucosal tumor of the right aryepiglottic fold extending to the lingual surface of the epiglottis, around through the paraglottic space and involving the left vocal cord. On the left upper lobe takeoff at its junction with the lingula takeoff a small exophytic mass was noted. On pathology review, the biopsy of the false cord lesion revealed in-situ and invasive keratinizing SCC, P16+. The endobronchial bx and brushings revealed invasive SCC. CT of the HN on 6.9.12 revealed a large infiltrating transglottic laryngeal tumor with occlusion of the airway, extra-laryngeal extension and infiltration of the adjacent soft tissue structures. CT of the chest did not reveal the endobronchial lesion, but showed only two nonspecific micronodules, one in the LUL and a subpleural nodule in the RLL, which was read as nonspecific for pulmonary mets. He was started on induction chemotherapy on 6.25.12 with carbo/taxol. Dose reduction was necessary due to neutropenia during C2. Today is C2D15 and he is here for regular follow up, his 5th dose of carbo/taxol and review of his most recent CTs on 8.9.12. CT neck revealed significant reduction in laryngeal mass from 3.8cm down to 2.1cm, but also showed a new RUL 6mm pulmonary nodule (stable 2 LUL and 1 RLL micronodules). He reports feeling well, no pain at trach site, no dysphagia, no shortness of breath/no orthopnea, stable weight, good appetite and energy levels. He notes recurrent LE swelling, which is symmetric, has been intermittently present for the past 5 years, approximately 3-4times/year and has been worked up with ECHO/LE angiograms (per patient) at multiple outside hospitals, with possible diagnosis of venous insufficiency. |2012-08-28:	/  HPI 54 y/o male with T4N0 SGL SCC admitted for C1/5 TFHX  The history is provided by the patient. He was started on induction chemotherapy on 6.25.12 with carbo/taxol and then continued with CRT with TFHX, currently post C4/5. Tolerating TFHX very well. His only complaints pertains on current trach, which has been causing difficulties with sleeping due to persistent cough (patient noted that while on Montgomery tube, he could sleep well throughout the night). Otherwise, he reports good appetite, stable weight, good energy levels. Lower back pain well controlled. No constipation. Denies dysphagia or mouth pain. |2012-10-23:	/  HPI 54 y/o male with T4N0 SGL SCC admitted for C5/5 TFHX  The history is provided by the patient. |2012-10-24:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-10-26:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-11-26:	Mr. Michael Delgado is a 54yo male here for follow-up of stage IVa, HPV+, T4N0 supraglottic laryngeal SCC s/p 2 cycles of carbo/taxol induction, now on CRT, completed C5/5 TFHX on 10.26.12. He was started on induction chemotherapy on 6.25.12 with carbo/taxol and then continued with CRT with TFHX, currently completed 5/5 cycles on 10.26.12. He is here today for a regular follow up and review of CTs performed on 11.23.12. CT head/neck showed persistent but stable 2cm L arytenoepiglottic thickening, while CT chest showed stable and new  bilateral pulmonary subcentimeter micronodules. His trach has been removed and his only current complaint is mild odynophagia. |2013-01-07:	Mr. Michael Delgado is a 54yo male here for follow-up of stage IVa, HPV+, T4N0 supraglottic laryngeal SCC s/p 2 cycles of carbo/taxol induction and 5/5 cycles of TFHX completed on 10.26.12, here for re-evaluation of pulmonary nodules detected in CT chest in 11.12. The endobronchial biopsy and brushings revealed invasive SCC. CT of the chest did not reveal the endobronchial lesion, but showed two nonspecific micronodules, one in the LUL and a subpleural nodule in the RLL, which was read as nonspecific for pulmonary mets. He was started on induction chemotherapy on 6.25.12 with carbo/taxol and then continued with CRT with TFHX and completed 5/5 cycles on 10.26.12. CT head/neck on 11.23.12 Mr. Michael Delgado is a 54yo male here for follow-up of stage IVa, HPV+, T4N0 supraglottic laryngeal SCC s/p  2 cycles of carbo/taxol induction, now on CRT, completed C5/5 TFHX on 10.26.12. Follow up CT head/neck on 11.23.12 showed persistent but stable 2cm L arytenoepiglottic thickening, while CT chest showed stable and new bilateral pulmonary subcentimeter micronodules. He is here today for a regular follow up and review of  PET on 1.4.13 to assess stability of pulmonary micronodules. PET showed no uptake in lungs,  but revealed L level II neck uptake (SUV=4.7) and retropharyngeal uptake (SUV=4.1). Triple endoscopy on 11.29.12 (Dr. Stenson) was unremarkable. He had EGD on 12.18.12 (Dr. Konda) which revealed a moderate stenosis at the upper third of the esophagus which was successfully dilated. His only current complaint is mild odynophagia and intermittent neck swelling (especially after waking up). His dysphagia has singificantly improved after the esophageal dilatation. No fevers, denies coughing. |2013-03-08:	Michael Delgado is a 55Yrs male with T4N0 supraglottic laryngeal SCC s/p 2 cycles of carbo/taxol induction and 5/5 cycles of TFHX completed on 10.26.12 |2013-06-24:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2013-10-04:	Michael Delgado is a 55Yrs male, completed TFHX October 2012 |2014-07-21:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2015-03-16:	Michael Delgado is a 55Yrs male, completed TFHX October 2012. However, in 2016 a peribronchial mass developed, which, when biopsied, showed SCC, HPV negative. Of note, the left epiglotis lesion (non-oropharyngeal) was HPV positive and the new lung mass is HPV negative. Complains of chronic back pain, s/p several surgeries, on opioids. Good response (PR). Today is C8D1. Denies any side effects since her last treatment. Treated with Nivolumab ~June 2016, initially kept tumor stable. Last CT in 9/2016 - stable lung disease. Last dose of Nivolumab 1/20/2017 - some side effects: Fatigue, aches, constipation, dry skin/itching. Clinically feeling well, but has skin itching, and social concerns as her illness has affected ability to work. Is planning to move back to Chicago and transfer her care back to us. She report feeling overall well, other than persistent xerostomia and reported regurgitation of food and liquids through her nose x 1-2 weeks. The rest of the review of systems is unremarkable. She is currently in the process of moving from Oregon to Chicago. |2018-04-06:	Patient received C1D1 carbo/taxol on 4/6/18 and was consented for pembrolizumab +/-- epicadostat trial with Dr. Seiwert. |2018-04-06:	Admitted 4/3--4/6/18 at UCMC for management of pain and progressive facial swelling due to disease and superimposed cellulitis. |2018-04-06:	Patient received C1D1 carbo/taxol on 4/6/18 and presents today for continuation of chemotherapy at Orland Park with plan to continue chemotherapy pending clinical trial availability. |2018-04-12:	Metastatic HNC (tonsil SCC)    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:   Suzanne Peace is a 52 yo woman with metastatic HNC--metastases to lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes--who presents today to transfer care to Orland Park for ongoing chemotherapy while awaiting clinical trial. Her oncologic history is as follows:    Part of KN12 pembrolizumab study with excellent response 2014/2015  Then transferred to Providence Cancer Care, but quickly transferred to Corvalis clinic/Samaritan (city: Corvalis). She has had dysphagia due to progressive mediastinal lymphadenopathy. Admitted 4/3-4/6/18 at UCMC for management of pain and progressive facial swelling due to disease and superimposed cellulitis. Dr. Seiwert consulted. While in Hyde Park she also consented for pembrolizumab +/- epicadostat trial with Dr. Seiwert. Today she endorses fatigue, mild persistent nausea, no appetite and generally feels poorly after beginning chemotherapy. She denies fevers and chills. Swallowing is better since beginning treatment but she endorses  mild dysphagia. Chronic musculoskeletal pain in neck/shoulder but no acute concerns. No dyspnea. She is very unhappy about being on chemotherapy, stating that she only moved back here to be on a clinical trial, and insists that she will receive no more than 3 doses, per her discussions with Dr. Seiwert, and if the study drug is not available by then, she will go back home to the West coast. |2018-04-20:	Metastatic HNC (tonsil SCC)    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Suzanne Peace is a 52 yo woman with metastatic HNC--metastases to lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes--who presents today to continue care at Orland Park for ongoing chemotherapy while awaiting clinical trial. Today she is doing well. No new concerns. Energy, appetite and weight stable. No nausea. No diarrhea. Swallowing improving and tolerating oral medications. |2018-05-23:	Metastatic HNC (tonsil SCC)    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Suzanne Peace is a 52Yrs woman with metastatic HNC--metastases to lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes--who is currently receiving carboplatin/paclitaxel, prior to potentially starting ORKA trial with pembrolizumab and epacadostat. Oncologic History:  On Keynote 12 study of single agent pembrolizumab (cohort B2) study with excellent response 2014/2015  Then transferred to Providence Cancer Care, but quickly transferred to Corvalis clinic/Samaritan (city: Corvalis). Second dose of paclitaxel 4/20. PLan for ORKA study of Pembrolizumab plus epacadostat after initial chemotherapy and reduction of symptoms. She is here for C2. She has noticed some gradual symptoms that are worsening since stopping the chemo. The biggest issue is pain in her left upper extremity that is due to disease. She thinks it has worsened some since stopping chemotherapy. She takes Ibuprofen 400 mg at a time which usually helps. She doesn't want anything stronger. She also thinks the oral study drug causes some nightmares, which were bad the first 3 nights  but havent been as strong since. She has sleep aids (Ambien and Ativan) which do help when she takes them but make her groggy the next day. She denies mood change during the day. This is a tolerable side effect for now. She denies GI upset. She is eating and drinking fairly well. Her other complaint is more coughing the last 3 days. She admits to frequent post nasal drainage and has had productive yellow-ish green nasal discharge. No fevers. Has Albuterol inhaler which she hasn't used recently because it causes her to cough a lot. Tolerating Pembro well without rash, GI upset, change in appetite or energy. Ready for treatment today. |2018-06-14:	She is here for C3. She is not feeling well. She has had symptoms of a cold for the past month with nasal congestion, wheezing, cough. She denies fevers. She requests promethazine + codeine specifically for cough. She refuses Tylenol with Codeine. She thinks swallowing has been more of an issue and wants the G tube back in. She denies diarrhea or rash. She is frustrated because she feels like she is not doing better and is getting  worse. She has upcoming CT scans and wants to keep everything on schedule but ultimately wants to transfer care to Orland Park. |2018-08-06:	Attempted Bronchoscopy (8/6/2018) which was aborted due to diffuse laryngeal edema with near complete obstruction of the airway. |2018-08-13:	8/13/2018:. |2018-08-14:	8/14/2018 -- :. |2018-08-27:	Patient received C1D1 carbo/taxol on 4/6/18 and was consented for pembrolizumab +/- epicadostat trial with Dr. Seiwert. Coughing, swallowing and breathing have improved. Now able to eat yoghurt. She self discontinued prednisone that was administered for airway protection. Endorses some fatigue. Did not start K despite recommendations. |2018-09-26:	9/26/2018 -- :. |2018-09-26:	Metastatic HNC (tonsil SCC)    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Suzanne Peace is a 52Yrs  woman with metastatic HNC--metastases to lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes--who presents today to continue care at Orland Park for ongoing chemotherapy while awaiting clinical trial. Now able to eat yogurt but taking majority of nutrition via G tube. Notes feeling that chemotherapy "isn't agreeing with" her and she wonders if there is something else she can do. Energy level is low. She endorses diffuse myalgias and arthralgias that are modestly controlled with morphine prn. She does not want to try a long-acting opiate given concern that it will affect her ability to drive and be functional if she wants to. She feels that taking a long-acting opiate, like a fentanyl patch, would make her just "lay there and die". She notes two evenings where, around 10 pm, she was at home with her ex and felt confusion, her mind felt foggy and she felt as though she new what she was trying to say but the right words weren't coming out and she was babbling. She did not have any other neurologic deficits at the time--no visual disturbances or unilateral weakness or paresthesia. She cannot identify any triggering factors and it has only happened on two episodes and has not recurred. |2018-10-13:	Metastatic HNC (tonsil SCC); HPV positive. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Suzanne Peace is a 52 yo woman with metastatic HNC--metastases to lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes--who presents today to continue care at Orland Park for ongoing chemotherapy while awaiting clinical trial. HPV positive. Day 8 delayed by 3 weeks due to non-compliance and neutropenia. narrative: 2012-05-01:	May 2012 -- chronic lesions over lateral tongue with scar tissue. |2012-05-01:	9/25/2012 -- Presented to UCMC with mother and father for initial visit in the H&N Onc Clinic to discuss possible treatment options. |2012-05-01:	8/15/2012 to 9/12/2012 -- underwent 21 radiation sessions. |2012-05-01:	surgical resection 5/2012 and adjuvant radiation therapy. |2012-05-08:	Diagnosed initially 5/8/12 under went tongue resection. |2012-05-08:	5/8/2012 -- Left tongue lesion biopsy: superficial fragments of invasive moderately differentiated (grade 2) squamous cell cancer. |2012-05-31:	5/31/2012 -- PET showed no involvement in the left neck without CT enlarged nodes. |2012-06-19:	6/19/2012 -- resection of tongue lesion. |2012-06-21:	6/21/2012 -- Tongue. |2012-07-09:	7/9/2012 -- Resection of tongue lesion for what was felt to be close margins. |2012-08-15:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-01:	He was seen here 9/2012 and care has been coordinated with his local oncologist. |2012-09-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-12:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-14:	9/14/2012 -- exam findings: left periumbilical mass measures 1.8 x 1.7 x 1.6 cm. |2012-09-18:	9/18/2012 -- Surgical pathology. |2012-09-20:	9/20/2012 -- PET shows widespread presumed metastatic disease. |2012-09-25:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-09-25:	9/25/2012 -- presents today with mother and father to discuss possible treatment options. |2012-09-25:	squamous cell cancer of the tongue, now metastatic    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: 37 y/o male with history of squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue status post surgical resection and adjuvant radiation therapy, now presenting with numerous skin nodules over the back, anterior left chest, and anterior abdominal wall, with biopsy proven metastatic disease. His oncologic history is outlined below. Of note, he previously had a tracheostomy (since removed), and is currently still with feeding tube. May 2012 - chronic lesions over lateral tongue with scar tissue, from severe tongue biting injuries. Above tongue biting injuries were due to seizures, possibly alcohol related. He noticed a "dime sized blister" and his pain became persistent. He was seen at an urgent care appointment and antibiotic therapy was attempted without improvement. He was referred to ENT. 5/8/2012 - Left tongue lesion biopsy: superficial fragments of invasive moderately differentiated (grade 2) squamous cell cancer. Exam with 5.5 cm, exophytic lesion. 5/31/2012 - PET showed no involvement in the left neck without CT enlarged nodes. 6/19/2012 - resection of tongue lesion, greatest dimension 3.6 cm (though felt to be larger clinically). 6/21/2012 - Tongue, left, resection: Squamous cell carcinoma of the lateral tongue. Well and moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma, grade 1-2. Inked surgical margins negative for carcinoma. Tumor thickness 7 mm. Negative for HPV virus subtype. T3 SCC of the tongue. 7/9/2012 - Resection of tongue lesion for what was felt to be close margins. Left lymph node dissection levels one, two, three: 2/23 lymph nodes positive for metastatic carcinoma. No extranodal extension. Negative  re-resection margins. Flap procedure with G tube. Felt to have T3N2bM0 oral cavity tongue cancer. 8/15/2012 to 9/12/2012 - underwent 21 radiation sessions. Per patient, side effects of facial swelling, mouth blistering, skin peeling, now starting to heal. During these radiation sessions, he noticed a mass/cyst on the right side of his head as well as a skin nodule over his abdomen. 9/14/2012 - exam findings: left periumbilical mass measures 1.8 x 1.7 x 1.6 cm, left subcostal mass measures 1.6 x 1.0 x 0.7 cm. Antibiotics attempted without change in size. 9/18/2012 - Surgical pathology, periumbilical mass biopsy: metastatic poorly differentiated carcinoma. Cytokeratin (+), keratin 7 (-), keratin 20 (-), p63 (+), and p16 weak (+). Poorly differentiated carcinoma suggestive of squamous origin. 9/20/2012 - PET shows widespread presumed metastatic disease. Scalp and brain: numerous metabolically active subcutaneous and dermal nodules were present in the scalp. Largest lies high over the right convexity and has an SUV max of 23. Other lies posterior to the lateral wall of the left orbit int he soft tissues. Chest: numerous metabolically active lung nodules are present. Subcutaneous nodules are present over the left upper anterior chest, the left posterior back, and ribs. Active hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes are present. Abdomen: subcutaneous nodules over the left and right sides of the abdomen in multiple areas. Pelvis: A large mass lesion is present in the anterior abdominal wall just lateral and inferior to the umbilicus. 9/25/2012 - presents today with mother and father to discuss possible treatment options. He reports that he had recent PORT placed in anticipation for chemotherapy. Today, he states that he is still recovering from the recent radiation treatments. He is using his G-tube for nutrition, and getting 2000 calories/day through the G-tube. He is taking pills and ~4 liters of  fluid by mouth. He states that food no longer tastes good since starting the radiation treatment. He reports that he has noticed several skin and soft tissue nodules over his back and anterior chest/abdomen over the past several weeks. He states that one lesion over his scalp opened ~ 1 week ago and was draining, but is no longer with active drainage. He is having a considerable amount of diffuse pain, for which he is taking fentanyl 300 mcg daily with dilaudid 8 mg Q2 hours prn. He is having poor sleep as a result of the pain. He has lost 20 lbs since diagnosis in May. |2012-10-01:	with whom he started his first cycle of chemotherapy 10/1/2012 with platinum/5FU. |2012-10-23:	Follow-up for squamous cell cancer of the tongue, now widely metastatic to the skin/subcutaneous tissue    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Mr. Eckart is a 37 year old man with Hx of squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue s/p surgical resection 5/2012 and adjuvant radiation therapy, now with numerous Bx-proven metastatic nodules over his back, anterior left chest, head, and anterior abdominal wall, with biopsy proven metastatic disease. He was seen here 9/2012 and care has been coordinated with his local oncologist, Dr. Gerstner, with whom he started his first cycle of chemotherapy 10/1/2012 with platinum/5FU. However, during his cycle, his molecular studies returned positive for PIK3CA mutation. Thus, he returns today to discuss clinical trial option investigating targeted therapy. Today, he complains of continued pain from his lesions. The one on his chest burst last night and has been draining bloody fluid. narrative: 2007-05-01:	May 2007-- March 2008 with carboplatin/cisplatin +paclitaxel . |2008-03-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2008-04-01:	April 2008 -- July 2008 cetuximab. |2008-07-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2008-07-01:	July 2008 -- October 2008 MTX. |2008-10-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2008-12-01:	December 2008 docetaxel. |2009-05-01:	May 2009 -- Feb 2011:. |2010-04-01:	March -- April 2010:. |2011-02-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2011-04-01:	March -- April 2011:. |2011-11-01:	Aug 2011 -- Nov 2011. |2012-02-01:	Feb 2012 -- April 2012 erlotinib. |2012-04-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-05-01:	PD documented again by May 2012. |2012-06-01:	May -- June 2012:. |2012-06-01:	June 2012:. |2012-08-15:	8/15/12:. |2012-10-05:	Jerome Buhr is a 59Yrs male former smoker with TxNxM1 SCC of the nasopharynx who has had worsening progression of disease over the past year. He states his cancer history dates back to 2003-2004, shortly after being treated for unstable angina and requiring CABG in 2002-2003. He was noting intermittent hemoptysis and eventually progressively worsening dysphagia but work-up had been unrevealing. By early 2005, he noted a painless progressively enlarging R neck mass that was consistent with locally advanced squamous cell carcinoma with a nasopharyngeal primary with invasion of the primary tumor into the skull base and cervical spine. He was treated with definitive CRT with carboplatin and RT (57.6 Gy + 720 boost) per review. He unfortunately developed pulmonary metastases in 2007, biopsy-proven. He underwent sveral chemotherapy regimens as summarized:  May 2007- March 2008 with carboplatin/cisplatin +paclitaxel , leading to disease progression  April 2008 - July 2008 cetuximab, led to disease progession, no allergy or intolerance  July 2008 - October 2008 MTX, with disease progression  December 2008 docetaxel, with disease prgression  March - April 2010:  WBI, CyberKnife to R frontal lobe lesion  May 2009 - Feb 2011:  cisplatin + capecitabine, with disease progression, eventual platinum allergy  March - April 2011:  Palliative RT to L lung mass (35 Gy)  Aug 2011 - Nov 2011  Gemcitabine, with disease progression  Feb 2012 - April 2012 erlotinib, with  PD documented again by May 2012  May - June 2012:  CyberKinfe to LUL lung mass (30Gy)  June 2012:  CyberKnife to LLL lung mass (30 Gy)  June 2012:  Pall RT to bilateral groin/thigh masses (20 Gy)       Last imaging:  PET scan:9/21/12:  Enlarged lingular/LUL mass, enlarging pericardiac/aortic lymphadenopathy, new focus in dome of liver, new R internal iliac lymphadenopathy and enlarging R inguinal lymph node, new focus in L iliac wing suspicious for metastasis. CT scan neck/chest/BLE:  8/15/12:  Neck unremarkable, some regression post-RT in LLL and LUL lesions, with multiple pulmonary nodules bilaterally, L thigh mass resolving, new small L pleural effusion  MRI brain:  July 9, 2012:  Small vessel disease with post-RT changes, prior R frontal lesion remains stable 8 mm x 6 mm    Currently, he has been feeling a bit better off chemotherapy. He is able to ADLs without impairment. He has mild fatigue and has noticed some gradual worsening dyspnea on exertion. He has a chornic productive cough but has not worsened but does note some increased dysphagia wtihout pain over last month or so. He has xerostomia and is mitigated byeeping water bottle and Biotene with him wherever he goes. He lives alone but has a circle of friends for support. He denis worsening subjective lymphadenopathy. He supplements oral intake with enteral feeds with BoostPlus 5 cans/day. His pain is current well controlled with his current medical regimen. He will rarely use Roxanol for breakthrough pain. In November 2011 he noticed a bump on the right side of his tongue which, at some point, he inadvertently bit into which caused it to ulcerate but it did not heal and, rather, continued to grow. He presented to his local ENT who performed a direct laryngoscopy with biopsy which was positive for poorly differentiated, p16+ SCC (see paraphrased pathology report below). His initial right tongue lesion measured ~2.5 x3 cm at the time of diagnosis. He completed 3 cycles of concurrent cisplatin RT by March of 2012 and by late August, routine imaging picked up bilateral pulmonary nodules which were suspicious for metastatic disease. FNA of one of the lesions confirmed this diagnosis and pt underwent palliative RT to a posterior pulmonary lesion which was in close proximity to the spine along with two other lesions. He received 2 cycles of salvage chemotherapy with carboplatin and Taxol in late August/early September. He began having back pain later in September and a bone scan revealed a metastatic lesion in the left femoral neck. Pt notes that he had not been having pain at this site, per se, nevertheless he received palliative RT to this lesion in 9/2012. Follow up CT on 10/4/12 revealed a new pleural based, 3.5 x 4.3 cm mass in the right lung which was new since 7/14/12. Pt presents today to discuss options for treatment moving forward. narrative: 2012-11-01:	pT2N2aM0 Stage IVA diagnosed in November 2012. |2012-11-01:	11/2012 Initial diagnosis of tongue tumor. |2013-03-01:	chemoRT in March 2013. |2013-03-11:	3/11/2013: Completed radiotherapy to the head and neck area. |2013-08-01:	In August 2013. |2013-09-01:	then recurrence with 2nd surgery 9/2013 with positive margins. |2013-09-01:	9/9/2013: Had partial glossectomy as well as thyroidectomy. |2013-09-01:	then recurrence with 2nd surgery 9/2013. |2013-09-09:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2013-09-09:	9/9/2013: Had partial glossectomy. |2013-10-01:	10/2013 a Ct scan at Northshore showed increasing mass along left aspect of the flap. |2013-10-01:	10/2013 a CT scan at Northshore showed increasing mass along left aspect of the flap. |2013-10-28:	10/28/2013: CT of the head and soft tissue neck showed increasing mass effect with associated subtle enhancement noted along the leftward aspect of the glossectomy flap. |2013-11-03:	Roslyn Ebstein is a 81Yrs female with oral tongue squamous cell carcinoma, pT2N2aM0 Stage IVA diagnosed in November 2012, s/p chemoRT in March 2013, who then had a recent recurrence and is s/p resection with PNI and positive margins. In August 2013, a screening CT sfound to have a new cystic lesion at the hemiglossectomy site that was positive for recurrent SCCa; she then underwent thyroidectomy, trach placement, partial glossectomy and free tissue transfer by Dr. Stenson. Pathology showed positive margins, as well as multifocal papillary thyroid carcinoma. She had an OPM afterwards that showed chronic vestibular penetration and trace aspiration; recommended she not take anything PO. Oncology History:    3/11/2013: Completed radiotherapy to the head and neck area. Received 60 Gy in 30 fractions. 10/28/2013: CT of the head and soft tissue neck showed increasing mass effect with associated subtle enhancement noted along the leftward aspect of the glossectomy flap, abutting the posterior aspect the fatty midline raphae. Although its margins are somewhat ill defined, it measures approximately 26 mm AP by 25 mm transverse by 16 mm craniocaudal dimension, worrisome for progression/recurrence. A previously demonstrated large ill-defined region of hypoattenuation inferior to the right mandibular body has decreased in size. However, more superiorly there is a more organized component with peripheral   enhancement which abuts the undersurface of the right mandibular body (best seen image 36, series 6) without evidence of osseous erosion. This may represent a more organized phlegmon or early abscess. ECOG Performance Status:  *** |2013-11-05:	Roslyn Ebstein is a 81Yrs female here for follow-up with oral tongue squamous cell carcinoma, pT2N2aM0 Stage IVA diagnosed in November 2012, s/p surgery, radiation, then recurrence with 2nd surgery 9/2013. She is now here to discuss a second round of adjuvant treatment versus watchful waiting. narrative: 2012-10-01:	Sept/Oct 2012 --. |2012-10-01:	Sept/Oct 2012 -- had developed sharp pains in the face. |2012-10-07:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-10-07:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2012-11-30:	11/30/2012 -- left superficial parotidectomy with FN dissection. |2013-03-01:	Feb/March 2013 -- he was treated with 6 weeks of radiation therapy at Silver Cross. |2013-05-01:	April/May 2013 -- noted to have soft tissue/dermal metastases soon after.. |2013-06-01:	June 2013 -- seen in medical oncology clinic at Silver Cross. |2013-06-25:	Edwin Moore is a 83Yrs male with history of CAD, CABG, and CKD (Cr 2.0), who presents with recurrent parotid gland carcinoma, with dermal metastases. His oncologic history is outlined below. Sept/Oct 2012 - had developed sharp pains in the face, which worked its way up and down his face on the left side over two months. He also noted some neck pain in late summer 2012. Sept/Oct 2012 -  patient was examined by Dr Gartlan and noted to have a 4 cm mass in the neck, specifically, at the level of the mandible, involving the neck and skin. PET/CT showed lymph nodes in the AP window. In the left hilum, there was a lymph node with an SUV of 3.55, in the right hilum an SUV of less than 2.5, and in the left infrahilar area an SUV of 3.53. The left neck showed a rounded mass, SUV of 8. Origin appeared to be salivary gland, with lateral margins of the anterior left SCM likely involved. 11/30/2012 - left superficial parotidectomy with FN dissection, left neck advancement flap reconstruction, left WLE neck SCCA, level II cervical LN dissection. Pathology notes well to moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of primary parotid gland origin, extending to the posterior and very close to the deep margin, with extensive replacement of 2 paraparotid lymph nodes. Left neck, level 2 lymph nodes: 1/4 lymph nodes positive. Close margins due to facial nerve preservation. Feb/March 2013 - he was treated with 6 weeks of radiation therapy at Silver Cross. Our preliminary records confirm 6600 cGy on 2/1, 5000 cGy on 2/15, and 4000 cGy on 2/26. April/May 2013 - noted to have soft tissue/dermal metastases soon after,  and possibly during end of, radiation treatment. June 2013 - seen in medical oncology clinic at Silver Cross. Asked to see medical and radiation oncology at U Chicago to see if more treatment is possible. While extensive surgical resection was considered, it would require wide excision of left facial and neck skin with flap reconstruction in a patient whose medical status was felt to be fragile with serious risk for morbidity. In addition, his dermal metastases were felt to be a poor prognostic sign, such that systemic options without further RT were favored. As such, he is referred for recurrent parotid gland neoplasm with dermal metastases. Prior therapy has included surgery, radiation. He presents with his family today. His medical co-morbidities include CAD with prior triple bypass surgery. He denies any angina. He notes mild dyspnea with activity. He notes history of CKD, with baseline Cr 2.0. His family notes that his dermal metastases have started to grow in size, and that the "open area" appears bigger. He ambulates with a walker or cane due to arthritis. He has lost approximately 15 lbs in the past year. He denies diabetes, but notes a numbness/tingling over his hands and feet. He notes a prior history of carpal tunnel. He has hypothyroidism, replaced with synthroid. He has mild abdominal discomfort, though this is largely over his prior umbilical hernia site. He notes some swelling over the left side of his face, over his soft tissue/mandibular mass. He notes that he sometimes has trouble swallowing. Functionally, his performance status is estimated to be 2. He continues to work in a hobby shop, but is able to work for 1-2 hours before taking a 1 hour break. He feels that he is able to spend approximately 4 hours when he is "up and about" during the day. The remainder of the day is spent in a chair, and in particular, he recalls spending most of his day in a  chair/couch during RT treatments.
