narrative: 2013-01-21:	Mary L Krueger is a 59Yrs female with squamous cell cancer of the right tongue. Her oncologic history is outlined below. She initially presented with sore throat, sore tongue, and sensation of a right sided "swollen gland." Her tongue discomfort on the right persisted since summer 2012. The above developed into right neck and jaw discomfort. She denied fevers, chills, sweats, weight loss. Denied dysphagia, voice changes, or SOB. Of note, she has not had prior tobacco use and has only had minimal EtOH use. She subsequently sought evaluation from a dentist, who noted an area of concern at the tongue and referred her to oral surgery. She later met with Dr. Ortega (ENT). 12/20/2012 CT scan of the neck with IV contrast - no definite abnormalities in the region of the tongue. Exam is limited by patient's dental fillings which produce prominent artifact in this area. Remainder of exam is otherwise unremarkable. On 12/27/2012, she underwent direct laryngoscopy with biopsies of tongue with Dr. Ortega. During procedure, there was noted to be a significant firmness and rough quality to the lateral aspect of the posterior tongue extending roughly 4 cm in length and possibly slightly more. Biopsies were taken at the most anterior as well as the most posterior portions along a 4 cm length of mucosa. 12/27/2012 surgical pathology, posterior tongue biopsy - invasive, moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma with keratinization. HPV status not reported. 12/27/2012 surgical pathology, anterior tongue biopsy - invasive, moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma with keratinization. Today, she notes that she can feel the roughness along the lateral aspect  of her tongue as well. She notes that her sense of taste has diminished. She has pain and discomfort, rated as a 9/10, for which she takes advil. She notes that sipping drinks with a straw causes further discomfort. She denies systemic symptoms of reduced energy, fever, chills, sweats, weight loss. She continues to work full time in the OR, in the surgical equipment field. Of note, she is up to date with respect to her other cancer screening, including mammogram, PAP, and coloscopy. She has a past medical history most notable for cardiac disease, including atrial fibrillation and sick sinus syndrome. She notes that she had an episode of sinus arrest for 6 seconds, which led to pacemaker placement. She has "runs" of atrial fibrillation at times, last episode 2 days ago, which she can subjectively appreciate. |2013-02-13:	Patient is here for f/u after recent visit. Pt was seen in ENT clinic on 4/9 and was stable at that time. Per family, pt was drowsy after being discharged on 4/8. She was complaining of SOB and mild abdominal pain prior to coming to ED. On Wednesday, pt was more lethargic and unresponsive and paramedics were called. Upon presentation to OSH, pt was obtunded with pH 6.99, CO2 103, HCO3 23. She was initially trialed on Bipap but failed quickly. Pt was intubated in the ED for Type II resp failure with elevated CO2. CT head negative for acute process. She was transfused 2u PRBC's and started on Levo for hypotension but unclear timeframe, now off. She was admitted to the CCU 2/2 elevated troponins, however had no EKG changes. narrative: 2013-05-01:	April--May 2013: noted minimal right neck swelling and isolated episode of small volume hemoptysis. |2013-05-10:	5/10/13: CT scan of the neck at OSH without contrast -- abnormally enhancing mass in the right anterior pharyngeal soft tissues which extends from the level of base of tongue into and obliterates the right aspect of the vallecula. |2013-05-16:	5/16/13: seen by his local ENT physician. |2013-05-24:	5/24/13: seen by Dr. Anderson at University of Iowa Radiation Oncology Dept who noted a right tonsillar mass emanating from the tonsillar fossa with no soft palate involvement. |2013-05-31:	5/31/13: PET/CT -- increased FDG in the right oropharynx consistent with known malignancy (max SUV 22.6). |2013-06-17:	William Bogard is a 71Yrs male with newly diagnosed right tonsil cancer, stage IVa. His oncologic history is outlined below. April-May 2013: noted minimal right neck swelling and isolated episode of small volume hemoptysis. No dysphagia, odynophagia, or weight loss. Noted his energy level to be good. 5/10/13: CT scan of the neck at OSH without contrast - abnormally enhancing mass in the right anterior pharyngeal soft tissues which extends from the level of base of tongue into and obliterates the right aspect of the vallecula, measuring 1.6 x 1.2 x 2.9 cm. There are multiple enlarged right level II and III cervical lymph nodes. Specifically, in the right neck, there is a 2.8 x 2.1 cm lymph node along the inner deep margin of the right SCM, with associated mass effect on the right IJ. Posterior to the above lymph node, there is a 1.7 x 1.3 cm lymph node, deep to the SCM. 5/16/13: seen by his local ENT physician, Dr Peter Hauslein. Right tonsillar biopsy demonstrated squamous cell carcinoma in situ, but the biopsy is superficial and underlying invasion could not be excluded. He was referred to University of Iowa. Exophytic portion extends to the level of the Uvula. On endoscopy, appears to be involving base of tongue, but on physical examination appears to rest upon base of tongue without invasion. FNA of right neck node: reported to demonstrate squamous cell carcinoma. HPV status unknown on report. Per patient, slides were sent to Loyola. 5/31/13: PET/CT - increased FDG in the right oropharynx consistent with known malignancy (max SUV 22.6). Two adjacent right level II lymph nodes that are FDG avid (SUV max 16.1), and third right level II lymph node with maximum SUV of 5.8. No increased FDG in the lungs or mediastinum. No distant metastases. Multidisciplinary Tumor Board at Iowa recommeded chemoradiation. He was referred to dentist, and had three dental extractions last week. Patient presents here for second opinion as he plans to get his treatment in Chicago because his son lives here and treatment would be easier as he lives alone. Today in clinic, he is doing well. He reports no oral or throat pain. No dysphagia or odynophagia. He is eating well, has a good appetite, and has not lost any weight. No hemoptysis or blood streak sputum since initial episode. No fatigue. No fevers, chills, night sweats. No otalgia. Denies trouble breathing. Past medical history of dyslipidemia, right carotid endarterectomy 5 years ago, iliac stents, HTN, and hearing loss from noise. Patient smoked 1 ppd for 31 years and quit 5 years ago. In more detail, Mr. Bogard was initially diagnosed with stage IVA HPV-positive R tonsil T2N2b SCC in 5.13, when he presented with several months of progressive R tonsillar enlargement, sore throat, occasional hemoptysis and R neck LAD. CT neck on 5.10.13 had showed a mass in the parapharyngeal space extending from the base of tongue to the vallecula with R sided neck LAD. R tonsil biopsy on 5.16.13 showed SCC in situ and R neck FNA was c/w metastatic SCC. The patient had PET/CT on 5.29.13 with no evidence of distant metastasis. He had induction carboplatin/paclitaxel (UoC) followed by CRT with carboplatin/paclitaxel/RT completed in 9.13. A follow up PET/CT in 13.13 showed a new 1.2cm RLL nodule which increased in size on CT chest in 1.14. On 2.4.14 the patient had a RLL wedge resection and pathology showed moderately differentiated SCC with negative margins and LVI present. Subsequent CT neck/chest on 5.27.14 showed a 2.8cm R paratracheal LN and a 3cm R level 4 SCL compressing the SVC (asymptomatic). The patient also reports that he recently started experiencing sore throat, for which he has been receiving fluconazole since approximately mid May. He was also evaluated by ENT and had a R tonsillar mass biopsy, which was reported as "benign" and c/w "yeast infection". The patient was self-referred to Dr. Blair and was seen today (6.3.14); laryngoscopy showed a suspicious R tonsilar mass, leukoplakia on the R vocal cord and multiple papillary lesion on the soft palate and base of tongue. The patient is here for further management plans. He reports stable weight, good appetite, and good energy levels. He denies mouth pain or sore throat or dysphagia. He had hearing loss bilaterally since his RT treatment. He quite smoking more than 20y ago. |2014-06-17:	William Bogard is a 72Yrs male with recurrent SCC with mediastenal LAD, here for further management plans. narrative: 2011-04-01:	Feb--April 2011 He received chemoradiotherapy with weekly cisplatin and 35 fractions of radiation over 7 weeks. |2011-12-01:	Late Dec 2011: initial presentation with persistent sore throat. |2012-12-01:	After treatment he then had 3 monthly f/u -- without evidence of disease until in December 2012 several spots in lung. |2012-12-01:	but with metastatic spread to the lungs noted in 12/2012. |2012-12-01:	cis--RT with lung mets noted 12/2012. |2012-12-21:	which were PET avid and biopsy on Dec 21 2012 confirmed SCC. |2013-08-14:	Dennis Fritz is a 67Yrs male with metastatic tonsil SCC carcinoma. Late Dec 2011: initial presentation with persistent sore throat, then patient developed progressive dysphagia  - On exam an enlarged Tonsil was noted, and he saw  Dr. Schmitt - who drained a left sided tonsilar abscess    January 21st laryngoscopy - - Biopsies were taken  Tumor in neck - Squamous Cell histology     Feb-April 2011 He received chemoradiotherapy with weekly cisplatin and 35 fractions of radiation over 7 weeks. He Tolerated ok, lost some weight though and required a feeding tube  Teeth removed post treatment    After treatment he then had 3 monthly f/u - without evidence of disease until in December 2012 several spots in lung, which were PET avid and biopsy on Dec 21 2012 confirmed SCC. January 3rd - Gerndt - thoroscopy - two removed 1.5cm + 2 more smaller lesions - (+) for SCC. He initiated 3-weekly chemotherapy with cetuximab - carboplatin 5-FU for 8 cycles followed by  cetuximab maintenance  This was done with his oncologist Dr. Mansky     Unfortunately in August - progressive disease was noted and he self referred himself here for a 2nd opinion. He continues to feel well, is entirely asymptomatic and fully functional    Other symptoms:  - Mild xerostomia post CRT  - Voice change post CRT |2013-09-11:	Dennis Fritz is a 67Yrs male here for follow-up of a metastatic SCC of the left tonsil s/p cis-RT, but with metastatic spread to the lungs noted in 12/2012. He had then received chemotherapy with Carbo/Taxol/cetuximab, but recently has had PD. He is referred here by Dr. Mansky for evaluation and potential participation in a clinical trial. We previously completed testing for PDL1 expression, a marker of an immune response against the cancer, and potentially a marker of benefit from anti-PD1 immune therapies. Of Michigan, and now returns to potentially participate in a clinical trial with BKM120 a pan-PI3K inhibitor given in combination with cetuximab. Of note BKM120 is CNS penetrating. He comes to clinic today to sign consent and plan the screening studies. He continues to feel well and denies any symptoms from the tumor including the brain mets or the brain RT that was given. |2013-12-17:	Of Michigan. Mild back pain stable. Still reports cough, worse with intake of liquids. States that he was tolerating solid food at home although witnessed coughing with PO solids as well. States he gets full very quickly and cannot eat much now. No fever, chills, worsening shortness of breath. Has not had BM in 1 week. No nausea or vomiting. +snoring at night per wife. |2014-02-04:	24 HOUR EVENTS   The patient reports stable back pain radiating to his thigh. Pain service discussed with patient who is amenable to trying an increase in his fentanyl as well as norco now that he is not constipated. Pulm bronchoscopy unable to place stent due to extensive disease burden but they did laser some tumor from out of the airway, patient feels breathing slightly improved. narrative: 2014-09-10:	Bhavesh Patel is a 45 year male with history of T3N1M0 squamous cell carcinoma of the left buccal mucosa status post resection with left mandibulectomy with fibular myocutaneous free flap reconstruction, left selective neck dissection with brief period of tracheostomy in March 2014 followed by adjuvant radiation therapy completed in May 2014 (no chemotherapy). Of note, a PET perfomed in January 2014 showed the buccal cancer and a small left level Ib SUV 2.3 node, no distant disease. At that time, he was also seen by Dr. Portugal, however, the patient had opted to receive surgery and radiation therapy locally with NorthShore Hospital. He had post-treatment imaging on June 23, 2014 that demonstrated no evidence of disease. However, soon after that time he began to experience intraoral discomfort and pain at the bilateral neck. He underwent further imaging with a CT neck on July 28, 2014 that demonstrated interval development of three enlarged, centrally necrotic right level IIa and IIb lymph nodes and a region of lucency possibly representing central necrosis or ulceration deep and medial to the posterior aspect of the mandibular graft along the buccal mucosa. Additionally, a PET was performed revealing multiple new areas of abnormal hypermetabolism including a lymph node adjacent to the right parotid, bilateral level II, left supraclavicular, left superior paratracheal, and left axillary lymph nodes, as well as a hypermetabolic lytic lesion in the left iliac wing and left upper lobe. The patient had an FNA of an ipsilateral cervical lymph node approximately one week ago that confirmed squamous cell carcinoma and an FNA of the left axillary lymph node soon after (8/7/14), that also confirmed metastatic SCC. He came to UoC for a second opinion on 8/8/14. Given the rapid growth of disease between June and early August, Dr. Campbell planned to start him on systemic chemotherapy as soon as possible. His choice of carbo/taxol was conditioned to reserve cetuximab to a possible second line therapy within the trial " tivanitnib/cetuximab", available at Northshore, in addition to the patient being platinum-naive. On 8/8/14, we also discussed clinical trials opened at UoC. However, I personally felt that delaying treatment to enrollment in clinical trials at that point (expected delay of at least 3 weeks, as discussed with RN and CRA at the time), when the patient already have a scheduled chemotherapy, would not be at his best interest. Mr. Patel then received chemotherapy C1D1, C1D8 and C1D15 on 8/28/q4 of carbo/taxol. Dr. Campbell felt the diseaese was not responding clinically and obtained a scan on 9/2/14, which confirmed so. There were growths in the left mandible, posterior parotid and right level 2 nodes. Presently, he reports moderate to severe pain controlled with morphine intraorally and at the bilateral neck. He tolerates a soft or pureed diet by mouth and has never required a feeding tube. He denies dysphagia, odynophagia, hoarseness, or otalgia. He reports he lost approximately 40 pounds between surgery and radiation therapy. He has gained about 10 pounds back and has fluctuated at his current weight of 160 pounds today. He has a brief history of betel-nut use, though denies current use and is a never smoker. No past medical history on file. No Known |2014-09-11:	Bhavesh Patel is a 46Yrs male here for consultation regarding Buccal cancer. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Bhavesh Patel is a 45 year male with history of T3N1M0 squamous cell carcinoma of the left buccal mucosa status post resection with left mandibulectomy with fibular myocutaneous free flap reconstruction, left selective neck dissection followed by adjuvant radiation therapy now with local-regional recurrence and proven distant metastases with progression after one cycle of chemotherapy (carbo/taxol) presenting for a third opinion. He states he first noticed non-healing oral lesions December 2013 and was referred by his dentist to an oral surgeon who took a biopsy and diagnosed him with cancer. He was initially staged as T3N1M0 squamous cell carcinoma of the L buccal mucosa. He underwent resection with left mandibulectomy with fibular myocutaneous free flap reconstruction, left selective neck dissection briefly requiring a tracheostomy in March 2014. He then had adjuvant radiation therapy (no chemotherapy) which he completed in May 2014. He underwent further imaging with a CT neck on July 28, 2014 that demonstrated interval development of three enlarged, centrally necrotic right level IIa and IIb lymph nodes and a region of lucency possibly representing central necrosis or ulceration deep and medial to the posterior aspect of the mandibular  graft along the buccal mucosa. He was seen by his primary oncologist Dr. Campbell at Northshore who started him on chemotherapy. He received C1D1 (carbo/taxol), C1D8 (taxol) and C1D15 (taxol) on 8/28/14. The patient and Dr. Campbell both felt clinically his disease was progressing while actively on chemotherapy. Thus, repeat imaging was obtained 9/2 which did confirm progression of disease with growths in L mandible, posterior parotid, and R level 2 nodes. He presented to UofC for second opinion on 8/8/14 and was evaluated by Dr. DeSouza. Clinical trials were discussed and he ultimately signed consent for MK trial. He was also considering participation in tivantinib vs cetuximab trial through NorthShore. He presents today for third opinion. He has difficulty opening his mouth but has continued to tolerate a soft or pureed diet by mouth and has never required a feeding tube. He states he has lost about 50 pounds between surgery and radiation but currently has been stable. He feels his lymph nodes continue to enlarge and he is concerned about delaying treatment. He denies tobacco or EtOh use. He has a brief history of betel-nut use. |2014-09-21:	Buccal cancer. No nausea, vomiting, constipation, fevers, sweats or chills. |2014-10-25:	He is enrolled in the MK-3475 anti-PD1 clinical trial (IRB 130311) and has received two cycles, last on 10/9/14. Interval history:   His treatment on MK-3475 has been complicated by severe post-treatment face and upper airway edema requiring hospital admission. He was admitted on 9/24-9/27 after cycle 1 for increased facial edema and difficulty breathing. Unfortunately edema progressed after discharge and he presented again to the ED on 9/29 for admission. He had tracheostomy placed 10/2 for airway protection. He received cycle 2 on 10/9 with recurrence of severe facial and upper airway edema. Imaging was performed while in house and although there was small interval progression noted on CT Head and Neck on 9/25/14, his repeat CT head and neck on 10/17 showed stable disease. He was discharged from hospital on 10/20. An exception to protocol was made to allow Mr. Patel to receive steroids in house and he also received course of clindamycin. Today he presents to clinic with his wife and sister. He is currently on decadron 8 mg daily. He has had approximately 30-40% decrease in facial edema. He has some difficulty lifting his head and some of the edema in lower jaw may be dependent. He denies difficulty breathing at this time. He does endorse pain in the lower jaw and neck. He denies food intolerance with GT placed on last admission, but weight is decreased by  9# since starting cycle 1. He reports regular BM, no abdominal pain or diarrhea. He denies CP, LE edema. He endorses fatigue. He received C1D1 (carbo/taxol), C1D8 (taxol)  and C1D15 (taxol) on 8/28/14. Clinical trials were discussed and he ultimately signed consent for MK trial and received C1 9/19. Treatment course has been complicated by facial and upper airway edema, requiring exception to protocol and use of steroids. ASSESSMENT & PLAN:  Bhavesh Patel is a 46YO male with PMH of relapsed SCC of the L buccal mucosa s/p resection in March 2014 and adjuvant radiation therapy in May 2014 unresponsive to 1 cycle carbo/taxol currently s/p 2 doses of experimental protocol anti-PD1 pembrolizumab p/w worsening agitation, confusion, and increasing R-sided facial edema of 4 days duration, admitted for management of pain, confusion, and discussion of goals of care. 1. Agitation, disorientation    -May be steroid induced vs. metastases to the brain   -Last head CT 09-25-14; ordered head CT w/ IV contrast    Renal function WNL   -Per recommendations from palliative, switched from Ativan 0.5 mg PO q6h to Haldol IM 2.5 mg q8h   -Neuro consulted for recommendations regarding w/u and management of AMS    2. Facial and neck edema    -Differential of lymphatic invasion by tumor/local inflammation vs cellulitis     Likely tumor-related given h/o edema and lack of response to antibiotics in previous hospitalization    -Administer dexamethasone (8 mg IV push, q8h). Dosing per regimen from previous hospitalization (9-29 thru 10-20-14)    -Ordered neck soft tissue CT to evaluate    3. Tachycardia   -Cardiac exam WNL otherwise   -No signs of infection or sepsis thus far on imaging or PE   -Telemetry monitoring ordered to evaluate for arrhythmia    4. Relapsed and disseminated SCC     -Refractory to carbo/taxol and experimental MK-3475 therapy    -Consider discussion of goals of care with family and primary oncologist     5. Tracheostomy tube    -Patient removed tube on 10-23-14    -ENT replaced 10-24-14     6. Pain management    -Continue PCA hydromorphone, 0.2 mg/hr continuous IV, 2.3 mg per demand, changed limit to q15 min    -Continue at-home Fentanyl patches, 150 mcg/hr    -Naloxone IV push, 0.04-0.08 mg q5 min PRN     7. Regurgitation of G-tube feeds    -Abdominal radiograph read as non-concerning for ileus or SBO   -Surgery adjusted G tube placement to prevent leakage from around button   -Consult Gastrostomy nurse if further G-tube issues   -Currently taking esomeprazole (40 mg PO qam) as stress ulcer prophylaxis     F/E/N: 0.9 NS 125 mL/hr IVF/ Replete electrolytes PRN / NPO, continue G-tube feeds   IBCD/Prophylaxis:   Code Status: FULL, d/w with patient's wife   Dispo: consider discussion of goals of care with family    Discussed with senior resident, to be discussed with attending. On arrival at bedside, his respiratory rate had spontaneously fallen and saturations had returned to >98%, however the patient was noted to be significantly agitated, felt short of breath, and had significant belly breathing, despite obvious retractions in his neck. ENT was noted to have scoped the patient earlier in the day and did not find any mucous plugging at that time, but did see some consolidation down the right bronchial tree with purulence and a foul smell. X-ray also showed right sided infiltration and significant effusion. Patient was re-evaluated 30 minutes later and noted to still be in significant distress, but had more extensive use of accessory muscles and was tripoding, so he was transferred to the MICU in anticipation of further deterioration of his respiratory status that might require. Thoracentesis was performed in the unit and approximately 1.6L of fluid was removed; cytology and gram stain are pending and need to be followed up on. Approximately 30 minutes after thoracentesis, the patient's respiratory function greatly improved; respiratory rate fell to within  normal range, he had much less labored breathing, O2 requirement was weaned down to 40% and his saturations remained stable between 93-100%. Overnight, his condition remained stable and thus he was transferred back to the floor. |

Angela is a 62Yrs female with 100+ pack year history of tobacco use and recurrent/metastatic larynx SCCHN. Her oncologic history is outlined below. 5/18/2006 - larynx, epiglottis, biopsy: detached fragments of squamous cell carcinoma. Necrotic debris, keratin, and foreign body reaction. Chronic inflammation of squamous lined mucosa. Unequivocal evidence of stromal invasion is not present in this biopsy. 5/2006 - staged as T3N2b SCC which was originally in the epiglottis, extending down through the aryepiglotic fold to he left arytenoid and left false vocal cord. She underwent concurrent CRT at the Cancer Treatment Center in Zion, IL. She received carbo/cetuximab/docetaxel every 2 weeks x 2 cycles. She received 79.2 Gy, BID fractionation, completed 11/9/2006. She then received four more cycles of carbo/cetuximab/docetaxel. 12/31/2009 - local recurrence in R level II LN and underwent radical neck dissection. Left supraglottis, biopsy: no high grade dysplasia or carcinoma. 12th cranial nerve biopsy: invasive SCC. Right neck level 1 dissection: 0/2 LN with tumor. Right neck, levels IV/V, dissection: 0/5 LN with tumor. Right neck, levels II/III, dissection: invasive moderately differentiated SCC. Vascular space and PNI identified. Tumor involves anterior superior surgical resection margin. Metastatic SCC in 1/10 LN. 4/2011 - noticed swelling behind R ear that was growing quickly. FNA confirmed SCC confirming dermal metastasis. 9/9/2011 to 10/14/2011 - weekly cisplatin 20 mg/m2 + weekly taxol 30 mg/m2. Completed re-irradiation with concurrent chemotherapy to 74.4 G at 1.2 Gy BID for 62 fractions on 10/20/11. 4/2/2012 - skin, right neck, shave biopsy: superficial shave of SCC (at least in situ). 5/2/2012 - PET: intensely hypermetabolic R postauricular subepidermal and infra-auricular epidermal lesions c/w recurrent SCCA. Additional interval development of heterogeneous uptake along deep R parotid bed is worrisome for disease recurrence. 5/10/12 - WLE with full thickness skin graft. Pathology showed SCC in two nodules. 8/21/2012 to 12/7/2012 - carboplatin 490 mg every 3 weeks + weekly cetuximab 250 mg/m2 + 5-FU (EXTREME). 1/11/2013 to 5/17//2013 - maintenance cetuximab 500 mg/m2 every other week. 6/12/2013 - CT chest: stable subcentimeter pulmonary nodules compared to prior CT dating back to 9/2010. PEG in good position. 6/27/2013 to 9/5/2013 - cetuximab 250 mg/m2 every other week. Dose reduced for rash and neutropenia. 9/19/2013 - CT neck: slightly increased size of level II LN on the left, now measuring 1.4 cm. Clinically, she had growth in 3 nodules: behind the ear, neck, and angle of R jaw. 10/24/2013 to 2/27/2014 - cetuximab with 80 mg/m2 taxol every other week. 2/20/2014 - CT neck: at least 3 heterogeneously enhancing masses in the cranial R neck anterior and posterior to the expected location of the SCM. Largest in the posterior upper neck measures 22 x 22 x 23 mm. 2/20/14 - CT chest: grossly stable bilateral subcentimeter lung nodules. 3/6/2014 - most recent chemotherapy. Cetuximab 200 mg/m2 monotherapy. Most recent imaging and clinically with PD. Here to discuss further options. Has discussed MTX 50 mg/m2 or (b) carbo/5-FU as in past, or (c) increase cetuximab to full dosing or (d) weekly gemcitabine with his oncologist. Today, in clinic, patient denies pain. Reports weight as stable. Strictly NPO and using G-tube for nutrition and pills. Feels that right sided dermal metastasis is enlarging. Denies cough. Denies systemic symptoms. Denies cardiopulmonary symptoms. Denies neuropathy. Continues to be active with her daily activities with PS 1. |2014-03-26:	Please refer to initial consult note from 3/26/2014 for full details. |2014-05-28:	Angela Angela is a 63Yrs female here for follow-up of recurrent/metastatic larynx SCCHN with dermal metastases. |2014-06-28:	She presents today to screen for IRB 14-0212 Nivolumab vs Therapy of Choice for refractory Head and Neck Squamous Cell Carcinoma. |2014-07-05:	She presents today to initiate IRB 14-0212 Nivolumab vs Therapy of Choice for refractory Head and Neck Squamous Cell Carcinoma. |2014-07-11:	She is currently enrolled in the IRB 14-0212 Nivolumab clinical trial. Additional complaints:  -Denies any pain at this time and is not taking any pain medications. -She continues to have occasional bleeding and clear drainage from the tumor on her right neck. She changes the dressing over the tumor daily. -Weight is stable. Nothing by mouth. Currently tolerating 4 cans of Jevity through gtube daily. Energy level is good. Denies fever/chills/night sweats. No SOB, CP. Denies n/v/d/c. narrative: 2014-06-11:	Mark Castro is a 52Yrs male an HPV(+) aggressive locally rcurrent HNC  .Returns to clinical to discuss treatment plan and consider participation in anti-PD1 trial. Prior oncologic history includes:  Stage IVB T4aN2c HPV-positive SCC R tonsil s/p cis/RT with CR, with 1st recurrence with R neck LAD in 08.13 s/p R neck dissection and 2nd recurrence in 12.13 with a large R orbital tumor with ethmoid cell invasion, progressed on carbo/docetaxel and presenting for further management plans. In more detail, Mr. Castro initially started noticing a R neck mass approximately in 11.12. He was referred to an ENT specialist and a biopsy of a R tonsilar mass on 11.13.12 revealed p16-positive moderately differentiated SCC. Concurrent CRT with cis/RT was started on 12.27.12 till 2.22.13 (D1, 22,43) with a CR achieved. The patient was clinically and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus of SCC in fibrous tissue. On 12.23.13, the patient was found to have a 2nd recurrence with a R medial canthus biopsy c/w metastatic SCC. Additional biopsy from a R cheek skin lesion on 1.8.14 further confirmed SCC. He was started on carboplatin/docetaxel on 1.22.14 and was continued up 3 cycles till 3.12.14, when he was felt to have progressed clinically. His most recent CT neck on 4.4.14 showed enhancing soft tissue nodules involving the R face/neck dermis, superficial lobe of the R parotid gland and R orbit which had increased in size (c/t CT on 3.5.14). The R inferior medial orbital mass was shown to have increased from 3.9x3.3cm to  4.4x4.8cm, with extension of this mass into the adjacent anterior ethmoid air cells with bone destruction involving the lamina papyracea and the ethmoid air cell septa which is more prominent. The mass caused displacement of the globe to the right and mild worsening proptosis. The lesion at the inferior margin of the superficial lobe of the R parotid gland had also increased from 0.7x0.5cm to 1x3cm. Smaller dermal lesions of the R face and superficial lobe of the R parotid gland were also shown to have increased minimally. A soft tissue massin the pterygopalatine fossa and the posterior of the nasal cavity appeared to have increased minimally in size too. No tumor was seen in the T tonsil tumor bed.No neck LAD was noted either. CT chest on the same day was negative for metastatic disease in the lungs. Currently, the patient reports the following:   - nasal stuffiness   - xerostomia   - R eye "irritation", 2-3/10, requires 2 norcos (hydrocodonee 5mg/acetaminophen 325mg) prior to sleeping   - dysphagia   - weight loss, 50p since his diagnosis and 5p over the past 1 month   - fatigue    No past medical history on file. No Known |2014-06-25:	--Weight stable since 6/25/14. |2014-06-25:	Mark Castro is a 52Yrs male an HPV(+) aggressive locally rcurrent HNC  Returns to clinical to discuss treatment plan and consider participation in anti-PD1 trial. Had recent chemotherapy with Dr. Clark at Loyola, with cis/navelbine - tumor showed minor response, but side effects from treatment (navelbine dose and cycle 2 deferred due to weakness/pre-syncope). Now would like to switch treatment to anti-PD-1 study. Vision on right eye is still present although markedly impaired by local tumor lesions. He was started on carboplatin/docetaxel on 1.22.14 and was continued up 3 cycles  till 3.12.14, when he was felt to have progressed clinically. The R inferior medial orbital mass was shown to have increased from 3.9x3.3cm to 4.4x4.8cm, with extension of this mass into the adjacent anterior ethmoid air cells with bone destruction involving the lamina papyracea and the ethmoid air cell septa which is more prominent. |2014-07-14:	Mark Castro is a 52Yrs male with HPV(+) locally recurrent HNC. He has signed consent for the pembrolizumab/anti-PD-1 study and will start treatment after he has CT scans, a biopsy, and labs completed. Current complaints:  -Continues to have right eye pain and swelling. States the swelling has increased some since he was last seen in the clinic. Also reports chronic clear/yellow discharge from his right eye. Denies change in vision. States he has not been evaluated by an ophthalmologist. -Reports chronic dysphagia and odynophagia. -Pain managed with norco 5/325 1-2 tabs q 6hrs prn  -Dry mouth  -Eating a regular diet. Weight is stable since 6/25  -Low energy    Denies fever/chills. No n/v/d/c. Denies shortness of breath/chest pain. The patient was clinically and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus  of SCC in fibrous tissue. No past medical history on file. |2014-07-25:	Mark Castro is a 52Yrs male with stage IV T4aN2c HPV + SCC R tonsil with orbital metastasis. Now currently enrolled in the pembrolizumab/anti-PD-1 study. Today is C1D1. Current complaints:  -Continues to have right eye pain. Pain not relieved with current regimen of norco 5/325 1-2 tabs q 6hrs prn  -Reports increased swelling around right eye. Still has some vision in his right eye, but limited. Continues to have clear watery drainage from eye. -Weight stable since 6/25/14. Eating a regular diet. Reports decreased appetite. Has chronic dysphagia, but denies pain when swallowing. -Energy remains low. -Dry mouth    Denies fever/chills. Denies shortness of breath/chest pain, cough. The patient was clinically and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was  managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus of SCC in fibrous tissue. |2014-08-14:	Today is C2D1. Current complaints:  -Continues to have right eye pain - controlled with norco 10/325 1-2 tabs q 6hrs prn. Feels like swelling around eye has increased since last visit. Vision is very limited. -Reports severe frontal headaches since he was last seen. He contacted Dr. Seiwert regarding this and was prescribed morphine (pt not sure what dose). States headaches have since resolved and hasn't had to take morphine. -Weight is stable. -Energy level worsened after 1st tx of immune thereapy. Still able to perform ADLs. The patient was clinically  and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus of SCC in fibrous tissue. |2014-09-04:	Today is C3D1. Current complaints:  -Right eye swelling and dermal mets increasing in size. -Pain around right eye is worsening. Pt states pain is controlled with current regimen of morphine   -Lost 5 pounds since 8/13. Reports no appetite. Tolerating liquids po. Supplementing with 1-2 Boost per day. Has chronic dysphagia. -Energy level is worsening. Sleeping most of the day. Denies fever/chills. The patient was clinically and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level  II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus of SCC in fibrous tissue. |2014-09-19:	Had CT scans 9/19/2014. |2014-10-19:	Today is C5D1 of IRB 130311    Current complaints:  -Pt and wife feel that right eye mass and dermal mets have increased in size. -Pain around right eye is controlled with current regimen of morphine. Pt unsure of how much he is taking at this time. -Weight stable since last visit. Continues to report no appetite. Now receiving daily IVF at home of NS. -Energy level has improved slightly. Pt's wife reports he is sleeping less during the day. Feels IVF has increased his energy level. The patient was clinically and radiographically followed and he was found to have a 1st recurrence in  the R neck in 08.13 (PET/CT 7.30.13: 2 small foci of increased uptake in the R neck at level II cervical region-SUV 4.9-, ~ 1cm each) which was managed with a R neck dissection on 8.15.13 which showed 2/4 R level II/III LNs positive for metastatic SCC (max size 0.8cm) and a small focus of SCC in fibrous tissue. |2014-11-05:	Today is C4D1. Current complaints:  - Tumor again seems to grow  -Right eye swelling and dermal mets again increasing in size. -Pain is stable and is controlled with current regimen of morphine   -Energy level is poor but stable. On 12.23.13, the patient was found to have a 2nd  recurrence with a R medial canthus biopsy c/w metastatic SCC. |

The patient presents to the Head and Neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss treatment options. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. Mr. Dickerson was found to have a right neck mass in 2/2012, initially attributed to a dental infection that failed to resolve with treatment. 7/5/13 Pathology, FNA, right neck mass at angle of mandible - squamous cell carcinoma. Positive for ck5/6, p63, p16 in less than 20%    Unerwent oral biopsies 7/13/13 with no primary identified. PET CT showed right Level II lymph node involvement as well as likely involvement of bilateral Level III and Level IVs. Deferred clinical trial and started on concurrent Cisplatin/RT. 9/2013 PET Increased FDG-avidity of conglomerates right level 2 mass, slightly increased in size. Grossly stable satellite right level 2 and 3 subcentimeter lymph nodes. The mild fdg avid left neck lymph nodes appear less conspicuous, some has resolved. He underwent Rt neck dissection by Dr. Lydiatt 3/13/14 with 7/7 lymph nodes involved, 30-40% viable tumor remaining, ECE+. Post dissection, he developed neck edema requiring drain. He was evaluated by ENT in 6/2014 and noted to have a paralyzed Rt TVC and a 6cm firm, fixed Rt neck mass, likely unresectable. FNA of the mass showed SCCa. 6/10/14 Pathology, FNA, rick neck mass - poorly differentiated carcinoma. Positive for CK5/6 and nuclear p63     PET 6/12/14  Since 2,2014, unfavorable changes, with new and increased FDG avid right cervical neck conglomerate lymphadenopathy, extending through levels  II-III, with continuation to the skin surface. Right vocal cord paralysis. No appreciable lad in left neck. Over the past two months, his performance status is slowly declining. He has been spending over 50% of his time on the bed or couch. He had a peg tube placed during his treatment, and was maintaining some oral intake until 1 month ago, when he stopped this completely. He was directed to take 5 Jevity cans/day, but is only taking 3-4 and is slowly losing weight. Over the past few weeks he has developed new weakness and numbness in his right deltoid region - he thinks he slept on his arm wrong. He saw Dr. Eisner last week for a second opinion and was found to be hypercalcemic to 12. He was hospitalized and was treated for an aspiration pneumonia. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     James Lynch is a 66Yrs with history of DM, HTN, hypothyroidism, Afib presenting for consultation regarding newly diagnosed L BOT ca. He notes for the last 6 months he has had swelling L side of face. He saw PCP in Indiana who prescribed course of antibiotics for possible sinus infection. He noted transient improvement but symptoms recurred. He then had CT neck at Riverside Medical Center showed lobulated soft tissue mass in the left parapharyngeal space measuring 2.8 x 3.1 x 5.6 cm abutting the anteromedial margin of the left sternocleidomastoid muscle and the posterior belly of the left digastric muscle as well as a soft tissue prominence in the left glossopharyngeal recess. PCP suggested referral to tertiary care center for further work-up. He was referred to Dr. Portugal on 9/2. FNA of the periauricular neck mass showed atypical squamous cells. MRI neck ordered 9/16 which showed 3 x 4 x 6 cm parapharyngeal mass in the left neck medial to the left parotid gland and along the anterior medial aspect of the left sternocleidomastoid muscle with a small component of this mass which infiltrating into the deep lobe of the parotid as well as an apparent 2.5 cm apparent mass in the left base of tongue. He then underwent panendoscopy with Dr. Portugal on 9/16 with L BOT and tonsil biopsy. Level 2 neck excisional biopsy revealed invasive squamous cell carcinoma involving skeletal muscle and fibroadipose tissue. p16 positive. Base of tongue, left tonsil superior  pole, left tonsil inferior pole, and left lateral vallecula biopsies showed invasive squamous cell carcinoma. He was referred to medical oncology and radiation oncology for further discussion of treatment options. Today, he is doing well other than L cheek swelling which he feels is stable. He has healed well from biopsy with no pain. No trismus. No dysphagia or odynophagia. Denies change in voice. His family does note some decreased hearing. Appetite good with no weight loss. Energy good. Of note, he has a history of chewing tobacco for 20 years daily which he quit 5 years ago. He also has a history of cigar use - few cigars daily for 5 years quit 4-5 years ago. narrative: 2014-08-28:	8/28/14 CT neck with contrast -- Right jugulodigastric and right posterior triangle adenopathy. |2014-09-10:	Il and underwent panendoscopy on 9/10/14. |2014-09-16:	Rick Swanberg is a 53Yrs male with cancer of the base of tongue. The patient presents to the H&N medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss initial treatment. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. Mr. Swanberg noticed a lump in his right neck for the past year. He recently went to his primary care physician to have this evaluated. 8/28/14 CT neck with contrast - Right jugulodigastric and right posterior triangle adenopathy. The largest of these in the level II right jugulodigastric chain measuring 2.5cm. He was prescribed Augmentin with no improvement in his lymphadenopathy. He was referred to Brian Farrell, ENT at Orland Park, Il and underwent panendoscopy on 9/10/14. He noticed an exophytic 2x2cm mass at base of tongue that was biopsied and returned positive for malignancy. He currently denies any weight loss, fevers, chills, night sweats. He has a good appetite and remains very active. He has no dysphagia. His only issue has been anxiety since his diagnosis, which is controlled with intermittent Xanax. No evidence of acute ischemic or hemorrhagic lesion. MRI Orbits WWO (10/24/15): IMPRESSION:  1. An intraocular mass on the left has increased in size from the prior examination. Given the clinical history of head and neck cancer, the findings are concerning for a  metastatic lesion. In addition, there is diffuse left choroidal inflammation with a mild degree of  choroidal detachment suspected at least on the left, with or without subchoroidal  bleeding. Generalized left orbital inflammation is seen both intraconally and  extraconally. A 6 mm enhancing lesion within the left anterior cerebellum is partially visualized on  this examination. Dedicated contrast enhanced brain MRI is recommended to assess for the  possibility of intracranial metastases. CT Neck Soft Tissue W 10/25/15:   IMPRESSION:   1. narrative: 2010-03-01:	March 2010 -- L tonsillectomy showing tonsillar ca. |2010-07-01:	He was treated with Cisplatin + 5FU + RT summer of 2010. |2012-08-01:	August 2012 underwent radical L neck dissection. |2012-10-01:	October 2012-- December 2012 was referred to Dr. Brockstein at Northshore where he was treated with cetuximab + RT. |2012-12-01:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2014-09-10:	Last dose 9/10/14. |2014-09-23:	Patrick Goheen is a 56Yrs male here for consultation regarding recurrent L tonsillar ca with mets to lung. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:     Patrick Goheen is a 56Yrs with history of recurrent L tonsillar ca with know metastases to lung presenting for consultation regarding further treatment options. Oncologic history - Unfortunately, we do not have records available at today's visit. History obtained from patient report. March 2010 - L tonsillectomy showing tonsillar ca, HPV+. CT following this showed small residual disease in L lymph node. Course was complicated by renal failure briefly requiring dialysis. He did not have follow up scans following this given concern of IV contrast in setting of renal failure. In 2012, he was noted to have pain in his neck and self palpated a lump. He was referred to ENT for LN biopsy again in L neck and was found to have a recurrence. August 2012 underwent radical L neck dissection   October 2012- December 2012 was referred to Dr. Brockstein at Northshore where he was treated with cetuximab + RT   He reports a CT Neck/Chest following completion of treatment with no evidence of disease. Summer 2013 - noted to have a lesion in chest on routine imaging. Biopsy proven SCC consistent with initial H&N Ca  He was then started on clinical trial of Tivantinib + Cetuximab with stable disease for several months. Repeat CT Neck/Chest 9/10 revealed small amount of growth in chest. No new lesions. Today, he feels overall well. He is still working and playing golf on a regular basis. No fevers or chills. Also reports her speech has become more unclear and that swallowing has become more difficult. Feels short of breath at times at night due to mucous production, but overall breathing without any difficulty during the day. - Continues to report serosanguinous drainage from tumor. Changing dressing multiple times/day. - Pain is stable and controlled with fentanyl 100mcg patch, Norco 7.5/325 q 4hr prn, and gabapentin 300mg TID. - Receiving 2-3 cans of Nutren 2.0 (500 calories per can) and through her gtube daily. States she is able to swallow liquids only. Oncologic History:  - 1998 SCC of the tongue - chemoradiotherapy - 5-FU/cisplatin/radiation. 14-day cycle 5 days on/5 days off, 7 cycles = 14 weeks (Payne / Sam Taylor / Greim). CR  - 9 months later 1999 - tumor recurs on tongue small lesion - biopsy - carcinoma in situ. Multiple sequential biopsies for almost 2 years  - ~2000 resection - right mandible and part of the tongue, Neck dissection (Hutchison/Neilson), titanium plates  - 2003 tissue breakdown and fibula free flap  - 2013 right lower neck/sternocleidoid area recurrence. 11/2013 Surgical removal of ~1 cm lesion, 12/2013-1/2014 adjuvant chemoradiation (?? ?/cisplatin)  - 2014 left mandibular necrosis - chronic infection. 6/2014 biopsy positive for tumor on left mandible  - 6-7/2014 rapid spread within head and neck area to contralateral side   - 8/2014 cetuximab, marked response, but PD in late November/early December. Last dose 12/1/2014  Most symptoms left neck with tumor breaking through skin and related pain. Also hearing on left side. Recent biopsy - HPV negative  Recent CT scans 11/18/2014      No past medical history on file. |2015-01-22:	Rosemarie J Towler is a 55Yrs female with recurrent HNSCC of the tongue, on IRB 140212 clinical trial with Nivolumab. She denies any fevers/chills. She also feels like left neck mass is increasing in size. Swallowing has become more difficult and her speech has become more unclear. - Receiving 3 cans of Nutren 2.0 (500 calories per can) through her gtube daily. All nutrition and medications are through her gtube due to worsening dysphagia. Weight stable since last visit. - Energy remains low  - Having regular BMs with senekot  - Also reports frontal headaches which have been going on for several months and not worsening. Denies fevers/chills, n/v/d/c. He was initially found to have a lump in the right neck in 2011. Underwent surgical resection and was found to have squamous cell cancer. Primary site identified as right tonsil. Final stage not in records, but either stage IVa or IVb. Underwent cetuximab/RT in 2011 at Cancer Treatment Centers of America. Developed local recurrence 2 years later, and in the right side of the neck. Felt to be without evidence of disease. Did not receive a second course of radiation as he had it previously. Completed reconstruction with supraclavicular flap. Due to limited jaw opening, he was started on induction with carboplatin/taxol/cetuximab for 2 cycles. Path specimen did not comment on PNI or LVI. He had a neck wound which separated, but seems to be well managed. There is no drainage. He is referred for consideration for re-irradiation. He otherwise feels well today. Now off anticoagulation (prior hx of DVT/PE). Notes good energy, appetite, weight. Denies cardiopulmonary symptoms. Denies neuropathy. Has a G-tube which he uses for feedings (100% calories from G tube). Able to take clear liquid by mouth. Functionally active. The patient presents to the thoracic medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and recommendations on management. Clinically he is doing well and denies any acute complaints. He denies any neck pain, dysphagia, odynophagia or ear pain/fullness. His weight has been stable and he continues to have good appetite. He denies any issues with fatigue and continues to work full time as an IT project manager and care for his wife who has Alzheimer's. He denies fever, chills, night sweats, CP, SOB, N/V, abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, LE edema. ONCOLOGY HISTORY (per EMR confirmed by Patient)  2002: noted non-tender right neck nodule  ~2003: underwent partial right modified radical neck dissection for palpable right neck node. No primary identifiable. No further treatment. Per notes, there was a solitary node involved. 2005: noticed right neck mass  11/1/05: right neck FNA negative for malignant cells  12/5/05: right tongue base biopsy demonstrated squamous cell carcinoma. Final stage uncertain, but suspect Stage IV based on nodal disease. 1/18/06 to 3/7/06: he underwent chemoradiation followed by surgical resection and neck dissection (concomitant cisplatin 100 mg/m2 q 21d and 70/60/54 Gy in 35 fractions over 48 days using IMRT, Dr. Henry Wagner PennState Hershey)  5/22/06: right base of tongue biopsy negative for carcinoma, right neck scar excision negative for carcinoma, and right neck soft tissue mass negative for carcinoma. He also underwent panendoscopy which was negative for malignancy. 5/21/07: right base of tongue biopsy negative for malignancy  2007 to 2008: no evidence of disease on serial imaging   ~1/2015: noticed left sided neck swelling. He went to an outside ENT and underwent CT, PET, and FNA of L neck mass. There is a heterogeneously enhancing mass is present along the right glossopharyngeal arcade inferior to the retromolar trigone and partially invading the base of the right hemitongue contiguously extending laterally into the left parapharyngeal fat plane contacting the masticator muscles without mandibular invasion measuring up to 2.5 cm. Isolated left level 2A lymph node measuring 2 x 1.5 x 2.2 cm with extracapsular invasion. 2/3/15: PET/CT demonstrated hypermetabolic mass along the left half of the nasopharynx (SUV 8.2), a right base of tongue mass with hypermetabolic activity SUV 22.5, a necrotic left level 2A lymph node with SUV 6.0, and a right posterior triangle lymph node SUV 5.7. There is also uptake in the region of the right torus tubarius SUV 8.3. There were also a few soft tissue nodules in the mesenteric fat with varying degrees of hypermetabolic activity ranging from 0 to 16.2 which were read as concerning for recurrent lymphoma. 2/6/15: FNA of left neck lymph node demonstrated metastatic squamous cell carcinoma    Patient Active Problem List   Diagnosis    Malignant neoplasm of tip and lateral border of tongue (CANCER)    Recurrent tongue cancer    Hx of cholecystectomy    Hypothyroidism    Hx of tonsillectomy    HTN (hypertension) |2015-03-15:	William Blong is a 56Yrs male with recurrent tongue/retromolar trigone SCC on re-irradiation clinical trial with abraxane (IRB 121554). with history of squamous cell CA with 2  Further recurrences. At the time of diagnosis the patient did not have an identifiable primary. Final pathology revealed the primary tumor in the left tonsil with multiple positive LN in the left neck with evidence of ECE. We have no record of p16 staining; however, the tumor tested positive for high risk HPV. The patient received adjuvant chemotherapy under the direction of Dr. Herbert Reisel together with adjuvant radiation under the care of Dr. James Ruffer. The 3rd cycle of bolus cisplatin was held secondary to local side effects in the radiation field. Per the patient, he lost roughly 30 lbs over the course of his CRT. He recovered completely from his prior CRT. PET-CT performed at an OSH on 9/12/2014 revealed FDG avidity at the site of pain/swelling on the left with an associated mass at the left skull base with involvement of the vertebral artery and likely CN X, XI, and XII. The patient's pain is now improved considerably with the addition of narcotics and PO steroid. Inferiorly this mass extends up to the tail of the parotid gland with loss of intervening fat plane. Findings consistent with known recurrent squamous cell carcinoma. This lesion extends into the left stylomastoid foramen with subtle enhancement along the mastoid segment of the left facial nerve which may represent perineural spread." At that point, he received TomoTherapy IMRT-SIB plan to gross recurrent disease, high-risk CTV, and low-risk CTV to 69.96 Gy, 59.4 Gy, and 54 Gy in 33 fractions completed on 11/13/2014, . Further, MRI of the skull base on 2/19/15 demonstrated interval increase size of signal abnormality in the left sided skull base. Inferiorly, it extended down to the left carotid bifurcation with increased infiltration into the adjacent paraspinal muscles and into the occipital bone and the inferior aspect of the petrous temporal bone. There was mild edema in the left masticator space, left parotid gland and along the superificial soft tissues of left lower cheek with associated mild fat stranding. There was stable mild enhancement along the mastoid segment of the left facial nerve. PET/CT on the same day demonstrated interval development of hypermetabolic left level II lymph node. There was mild to moderately decreasing metabolic activity in the known soft tissue thickening/ lesion with underlying bone destruction in the left stylomastoid region. CT of the neck earlier today demonstrated a necrotic mass at the left carotid bifurcation with partial encasement of the proximal left internal carotid artery, corresponding to the increased uptake seen on PET. He comes to our office today with a PS of 0, complaining of intermittent spasms of left neck/face pain. He is being able to keep his weight. Patient currently takes cymbalta 30 mg, gabapenting 900 mg TID, oral dilaudid 8 mg and oxycontin 20 mg BID. The oral dialudid and oxycontin are new additions to his regimen. Pt states he has tried lidocaine patches before without relief. How does your pain affect    your sleep? Decreased    hours per night? 6 hrs. your appetite? Decreased    your physical activity? The patient presents to the head and neck cancer medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management of his disease. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. 2/19/15 - PCP noted left neck mass during a routine exam. On the same day, underwent an ultrasound demonstrating a 4.4x2.3x3.2cm left upper neck LN with adjacent LN measuring 1.4x0.8x1.5cm just inferior to the submandibular gland. (In retrospect, he notes he was having some dysphagia that was developing around this time that has since worsened.) 2/23/15 - CT neck demonstrated asymmetric mucosal thickening of the left base of tongue and piriform sinus. Masslike appearance of the mucosa extending into the left vallecula and crossing midline, measuring 3.5x1.6x2.5cm. A large left cervical LN measured 4.3x3.6x2.7cm with smaller adjacent lymph nodes. There were a few right sided LNs, but all measured less than 10mm. 2/27/15 - biopsy, submandibular lymph node - SCC (per pt, no report available). Dr. Gregory Schwartz at Porter Memorial Hospital in Indiana. 3/9/15 - PET/CT - hypermetabolic left BOT mass and left cervical LN conglomerate (no report available). Currently, he states he is doing well. His weight is stable, he is staying active. He does note his dysphagia is slowly worsening since his diagnosis. He denies any pain from his neck mass. narrative: 2015-02-01:	February 2015: Increased snoring and 10 lb weight loss prompted visit to ENT in northern Indiana. |2015-03-18:	He had a CT scan on 3/18/15 that showed a 2.6x4.1x3.5 cm right tonsillar mass and a 1.7x2.1x2.1 right cervical LN with central necrosis. |2015-03-21:	3/21/15: CT neck at Franciscan Alliance Hospital showed right tonsilar mass 2.6 x 3.5 x 4.1cm. |2015-03-23:	3/23/15: Right tonsil biopsy at OSH showed keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. |2015-03-26:	3/26/15: Seen in consult by Dr. Portugal. |2015-04-03:	4/3/15: Panendoscopy by Dr. Portugal showed no suspicious lesions other than known oropharynx cancer. |2015-04-03:	He has some pain in the Ln with radiation to the ear.The patient had triple endoscopy on 4/3/15 that showed the right tonsillar lesion that was sitting within the tonsillar fossa and occupying the entire tonsillar fossa with no extension beyond the tonsillar fossa and no involvement of the base of tongue. |2015-04-06:	Referral for tonsillar SCC    HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:   53-year-old male patient referred for tonsillar SCC. Initially was noted by his wife to have increased snoring and a 10 lb weight loss (was on a diet). He was referred to an ENT and underwent an office biopsy revealing squamous cell cancer of the right tonsil that was HPV positive. He has no aspiration symptoms. This actually looks like a conglomerate of LN. He has some pain in the Ln with radiation to the ear.The patient had triple endoscopy on 4/3/15 that showed the right tonsillar lesion that was sitting within the tonsillar fossa and occupying the entire tonsillar fossa with no extension beyond the tonsillar fossa and no involvement of the base of tongue, and onlydisplacement of the soft palate, but no evidence of tumor invading the mucosa of the soft palate. There was no lateral pharyngeal wall extension. He has no fatigue and has been eating well with no dysphagia. |2015-04-20:	Douglas Matthias is a 53Yrs male with T2N2bMx HPV+ right tonsillar SCC, starting induction chemotherapy with carbo/abraxane today (on OPTIMA clinical trial). States he is feeling well today. Reports bleeding from tumor site one day last week. No bleeding since. Continues to report mild right sided neck pain that radiates to his right ear. Pain is controlled with ibuprofen as needed. Also reports decreased hearing in his right ear. He is eating well and has gained 6 pounds since he was last seen. Tolerates a regular diet PO and denies dysphagia/odynophagia. Reports good energy levels. Denies fevers/chills, n/v/d/c, sob, neuropathy, tinnitus. Onc History:  February 2015: Increased snoring and 10 lb weight loss prompted visit to ENT in northern Indiana. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss possible clinical trial options. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. Mr. Harnett was originally diagnosed with T2N1M0 epiglottis cancer in 2010. He was treated with induction chemotherapy followed by radiation and did well afterwards until the summer of 2014 when he began developing tongue pain, weight loss, and decreased appetite. A PET scan was done which showed recurrent disease of the right tongue and tongue base. 6/2014 - PET scan - increased uptake in the oral cavity to the right of the midline contiguous to the lateral aspect of the tongue. 17.6x33.8mm. Multifocal uptake in the bilateral lower anterior hemithorax at the pleural interface corresponding to calcified plaque formation. He underwent resection of his tongue. 7/28/15 - Pathology - right hemiglossectomy and portion of tongue base - invasive moderately differentiated keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma. Level 1,2, and 3 lymph nodes negative. P16 IHC stain is negative. He was started on therapy with carboplatin/taxol/erbitux. He has tolerated this well, with only a few delays due to fatigue. He was treated with this therapy until 2-3 weeks ago. Around 2 weeks ago he began developing skin lesions along his neck that have increased rapidly in size. They are causing compression due to mass effect. He states his quality of life is miserable. He is constantly coughing up secretions. Imaging shows -      5/29/2015 - CT scan - Recurrent oral tumor along the flap with adjacent necrotic submandibular lymph nodes. Nonspecific rim enhancing fluid collection in the left parapharyngeal space which may represent sequela of treatment, necrotic nodes, or potential abscess. Extensive neck edema and laryngeal edema related to treatment. Stable spiculated left upper lobe nodule. He has developed some tongue swelling during this time, which he has been getting treatment with prednisone (last dose 2 days ago). This was helping with the swelling somewhat. Other than the skin lesions, he is doing okay. He remains active. He drives his wife to work and is working around the house most of the day. His weight is stable with g-tube feeds. Dr. Joy Coleman for radiation. - Regular f/u every 4-8 weeks, NED until  - 9/2014 Noticed pain right hip - noticed to have bone metastasis with risk of fractured. - Oct 2014 surgery with rod placement per Dr. Peabody, followed by radiation Dec 2014 with Dr. Dean Conterato at Condell. - Spring 2015 PET scan - all clear  - 8/2015 2nd PET scan - activity in the femur + spots in the lung (too small to biopsy) + recurrent right hip pain  Also had back pain  - Started carboplatin/paclitxel + Cetuximab (Extreme) 9/9/2015 - Had PORT place   - feeling better maybe because of back pain improved with Steroid co-medication  - Finished Chemotherapy in February 9th, 2016  - PET on 5/16/2016 with PD and new lesions. - 6/22/16: Started Nivo/Kir study. narrative: 2015-10-21:	Mark Hardesty is a 66Yrs male who presents to the University of Chicago Medical Center for a history of pT2N2bM0 poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the left base of the tongue, now recently found to be metastatic to the lung. Mr. Hardesty's oncologic history is as follows:     He first completed treatment with concurrent chemoradiotherapy (cisplatin + RT) in January 10, 2014. He recently developed swelling in the face and the upper left neck and left submandibular region; he was treated with a course of antibiotic therapy after examination by his radiation oncologist Dr. McGee did not demonstrate any recurrent disease. The antibiotics did not help and a CT scan was performed on August 19, 2015 which demonstrated edematous thickening and stranding of the supraglottic structures consistent with post-treatment changes but also demonstrated some new non-enlarged lymph nodes in the left supraclavicular region which were felt to most likely represent reactive changes. This scan also demonstrated some paratracheal lymph nodes and a CT chest was subsequently done for these findings. This CT chest showed a new dominant solid-appearing nodule in the right lower lobe with ground glass nodule in the left lower lobe as well as some peribronchial nodularity in the inferior lingula. There was an increased number and slightly increased prominence of multiple small right and left paratracheal lymph nodes. A follow up PET was done on August 31, 2015 which showed a hypermetabolic right lower lobe pulmonary nodule and mediastinal lymph nodes which were suspicious for malignancy. He had some low level uptake within the nodular opacities and the lingula which were felt to be post inflammatory. Bronchial washings did not show malignancy but biopsy of the left  paratracheal nodes showed squamous cell carcinoma that was positive for p63, CK5/7, and high risk HPV. TTF1 was negative. The right lower lung BAL was negative for malignant cells. Right paratracheal lymph node biopsy did not show any abnormal lymphocyte population. Right paratracheal biopsy also showed squamous cell carcinoma. Today he is accompanied by his wife. He overall feels quite well other than the persistent swelling on the left side of his neck. He has had some persistent hoarseness as well. He has an excellent energy level and only intermittently becomes short of breath. He has been seen locally in Peoria where his oncologist is attempting to enroll him on a nivolumab trial, however a requirement of this trial is receiving standard of care cytotoxic therapy in the 6 months prior to the trial which he has not received. He and his wife are currently petitioning the drug company to enroll on this trial. He has also been seen at MD Anderson where the MEDI0562 Phase I trial was offered to him. He has a spot in this trial if he would like it - he was told the chance of success with this trial is very high and the drug is likely to be approved per their report. He has also been offered a standard of care treatment consisting of carboplatin + cetuximab + 5FU or carboplatin + cetuximab + taxane based therapy which he could receive in Peoria. He is interested in getting a third opinion here at UCMC today and also to see if there are any treatments available here. He is willing to travel here if necessary. He also is curious about prognosis - he was told his prognosis is somewhere between 6-8 months. Patient Active Problem List   Diagnosis    Squamous cell carcinoma of tongue    GERD (gastroesophageal reflux disease)    Seasonal allergies    Erectile dysfunction |2015-10-28:	Most recently he has been approved for nivolumab off label in Peoria and is set up to receive this infusion tomorrow. He has come down with a sinus infection and has started on TMP/SMX for this. He is accompanied by his wife today and they have a number of questions regarding nivolumab side effects and treatment. |2019-11-23:	He also is curious about prognosis -- he was told his prognosis is somewhere between 6--8 months. |

Ms. Sanders presented with presented to OSH PCP with facial and neck swelling and given antibiotics without relief. She then presented with acute worsening in swelling of her tongue and shortness of breath, felt to be angioedema secondary to ACE inhibitor. However during this work-up, she underwent CT neck (4/25/15) demonstrating extensive, partially necrotic adenopathy in right neck at submandibular, internal jugular deep cervical chain extending inferiorly to level of right clavicle (full read below). On 5/5/15, she underwent core needle biopsy of right neck lymph node. This was consistent with "malignant epithelioid neoplasm consistent with metastatic cancer." She underwent further staging with direct laryngoscopy 5/28/15, final stage pT2N3 (patholgoy below) supraglottic squamous cell carcinoma. At the beginning of June 2015, a Gtube was placed. She was evaluated with radiation (Dr. Michael Spiotto) and medical oncology (Dr. Lucy Chen) with recommendation for definitive chemoradiation with cisplatin 100mg/m2 Day 1, 22, 43 and 33 treatments of radiation (region treated PTV1, daily fraction 212cGy; PTV2, daily fraction 180cGy). On  7/6/15 she started chemo/radiation completed 8/19/15; course was complicated by nausea, skin irritation (grade 3 desquamation), and grade 2-3 mucositis and she only had 2 rounds of chemotherapy at day 1 and 22. Per patient, at that time, she was also diagnosed with a LLE DVT (no documentation at time of consultation regarding this event, however, per patient she needed IV blood thinners via left groin sheath and ultrasound of her heart). She was sent home on Lovenox which she d/c'd because she had worsening LE swelling which she attributed to the drug; no easy bleeding or bruising aside from expected abdominal swelling. Her oncologist had told her to continue this medication. On 9/5/15, she presented to the ED with stridor and difficulty breathing and started on steroids for suspected laryngeal edema; per report she underwent laryngoscopy at that time demonstrating airway narrowing with an exophytic mass although notes mention a "seemingly complete locoregional response". She is completing her steroid taper this week. Further work-up was consistent with 9/9/15 CT chest demonstrating new R axillary retropectoral lymph node suspicious for metastasis which was biopsied 9/18/15 and showed metastatic squamous cell carcinoma. 10/5 PET scan also concerning for inguinal lymph node involvement, residual vocal cord disease, right axillary lympadenopathy (read below). Recommendation at UIC was for palliative chemotherapy or second opinion. She went to see her PCP at Rush University for second opinion who referred them to the University of Chicago for consideration of clinical trials and further chemotherapy. Over past months states that she has felt OK. Notes some dyspnea when eating. She does cough when she eats, does not feel like she is chocking. Her weight is variable; states she was 237lbs at diagnosis and now 217lb,  but has remained stable over the past month. She supplements with 2-3 cans of Jevity 1.5 to maintain her weight. She tries to drink 2-3 bottles of water and also gets 4 syringe flushes water with each can of Jevity. Notes normal frequency of urination. She notes that she has good BM's 1-2/week, but this has always been her routine. She denies pain complaints, takes Tylenol for occasional headache. Completing decadron taper currently. narrative: 2014-09-01:	radical prostatectomy in Sept. 2014. |2015-10-01:	Date of Diagnosis: 10/2015. |2015-10-06:	10/6/15: CT Neck w/ contrast. |2015-10-06:	10/6/15: CT --> 1.3 x 1.9 cm mass of right lateral base of tongue; conglomerate right level 2A mass 3 x 1.5 cm; multiple additional nodes at right level 2A. |2015-10-09:	10/9/15: NM PET Scan:(summary of findings). |2015-10-09:	10/9/15: PET --> Hypermetabolism at right side of base of tongue (SUV 13.2). |2015-10-14:	10/14/15: CT chest w/ contrast:(summary of findings) No definite pulmonary metastases are identified. |2015-10-14:	10/14/15: CT chest --> no metastatic disease. |2015-10-26:	Philip Enquist is a 63Yrs old male patient  who presents with recently diagnosed p16+ squamous cell carcinoma of the right base of tongue/tonsil. He had noticed some intermittent sore throat over the past year and then over the past 6 months has noticed swelling in the R neck- he saw ENT at NorthShore  2 weeks ago for further evaluation and was found to have a mass on the right base of tongue. He had FNA of the R neck lymph node which showed squamous cell carcinoma, p16 positive. He reports that he is feeling reasonably well and denies ongoing throat pain, dysphagia, otalgia or shortness of breath. He reports that energy level is stable. PS 0. His past medical history is significant for prostate cancer (Gleason 3+4 per patient history) s/p radical prostatectomy in Sept. 2014. Images:    10/6/15: CT Neck w/ contrast  (summary of findings) : the nasopharynx is unremarkable. There is a 1.3 x 1.9cm enhancing mass of the R lateral base of tongue. It likely measures at least 1.9cm in craniocaudal dimension and may slightly invade the R posterior lateral aspect of the right genioglossus muscle. It also abuts the medial margin of the R hyoglossus muscle which could be invaded by the mass. The mass does not cross the midline. It does extend to the right glossotonsillar sulcus. The hypopharynx, larynx and visualized proximal trachea are unremarkable. Cervical soft tissues: there is pathologic R cervical lymphadenopathy. There is a conglomerate right level 2A nodal station mass measuring approximately 3 x 1.5cm and there are areas of central and gliosis within this mass. Portion of this right level 2A nodal station lymph node mass abuts and is inseprable from the medial margin of the right sternocleidomastoid muscle. This R level 2A nodal station LN mass also  abuts and moderately effaces the proximal R IJ vein. A portion abuts the proximal R external carotid artery. There are multiple additional lymph nodes reported at right level 2A, R 3 and at R 3/4 nodal station- several lymph nodes prominently enhancing and findings most consistent w/ metastatic lymphadenopathy. 10/9/15: NM PET Scan:(summary of findings)  Hypermetabolism on the right side of the base of the tongue w/ associated mass (SUV 13.2)  is consistent with malignancy. Hypermetabolism in R level 2A/2B cervical lymph nodes and in a right cervical node at the border of levels 3 and 4. No other  Areas of abnormal hypermetabolism are demonstrated. CT images demonstrate no lung nodules within the limitations of the nonbreath-hold CT technique which is not optimized to detect micronodules. There is a low attenuation lesion in there right kidney, adrenals and pancreas appear normal w/in the limitations of the low dose noncontrast CT technique. There are 2 small hypervascular lesion seen within the liver and one small cystic lesion within the spleen. These are felt to be most likely to be benign even in this patient w/ a known malignancy. The patient presented to his ENT on 11/6/2015, at which time he complained of progressive difficulty swallowing to the point of choking on liquids. He has been resistant to this given significant burden associated with disfiguring surgery. The patient endorses significant pain related to radiation mucositis v tumor burden. He also has lost significant weight: 8 pounds over the past month, and a total of 40 pounds since diagnosis. The patient was started on steroids for his dysphagia. narrative: 2015-10-01:	10/2015: Presented with right neck mass. |2015-10-16:	The patient presented to his PCP on 10/16/2015 with a right neck mass. |2015-10-28:	10/28/15: FNA of right neck mass --> suspicious for malignancy. |2015-10-28:	Therefore on 10/28/2015. |2015-10-28:	Dr. Mulder of ENT on 10/28/2015. |2015-11-01:	Date of Diagnosis: 11/2015. |2015-11-02:	On 11/2/2015. |2015-11-02:	11/2/15: CT --> Prominence of right tonsillar pillar and a 2.8 x 2.4 x 4.0 cm level II lymph node in right neck. |2015-11-05:	The patient received a PET/CT on 11/5/2015. |2015-11-05:	11/5/15: PET --> Tonsillar and right neck lesions described above were FDG avid. |2015-11-11:	New diagnosis of head and neck cancer, likely R tonsillar cancer     HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:   The patient presented to his PCP on 10/16/2015 with a right neck mass. He stated he noticed it about 10 days prior to presentation. He was given a course of Augmentin without resolution. He was evaluated by  Dr. Mulder of ENT on 10/28/2015. He received a flexible laryngoscopy in clinic, which was without evidence of mass or lesion in the nasopharynx, oropharynx, supraglottis, glottis, or hypopharynx. Therefore on 10/28/2015, the patient received an FNA of a right neck mass. Cytology was read as: "Suspicious for malignancy. Predominantly necrotic material and scattered dysplastic squamous cells, highly suspicious for malignancy. Correlate clinically." On 11/2/2015, the patient received a CT neck w/wo contrast. This demonstrated a 2.8x2.4x4.0cm heterogenous solid enhancing mass in level II of the right neck. Also seen was asymmetric prominence of the right tonsillar pillar compared to the left. The patient received a PET/CT on 11/5/2015, which demonstrated a Level II mass that was FDG avid, as well as asymmetric uptake within the right tonsillar pillar relative to the left, corresponding to recent CT. This was thought to be consistent with a primary right tonsillar neoplasm, with a single metastatic 4cm lymph node of the right neck. The patient denied pain, dysphagia, odonophagia, otalgia, cough, hemoptysis, voice change, weight loss. Extensive history of tobacco use (1/2-1.5 PPD x 45 years). |2015-11-19:	11/19/15: Right tonsillar biopsy --> SCC. |2015-11-25:	HPI    He reports he is doing well since his last visit. narrative: 2015-10-20:	She underwent FNA biopsy of both lesions on 10/20/15. |2015-10-23:	CT neck was then performed on 10/23/15 which showed an asymmetric prominence of the right tonsil and a right 3.0cm level 2A node. |2015-11-04:	PET/CT on 11/4/15 showed hypermetabolic activity in the right tonsil. |2015-11-17:	Susie Kelly is a 58Yrs female with recently diagnosed papillary thyroid carcinoma and imaging findings concerning for tonsillar carcinoma that presents to establish care. The patient first noted a tedner right neck mass in early October. She was given antibiotics with no improvement. She subsequently underwent neck u/s which revealed a 3.0cm right level 2B node and a 1.3cm right thyroid nodule with poorly defined margins suspicious for extracapsular invasion. The thyroid nodule was found to be papillary thyroid carcinoma. The right cervical node showed only atypical cells. PET/CT on 11/4/15 showed hypermetabolic activity in the right tonsil, right submandibular node and right upper pole of the thyroid. No other lesions were identified. Findings were concerning for 2 primaries, a papillary thyroid carcinoma and possible right tonsillar carcinoma. She has been receiving care at Northwestern and was advised to undergo a right tonsillectomy and modified radical right nodal dissection. She was seen by our ENT colleagues for second opinion and underwent repeat FNA of the right submandibular node with pathology pending. She is now presenting to medical oncology for further evaluation. narrative: 2015-11-19:	PET scan was performed on 11/19/2015. |2015-11-25:	Dr. Haraf performed a laryngoscopy on 11/25/2015. |2015-12-02:	New diagnosis SCC of oropharynx     HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: 48 y/o M presents with recently diagnosed SCC of the head and neck, likely right tonsillar primary mass. The patient first presented in March with swelling of the right neck, and was given a prescription for antibiotics by his PCP, with subsequent improvement. He then again presented in late summer with worsened apnea symptoms and heavy, wheezing breathing. At that time he received a CT scan of the neck, which demonstrated a 3.2 cm right oropharynx mass, with two right cervical lymph nodes. Biopsy was performed in October, which was consistent with squamous cell carcinoma. We do not have access to this report currently, but it reportedly showed an FDG avid primary of the oropharynx with FDG avid ipsilateral nodes (2). Dr. Haraf performed a laryngoscopy on 11/25/2015, which demonstrated: a mass present in the soft palate, visible from the oropharynx. The tumor began at the midline and extended down the right tonsil, displacing the uvula. Repeat CT scans have been performed as below. Regarding his symptoms, the patient is able to maintain sufficient PO intake, and is not loosing any weight. He denies any dyspnea, though occasionally has sleep apnea. He denies any pain. Denies nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, sores in the oral cavity. Interestingly the patient reports he had swollen lymph nodes in 2011 at which time he received a biopsy, which was consistent only with inflammatory changes. |2015-12-09:	Lamar Thomas is a 48Yrs male here for follow-up of R T3N2b soft palate/OP HPV+ SCCHN.
