narrative: 2015-11-24:	11/24/15 -- Flexible fiberoptic exam -- lesion in left BOT. |2015-11-25:	11/25/15 -- CT neck -- mass within the vallecula at the BOT on the left. |2015-12-15:	12/15/15 -- BOT biopsy -- sections show infiltrating moderately well differentiated SCC and squamous mucosa. |2015-12-23:	12/23/2015: CT chest w/ contrast (performed at OSH. |2016-01-06:	Myong Kim is a 63Yrs male with p16+ cT2N0-1Mx BOT SCC. The patient presents to the head & neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. Around 7 weeks ago, the patient began developing a globus sensation with the feeling that there was something in the throat. He also complained of hoarseness. He was initially treated with an antibiotic with no improvement. 11/24/15 - Flexible fiberoptic exam - lesion in left BOT, left side of vallecula. No other lesions noted. 11/25/15 - CT neck - mass within the vallecula at the BOT on the left. This measures 2.5x3.0x2.5cm and results in moderate narrowing of the airway toward the left. The mass displaces the epiglottis inferiorly on the left. The lesion is medial to, and appears somewhat separate from, the left submandibular gland. No cervical nodes appreciated. 12/15/15 - BOT biopsy - sections show infiltrating moderately well differentiated SCC and squamous mucosa. p16 performed by IHC is strongly positive. 12/23/2015: CT chest w/ contrast (performed at OSH, images and report available): Multiple indeterminate nodules within the right lung with largest measuring 4 mm. Faint groundglass opacities within the RML which may be infectious or inflammatory in etiology. No intrathoracic lymphadenopathy. Currently, he reports he is doing well. The globus sensation and hoarseness improved after the biopsy. He is exercising multiple hours a day. Appetite is good and weight is stable. Energy level is good. No dysphagia. In October 2015, patient began to notice a globus sensation and throat discomfort. He also had small episodes of intermittent hemoptysis. He was evaluated by his PCP who gave him a trial of antibiotics and antifungal treatments without resolution of his symptoms. He was then referred to an ENT, Dr. Curtis Walsh at Century ENT on 12/21/15 who noted a fullness of the base of the tongue with a small amount of blood in the vallecula but no ulceration or discrete mass. CT neck and direct laryngoscopy with biopsy was recommended. On 12/22/15, he had a CT neck that showed a thin rim enhancing hypoattenuating 24x 30 mm necrotic lymph node just above the left carotid bifurcation. There was an asymmetric left tonsillar mass-like prominence measuring at least 18x 14 mm. On 12/31/15, he underwent US guided biopsy of left neck lymph nodes with pathology showing poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma with positivity for p40 and p16. He then saw his ENT, Dr. Walsh in follow up and he was recommended to see radiation and surgical oncology. He was evaluated by radiation oncologist, Dr. Daniel Golden and silver Cross who  ultimately referred Mr. Harrison to University of Chicago for further management. Mr. Harrison currently feels well. He complains only of mild pain in his throat for which he is taking one norco tab a day with good pain relief. He denies dysphagia or odynophagia, choking or gagging, xerostomia, hoarseness, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, fevers, chills, weight loss, chest pain, sob. His appetite has been unchanged and he has maintained his weight over this time period. His energy level is good. A few weeks ago he noted altered taste but this has since resolved. He wears partial lower and upper dentures and sees a dentist regularly. He smokes 1/2 pack of cigarettes a day from 20-25 years, but quit 18 years ago. He drinks about 2-3 beers a day currently and has done this for 20+ years. |2016-01-29:	Patient presents with    Appointment     He presents today for outpatient consultation for poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the left base of tongue (cT2o N2c), p16 positive, diagnosed December 2015. He underwent CT neck showing enlarged lymph node above left carotid bifurcation and asymmetric left tonsillar mass. On 12/31/15, he underwent US guided biopsy of left neck lymph nodes with pathology showing poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, positive for p40 and p16. He was also noted to have a mass in the left base of tongue consistent as primary disease. He has since seen Dr. Golden for radiation therapy evaluation and oncologist, Dr. Seiwert, at UCM for clinical trial. He presents today to discuss induction chemotherapy here  as it is closer to his home. He has medical hx of HLD, HTN, and OSA. Overall he is doing well with good energy level. He reports mild throat pain and pain with swallowing controlled with Ibuprofen as needed. His appetite is unchanged and weight is stable. He denies fever, chills, sweats, chest pain, dysphagia, hoarseness, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or constipation. He is a former smoker 0.5 packs daily for 20-25 years, quit 18 years ago. narrative: 2015-09-01:	September 2015 -- Noted a lump in his right neck which was painless while shaving. |2016-01-08:	1/8/16 -- underwent a surgical excision of the lymph node (not felt to be a candidate for needle aspiration by IR). |2016-01-16:	1/16/16 -- CT scan of chest -- 1.6x1.cm left adrenal mass. |2016-01-20:	1/20/16 -- PET scan -- right neck node that was hypermetabolic with an SUV of 13 and that corresponded to the smaller lymph node noted on OR report. |2016-01-20:	1/20/16 -- PET scan -- right neck node that was hypermetabolic with an SUV. |2016-01-27:	Per Dr. Nabrinskiny's note from 1/27/16. |2016-02-09:	Bradley Busch is a 60Yrs male with HPV+ TxN2b SCC of the head and neck. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management and workup of his disease. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. September 2015 - Noted a lump in his right neck which was painless while shaving. A few weeks later, he went to his PCP and was prescribed a Z-Pak. The lesion did not respond. December - Returned to PCP office. CT scan was performed without contrast. Notable for a 2.5cm lymph node in the right level IIA region with several smaller lymph nodes adjacent to this. There was no evidence of other abnormalities. Imaging was reviewed by rad onc, who noted a 15x18x15mm prominent lymph node superior to the one noted on the official read. Referred to Dr. David Hemmer. On his exam, did not see any obvious lesions in the oral cavity, nasopharynx, oropharynx, or hypopharynx. No biopsies were taken. 1/8/16 - underwent a surgical excision of the lymph node (not felt to be a candidate for needle aspiration by IR). In operative report, noted that there is an enlarged lymph node in the cephalad direction from the node that was resected. Final pathology demonsrated metastatic poorly differntiated SCC, 3cm in size with no extracapsular extension of tumor. A p16 stain was performed and was strongly positive. 1/16/16 - CT scan of chest - 1.6x1.cm left adrenal mass. No pulmonary abnormalities. Per Dr. Nabrinskiny's note from 1/27/16, this is an adrenal adenoma that is NOT new. 1/20/16 - PET scan - right neck node that was hypermetabolic with an SUV of 13 and that corresponded to the smaller lymph node noted on OR report. No other areas of nodal uptake. Increased uptake in the base of tongue/lateral pharyngeal wall on the right side with SUV of 6.8. Referred back to Dr. Hemmer. Thought to have some fullness on right BOT and right lateral pharyngeal area. Underwent biopsy which demonstrated fragments of benign lympho-epithelial tissue with acute and chronic inflammation, consistent with lingual tonsillar tissue. No carcinoma present. Referred to UCM to discuss OPTIMA trial and for further workup of primary site. He was seen by both Dr. Haraf and Dr. Agrawal today. He underwent a biopsy of his right tonsil. Currently, he reports he is doing well other than some soreness at the biopsy site earlier today. He denies any weight loss, appetite changes, fevers, chills, dysphagia. mucoepidermoid carcinoma. |2016-05-10:	5/10/16: He was evaluated by Dr. Blair and Dr. Gottlieb. |2016-05-10:	Brian Comstock is a 48Yrs male with T4N2cM0 high grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma of the head and neck who presented with left chin numbness in fall 2014. His chin numbness progressed and he also developed oropharyngeal pain and multiple dental issues in May 2015.These symptoms led to left-sided mandibular wisdom tooth extraction and was noted to have an erosive process within the mandible. In May 2015 he underwent biopsy confirming invasive carcinoma involving the mandible, originally diagnosed as invasive SCC. Subsequent mandibulectomy with bilateral radical neck dissection and reconstruction occurred in may 20, 2015 at Indiana University. Pathology was consistent with high-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma 9.5 cm in size with extensive involvement of the mandible, perineural invasion, lymphovascular invasion, positive margin at the pterygoid, and 6/65 bilateral positive lymph nodes with metastatic disease. From June-August 2015, he underwent  concurrent chemoradiation with cisplatin and intensity modulated radiation therapy to the bilateral necks, oral cavity/floor of mouth with special attention to the left pterygoid region and the skull base( total 60 Gy). Three months after the completion of adjuvant CRT, he had a PET/CT scan in November 2015 which showed uptake in a new sternal lesion. FNA of lesion was performed and showed features similar to mucoepidermoid carcinoma. At the completion of RT, Jan 2016 CT C/A/P showed enlarged sternal lesion and increase in size was attributed to inflammation. However, surveillance PET in 4/19/2016 showed uptake at R subcarinal/paraesophageal LN in mediastinum that was increased in size  from prior CT from Jan 2016 along with a Faint focus in R hilar region, Uptake at sternal metastasis, Post-op uptake within face/neck, and Low-grade uptake within L aspect of tongue. These hypermetabolic nodes at station 7 and 11R were sampled during bronch with EBUS and consistent with spread from mucoepidermoid carcinoma. Most recently, he reports that the plate placed during his reconstruction has become exposed over the last two weeks. He overall feels well. He is a 4th grade teacher but not currently working says diagnosis. His energy level is pretty good and he remains relatively active doing household chores, completing his own ADLs, gardening, driving, mowing the line, etc. He does note some increased fatigue on some days and notes being active at least 50% of most days. He is getting his nutrition primarily through the G-tube but is able to take some soft foods by mouth. He endorses dry mouth, drooling, dysphagia, neck stiffness, and trouble with mastification. His weight has been relatively stable after an initial signifcant weight loss at the time of diagnosis. He had met with our radiation oncologist, Dr. Haraf who advised consideration of systemic therapy with possible radiation at a later date. He also met with our ENT colleague,, Dr. Blair who cultured his left sinus tract and ordered CT neck and chest imaging to further assess his disease. Oncology history( as summarized by rad onc):  Thanksgiving 2014: He developed L chin numbness that was progressive to the R chin; he also had trismus. He underwent steroid injections without benefit. He saw several healthcare providers, including ENT and dental, without a diagnosis. 4/23/15: Path of lower left mandible revealed focally keratinizing SCC,  moderately differentiated. Could not exclude possibility of high-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma. He was evaluated at Indiana University, who noted an expansile lesion involving most of L hemimandible and L masticator space; moderate trismus. 5/4/15: CT neck revealed lytic mildly enhancing mass involving R parasymphyseal, midline, and L hemimandible. There were nonenlarged but mild-moderately suspicious L level Ib and IIA LN. CT chest negative for pulmonary mets; nonspecific mediastinal and R hilar LN. 5/20/15: Per outside records, a L hemimandibulectomy was planned, but due to extent of disease at the time of surgery, he underwent composite mandible resection/FOM resection, b/l ND, and resection of facial skin with R fibula flap for reconstruction and b/l TMJ prosthesis. Final path revealed central mucoepidermoid carcinoma, high-grade, 9.5cm. There was +LVI, +PNI. Main resection margins were positive anterior soft tissue, medial soft tissue, medial mucosal margin, FOM mucosal margin, inferior soft tissue of anterior mandible. There were 6/65 LN (at R level IB, L level IB, L levels II-IV, and in "main mandibular resection" specimen), max 1.2 cm, +ECE. Staging was pT4aN2c. His surgery was complicated, requiring multiple revisions of his arterial anastomosis due to persistent thrombosis. Post-operatively he developed recurrence of the thrombosis; his flap failed on POD #1. 5/29/16: He underwent reconstruction/revision with L fibular flap. 6/10/15-8/20/15: He received adjuvant CRT (weekly cisplatin). Reportedly 30 XRT treatments. 11/24/15: PET/CT revealed uptake at a sternal lesion, 1.5cm. 12/3/15: FNA of sternum revealed non-small cell carcinoma with morphologic features similar to prior mandible mucoepidermoid carcinoma. He was offered palliative radiation and received 5 fractions in Indiana. 1/18/16: CT CAP revealed slightly large sternal lesion    4/19/16: PET/CT revealed uptake at R subcarinal/paraesophageal LN in mediastinum. Faint focus in R hilar region. Uptake at sternal metastasis. Post-op uptake within face/neck. Low-grade uptake within L aspect of tongue. 4/28/16: He underwent bronchoscopy with EBUS/TBNA of stations 7, 11R. Pathology revealed mucoepidermoid carcinoma. Dr. Blair cultured the L facial sinus tract and ordered CT neck/chest with panorex. ECOG Performance Status:  1 |2016-05-18:	HPI   Since last visit, reports he has been doing well. Terry L Pfeifer is a 56Yrs old male presents today for an outpatient consultation for his newly diagnosed SCC of a left neck node. He initially noticed a mass in left neck about 1 year ago, he was seen by a physician at the time and underwent US of node, they decided to hold off on biopsy and observe at the time. He was without issue until about 3-4 weeks ago when he noticed the right neck node increased in size and became bothersome. He underwent excisional left neck mass biopsy on 05/18/16 finding metastatic poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, positive for p16 (HPV) by immunostain. He is scheduled for surgery(triple endoscopy and tonsillectomy) and PAC placement on 06/10/16 with Dr. Mehta. Recent PET scan showed hypermetabolic prostate and pt is scheduled to see Urologist. Overall he is doing well with good energy level. His appetite is good and weight is stable. He denies trouble swallowing, pain with swallowing, sore throat, weight loss, or dyspnea. The pt has never smoked. FFL was normal. 5/4/16: CT neck revealed a tumor involving the L oral tongue, crossing midline and involving BOT and sublingual space/left geniohyoid and genioglossus muscles. Tumor is inseparable from left SMG. There were b/l necrotic LN in jugular chain and SCV. He was referred to Dr. Yajnik for definitive CRT. 5/16/16: PET/CT revealed increased activity at "Lower left aspect but extending to the R, anteriorly, and posteriorly." There was increased activity in the bilateral submandibular (highly suggestive of metastasis) and at least L-sided level II LN; there was also activity in multiple R LN and R SCV "can not r/o met." He was felt to have cT4N2c disease. He was evaluated in the ER with concern for airway compromise due to tongue edema and decadron were given. Prophylactic trach was discussed but Mr. Harrison did not feel that he was having any problems. There was some improvement with steroids but continues to have tongue swelling. 5/23/16: He started CRT in 2 Gy/fx with cisplatin (q3w)    6/3/16: He was evaluated by Dr. Samant, who noted b/l neck LAD (largest 2cm). He suggest continuing with CRT. PET/CT was obtained and per verbal report from Dr. Dorn, there  is decreased SUV in the areas of disease with some new avidity at anterior to tongue. Currently completing his 3rd week of CRT. He has lost 20 lbs over the past month. Remains on decadron 24mg daily. PAST MEDICAL, SURGICAL, SOCIAL, AND FAMILY HISTORY  No past medical history on file. narrative: 2016-05-01:	In 5/2016. |2016-06-01:	On 6/2016. |2016-06-20:	James Donnelly is a 74Yrs male who presents to the University of Chicago Medical Center for further care of a newly diagnosed tongue cancer. His oncologic history is as follows:   He first noticed some difficulty swallowing 3-4 months prior to presentation but attributed this to a chronic cough stemming from bronchitis. He had a PET scan performed that demonstrated high uptake in the right base of the tongue and at level of on the right side of the neck. This was corroborated on physical exam which demonstrated a 3 cm x 3 cm right cervical node at level II. A flexible laryngoscopy was performed and demonstrated lingual fullness at the base of the tongue but no discrete mass. The right cervical node was ultimately biopsied via FNA and returned metastatic moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, p16 immunoperoxidase stain positive. He was immediately referred to UCMC for further care. He comes to clinic today with his wife and brother. He is doing well and has not noticed a dramatic worsening of his symptoms. He does have slightly increased pain at the site of his right lymph node. His performance status is good and he actively works around the yard and golfs. He intermittently drinks but does not smoke any longer - quit 20 years ago after a 30 pack year history. His main questions today involve his stage, what treatment regimen he will receive, and if he can receive some of the therapy closer to home in Crown Point, IN. He intermittently has positional lightheadedness for which he sees a cardiologist. The patient presents to the thoracic medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management of his disease. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. 8/2014 - Presented with T1aN0 SCC of right true vocal cord s/p XRT to larynx (28x, 6300cGy) completed 10/2014    9/28/15 - CT neck demonstrated recurrent disease. 10/2015 - Salvage total laryngectomy (w/o neck dissection) with placement of tracheoesophageal voice prosthesis    2/2016 - Began experience redness and swelling around stoma site. Biopsy at the time was normal, but tracheal lesion was re-biopsied 5/25/16 and demonstrated recurrent SCC. 6/2016 - PET and CT done. PET demonstrated the following -     1. 3.1x2.7 anterior left neck mass noted on the prior CT demonstrates significant hypermetabolism with a mean SUV of 7.7 and maximum SUV of 9.8. Findings consistent with recurrent malignancy. 2. Increased number of up to 8mm short axis bilateral neck lymph nodes with a few lymph nodes demonstrating mild increase in hypermetabolism compared to background. Additionally, mild chest, abdominal, and pelvic lymphadenopathy noted as detailed above with a few lymph nodes demonstrating mild hypermetabolism most prominently of the left para-aortic lymphadenopathy, and an enlarged subcarinal lymph node. He has been following closely with Dr. Vokes for routine f/u and was noted to have a mild anemia ranging between 9-10 in 2016. His hemoglobin at that time was 8.9. His repeat CT imaging in 7/17 showed multiple prominent thoracic and abdominal lymph nodes, particularly in the retroperitoneal space and these were no appreciably changed in his imaging in 11/29/17. On 11/29/17, he was seen in clinic and noted to have a hemoglobin of 7.1. In December 2017, he presented to an OSH for anemia and hemoglobin <7 and was transfused 2 units of PRBCs. Given his new onset anemia in the setting of his prominent lymph nodes, he underwent a bone marrow biopsy on 1/18/18. He then underwent a repeat PET scan on 1/27/18 which revealed no hypermetabolic FDG avid tumor, though there were many enlarged. He presents today to discuss the diagnosis and treatment options. Mr Leonard presents today with his wife to discuss treatment options. He reports to be healthy and has no complaints. His wife states that pt has swelling in the neck. Patient reports that the swelling of the neck has improved, and still notes small area of non-tender swelling and firmness on the right side of his neck. He denies oral pain, dysphagia, odynophagia, trismus, dysarthria, tongue immobility, or face swelling. He denies any  significant weight loss. He feels well and denies any other complaints. PS 0      Oncologic History:  Mr Sokol is a 57 y/o male with no significant PMH developed a sore throat in the end of September. He was seen by his PCP who started him on antibiotics and he was referred to ENT. IHC was p16 positive. A CT scan on 10/6 demonstrated an ill defined soft tissue mass in the left palatine tonsil measuring  1.7 cm x  2.2 cm x 2.6 cm. Abnormally enlarged left level 2A/3 lymph node measuring 2.4 x 2.1 x 3.7 cm. A PET/CT showed asymmetric hypermetabolic mucosal thickening of the left tonsillar pillar at the level of the uvula measuring 2.3 cm with a maximal SUV of 16.4 compatible with patients known tonsillar carcinoma. There were 2 adjacent enlarged and hypermetabolic left level 2 jugulodigastric lymph nodes, measuring 2.1 cm x 1 cm with a max. SUV of 10.8 compatible with metastatic left cervical adenopathy. He works as an IT consultant and has been able to continue working his routine hours. He is a former smoker, 10 pack year, quit 10-15 years ago. narrative: 2016-10-11:	10/11/16 -- CT neck -- 2.8x1.9x2.5 cm enhancing mass at the right tongue base with involvement of the lateral pharyngeal wall and extension to the parapharyngeal and subglottic space. |2016-10-17:	10/17/16 -- panendoscopy. |2016-10-21:	10/21/16 -- PET/CT -- confirming SUV uptake in BOT mass and right lymph node. |2016-10-26:	Thomas Carroll is a 70Yrs male with newly diagnosed cT4N1 BOT SCC, p16+. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and to discuss further management of his disease. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. He began developing right sided tongue pain around 1.5 years ago after a dental cleaning. This persisted, but has worsened in the past month or two. He notes over the past two months he has begun developing restriction in his tongue movement. He can no longer move his tongue very far to the right and has difficulty clearing food from the back of his right mouth. He was seen by a dentist who was concerned about his restriction in tongue mobility. He was referred to local ENT, Dr. Clark. 10/11/16 - CT neck - 2.8x1.9x2.5 cm enhancing mass at the right tongue base with involvement of the lateral pharyngeal wall and extension to the parapharyngeal and subglottic space. narrative: 2017-02-24:	He was evaluated by ENT at an OSH recently for increasing jaw pain and a biopsy demonstrated Squamous cell cancer on 2/24/2017. |2017-04-04:	Richard C May is a 68Yrs male with recurrent squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue. The patient presents to the head and neck medical oncology clinic for an initial consultation and a second opinion. Please allow us to review the patient's history for our records. The patient is a 68-year-old male who is a smoker h/o right tongue squamous cell cancer treated with a right hemiglossectomy and XRT in 2003. He was diagnosed with osteoradionecrosis of the mandible and was treated with hyperbaric oxygen and underwent extraction of all his teeth. In clinic today, he reports pain in the left jaw, 2-3/10 which is exacerbated by speaking/eating. He denies any weight loss. He usually grinds his food to a fine paste and has been able to maintain a steady weight. He endorses some xerostomia. He has also been diagnosed with right total occlusion of his carotid, and partial occlusion of the left carotid. He notes a CVA 2.5 years ago, at which time he had left-sided paresis, but this fully resolved. Of note, he is a Current smoker and has a 60 pack year history of smoking. Patient Active Problem List   Diagnosis    COPD (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease)    History of tongue cancer    HTN (hypertension)    H/O: CVA (cerebrovascular accident)    Arthritis of left knee    H/O head and neck radiation    History of CVA (cerebrovascular accident)    Carotid occlusion, right    Smoking greater than 40 pack years       No Known |
Dx_: ['Squamous cell cancer', 'squamous cell carcinoma', 'History of tongue cancer', 'right tongue squamous cell cancer']

Results   HPV 16 DNA DETECTED     Interpretation   HPV 16 DNA is detected in this specimen. High-risk HPV is an etiologic agent of   many squamous cell carcinomas, including those of the oropharynx, uterine cervix   and anal canal. Evidence suggests that patients with HPV-positive oropharyngeal   squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC) have improved survival outcomes compared to   those with HPV-negative tumors (N Engl J Med 2010; 363:2435, J Natl Cancer Inst   2008; 100:2619). This test does not provide information about viral oncogene expression, and   cannot distinguish bystander HPV infections from integrated (potentially    oncogenic) HPV DNA. Correlation with p16 immunohistochemistry is recommended. IMAGING:  ~  PET WB H AND N INITIAL STAGE, 4/4/2018 11:02 AM    CLINICAL INFORMATION: 73 years old Male. Reason: Right tonsil mass with associated  lymphadenopathy. History: Right tonsil mass with associated lymphadenopathy. RADIOPHARMACEUTICAL: 10.9 mCi F-18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG). BLOOD GLUCOSE (FASTING): 109 mg/dL. TECHNIQUE: After administration of the radiotracer and an uptake delay of 77 minutes,  nonenhanced CT images were obtained for attenuation correction and for fusion with the PET  emission images. (The nonenhanced CT images were obtained solely for purposes of  completing the PET scan, are not of diagnostic quality and are thus not interpreted or  used to diagnose disease independently of the PET images.) A series of overlapping PET  emission images was then obtained from the skull base to the proximal thighs. The average  SUV of the normal liver was 2.5 for this exam. COMPARISON: No previous PET here. Neck CT, 3/20/2018    FINDINGS: Today's CT portion grossly demonstrates enlarged lymph nodes in the left neck  level 2 region. Diffuse coronary calcifications are noted. Linear densities are seen in  the left lung base, consistent with atelectasis or scarring. Patient is status post  bilateral hip arthroplasty. Radiation seeds are noted in the prostate gland. Today's PET examination demonstrates a focus of increased activity in the right palatine  tonsil with SUV max of 14.7. Intense FDG uptake is seen in the enlarged lymph nodes in the  right neck level 2 region with SUV max of 9.1. There is decreased metabolic activity in  the center of the enlarged lymph nodes, suggesting central necrosis. No other evidence of FDG avid tumor. IMPRESSION:     1. Hypermetabolic lesion in the right palatine tonsil, consistent with the patient's  diagnosis of tonsillar cancer. 2. Hypermetabolic lymph nodes in the right neck at level 2 region with central necrosis,  consistent with the nodal metastasis. 3. TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar and multi-sequence MR images of the neck were obtained with and  without contrast, with intravenous administration of 19 cc Dotarem. FINDINGS: Previously seen necrotic right tonsillar mass is no longer discernible. Previously seen cystic/necrotic abnormal right level 2 lymph nodes appear to be decreased  in size when comparing to the prior exam dated 4/4/2018, for example the targeted right  level 2A lymph node measures 15 x 16 mm in axial sections, previously was 19 x 20 mm; the  targeted right level 2B lymph node measures 10 x 10 mm in axial sections, previously was  16 x 16 mm. No new additional abnormal lymph nodes by size criteria are noted in the neck. The nasopharynx and hypopharynx are unremarkable. Again seen is a small left vallecular T2  hyperintense focus consistent with retention cyst or secretions, unchanged. The larynx is  unremarkable. The upper trachea and esophagus are unremarkable. The contrast-enhanced  appearance of the submandibular, sublingual, and parotid glands bilaterally is  unremarkable. The thyroid gland is unremarkable. The oral tongue and the floor of mouth  are unremarkable. Scattered mucosal thickening in the partially visualized paranasal sinuses are again  noted, which appears to be slightly progressed in maxillary sinuses bilaterally. The  partially imaged brain structures and orbits are unremarkable. There are multilevel  spondylytic changes which is worse at C5-6 and C6-7 resulting in mild spinal canal  narrowing, unchanged. No focal worrisome bone marrow signal is noted. Previously seen right tonsillar mass is no longer discernible, which indicates  treatment response. Interval decrease in size of targeted cystic/necrotic abnormal right level 2 lymph  nodes, as detailed above. No new additional abnormal lymph nodes are noted in the rest of  the neck by size criteria. narrative: 2017-08-01:	Presented to PCP in late August 2017. |2017-08-16:	A CT scan 8/16/17 a large (3.6cm) mass in the right neck with a necrotic core. |2017-09-28:	who performed a tonsillectomy and biopsy of other sites 9/28/17. |2017-10-14:	Mr. Anderson then saw Dr. Ajay Bajaj (GI) 10/14/17 who visualized a. small ulcer at G--E junction on EGD that appeared consistent with GERD. |2017-10-14:	Mr. Anderson then saw Dr. Ajay Bajaj (GI) 10/14/17 who visualized a small ulcer at G--E junction on EGD that appeared consistent with GERD. |2017-10-16:	Robert Anderson is a 68Yrs never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right pT1 cN2a cM0, left pT1 cN0 cM0, both p16 positive). Mr. Anderson first noticed R sided nonpainful swelling in neck, detected due to visible change. Presented to PCP in late August. A CT scan 8/16 a large (3.6cm) mass in the right neck with a necrotic core. An FNA biopsy of the mass showed moderately differentiated p16+ SCC, but the primary source was not clear at that time. Subsequent PET imaging 8/24 revealed hypermetabolic bilateral tonsils and associated right neck LN. The PET also showed faint uptake in the distal esophagus near the GE junction. He was referred to ENT, who performed a tonsillectomy and biopsy of other sites 9/28. Both tonsils had involvement of SCC, and both were p16+. The right tonsil contained a 0.9cm mass and the left a 0.15cm mass. Biopsies of the nasopharynx and base of tongue showed no involvement of SCC. Mr. Anderson then saw Dr. Ajay Bajaj (GI) 10/14 who visualized a small ulcer at G-E junction on EGD that appeared consistent with GERD; this was biopsied and the results are pending. Mr. Anderson's medical history includes a five-vessel CABG in 2003. Historically he has taken only atorvastatin and a baby aspirin. Since the esophageal inflammation was seen on PET, he has started pantoprazole 40mg daily. He has a good performance status and exercises regularly: runs, swims, rides bike. Weight has been stable and appetite normal. He lives with his wife and has 4 children (adult) in Chicago. He worked as a police officer in Chicago for 39 years, most recently on a gang unit on the West Side. He retired from the CPD in 2009. He now works part time for United  Center and Board of Options as a security guard. His father and mother both had heart disease and died of cardiac complications. His sister also has heart disease. There is no other history of cancer in the family. Today, Mr. Anderson continues to have pain at the site of the tonsillectomy and is taking Hycet for pain control. He can tolerate a soft diet and has maintained a steady weight. The pain is improving since the procedure. He has no pain at the site of the right neck mass. Today will receive Carboplatin, Abraxane and Nivolumab. Mr. Anderson feels well overall. He is anxious about starting chemotherapy today. Pain at site of the tonsillectomy continues to improve- he is no longer requiring Hycet for pain control. He denies pain at the site of the right neck mass. Today will receive Abraxane. Mr. Anderson feels well today. He notes mild-moderate nausea following chemotherapy on 10/27/17. The nausea lasted 2-3 days and then was followed by diarrhea x 1 day which has since resolved. Pain at site of the tonsillectomy continues to improve. He can tolerate a soft diet by mouth. He denies pain at the site of the right neck mass which he feels is unchanged in size. |2017-11-10:	Robert Anderson is a 68 y/o never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right T1N2a, left pT1N0, both p16 positive) presents to IV Therapy for induction chemotherapy C1D15 per OPTIMA 2. Mr. Anderson c/o frequent episodes of diarrhea x 5-6 days. Denies fever or abdominal pain. He denies pain at the site of the right neck mass which he feels may be somewhat softer and smaller in size. |2017-11-13:	Robert Anderson is a 68 y/o never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right T1N2a, left pT1N0, both p16 positive) presents to IV therapy for induction chemotherapy C2D1 per OPTIMA 2. Patient states that his diarrhea lightened over the weekend and he had a solid stool this morning (continues the flagyl that was prescribed to him on Friday). He notes that he has developed a metallic taste in his mouth which has been affecting his eating--everything taste "weird and off" but he's been continuing to try to eat soft foods. He used antiemetics after chemo last week for about three days with one episode of vomiting, but hasn't had any further episodes of nausea. He complains of a small patch of reddened swelling on anterior left arm--notes that he had an peripheral IV in that area with treatment three days ago which hurt while receiving treatment, but he denies any associated fever, chills, or pus coming from the area and thinks it has remained about the same size. He denies sob, chest pain, headache, or dizziness. Started cycle 1 day 1 of OPTIMA II trial. |2017-11-17:	Robert Anderson is a 68 y/o never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right T1N2a, left pT1N0, both p16 positive) presents to IV Therapy for induction chemotherapy C2D1 per OPTIMA 2. He feels that the right neck mass has significantly decreased in size. |2017-12-08:	Robert Anderson is a 68 y/o never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right T1N2a, left pT1N0, both p16 positive) presents to IV Therapy for Induction Chemotherapy C3D1 per OPTIMA 2. Mr. Anderson continues to feel well. Currently denies oral pain, odynophagia or GI symptoms. He is eating regular food and his appetite remains strong. His main complaint is general fatigue that usually manifests in the afternoons. His energy is best in the morning and this is when he exercises. He feels that the right neck mass continues to decrease in size. |2017-12-14:	Robert Anderson is a 68 y/o never smoker male with synchronous SCC of bilateral tonsils (right T1N2a, left pT1N0, both p16 positive) presents to IV Therapy for Induction Chemotherapy C3D8 per OPTIMA 2. Today will receive Abraxane    Mr. Anderson experienced severe nausea with emesis earlier this week- this improved significantly after rcvg Zofran, Reglan and Zyprexa. He was able to drink a large shake yesterday but has not eaten much food over the last several days. Today his Cr is elevated to 3.6. He is voiding normal, clear urine and states that he is voiding "a normal or increased amount". He denies dysuria. Currently denies oral pain, odynophagia however his appetite has decreased due to altered taste sensation. His main complaint is general fatigue but states "Actually I feel pretty good". He feels that the right neck mass has continued to gradually decrease in size. He was started on Amioderone 6 weeks ago by his Cardiologist. narrative: 2017-06-01:	6/2017: Developed a painless right neck mass. |2017-08-14:	8/14/2017: Went to PCP who performed an US of neck demonstrated a 2.6x4.1x1.5cm hypoechoic mass with internal septations. |2017-08-22:	8/22/2017: FFL demonstrates bilateral TVC mobile without masses or suspicious lesions within the oropharynx. |2017-08-22:	8/22/2017: CT neck WO contrast -- demonstrated right jugular chain adenopathy of uncertain etiology. |2017-08-29:	8/29/2017: needle biopsy and FNA of right level II LN demonstrated SCC. |2017-09-07:	9/7/2017: PET/CT demonstrated an increased uptake in the anterior hypopharynx/pre--epiglottic space effacing the valleculae (12.6 SUV). |2017-09-08:	9/8/2017: Oropharynx/vallecula biopsied. |2017-09-12:	9/12/2017: Biopsy results returned positive for poorly differentiated SCC with p16+. |2017-09-19:	Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0. Oncologic history as below. Patient met with Dr. Haraf this morning. He is meeting Dr. Aggarwal today as well. Patient endorses a mild globus sensation, mild sore throat, and mild hoarseness. His voice may have changed slightly. Patient denies trouble swallowing or pain with swallowing. No appetite changes or weight changes. Patient denies fevers, chills, or night sweats. He also denies chest pain, SOB, abdominal pain, and changes in bowel habits. Oncologic History:  6/2017: Developed a painless right neck mass. Likely represents an enlarged lymph node. 8/22/2017: CT neck WO contrast - demonstrated right jugular chain adenopathy of uncertain etiology. Lymphoproliferative disorder is possible. As per our read, the right level II LN appears to be a combination of 2 lymph nodes or 1 large lymph node although it was difficult to discern without IV contrast. 8/22/2017: FFL demonstrates bilateral TVC mobile without masses or suspicious lesions within the oropharynx, hypopharynx or glottis    8/29/2017: needle biopsy and FNA of right level II LN demonstrated SCC. Flow cytometry performed demonstrated no monoclonal B-lymphocyte population. T lymphocytes with increased CD4:CD8 ratio (7:1)    9/7/2017: PET/CT demonstrated an increased uptake in the anterior hypopharynx/pre-epiglottic space effacing the valleculae (12.6 SUV). 2.3x1.9cm right jugular LN (level II) (11.5 SUV). Additional sub  centimeter scattered cervical LNs without significant FDG uptake. On the left, there is a 1.2x0.6cm suprahyoid jugular LN (level II) (2.8 SUV). No distant mets. 9/8/2017: Oropharynx/vallecula biopsied    9/12/2017: Biopsy results returned positive for poorly differentiated SCC with p16+        Patient Active Problem List   Diagnosis    Malignant neoplasm of base of tongue    Secondary malignancy of lymph nodes of head, face and neck    Non-smoker |2017-09-26:	9/26/17: Started Induction chemotherapy C1D1 with OPTIMA 2. |2017-09-26:	9/26/17:. |2017-09-26:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 who presents for C1D1 of induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial. Patient states that he feels pretty well today except that he feels like he has something constantly in the back of his throat. He has no trouble swallowing or eating, but the sensation remains. He notes good energy and has no trouble performing his ADLs. He denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or constipation. |2017-10-02:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 who presents for C1D8 of induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial. Patient states that he tolerated his first treatment of chemotherapy pretty well. He had a few episodes of nausea which were relieved with anti-emetics--no actual vomiting. He notes that food doesn't taste good anymore and he's losing his appetite--did not eat or drink very much this week. Energy remains good--has taken a nap over the last few days but has been able to do his ADLs. Notes he shared the news of his cancer with his young sons which was hard and stressful, and he has been waking up early in the mornings worried about his disease. He notes constipation for the last few days--has started taking miralax. He is amenable to trying to eat and drink more, and he thinks his right-sided neck mass has gotten "tighter." Denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, tingling in fingers/toes, or headache. Interested in getting a port placed during induction chemo. |2017-10-11:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 who presents for C1D15 of induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial. Patient notes that he did pretty well after day 8 of his chemo treatment. He had nausea for about 3 days last week which was relieved with the use of anti-emetics--has not had any vomiting so far. He is trying to eat as much as possible and has managed to gain 2.5kg from his last visit. Still has good energy--able to go to work every day and attend his sons' activities. He did note several days of constipation last week which resolved with the use of Miralax. Not sure if he can tell a difference in size of his right-sided neck mass. For port placement next week before treatment. Denies fever, chills, sob, chest pain, numbness/tingling in extremities. He notes that for the last ten years or so, he's experienced intermittent episodes during which his head will start to itch, then his mouth gets extremely dry, and he becomes profoundly tired (has to lie down immediately). During two such episodes, he continued to function (appeared to his family that he was drunk, but he wasn't) but had little or no recollection of the previous day's events. He states he's mentioned this to doctors over the years but was never referred to neurology. |2017-10-16:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 who presents for C2D1 of induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial. Patient notes that he's tolerating this treatment well overall. He had a port placed this morning which was unremarkable--thinks he slept through most of it. He had one day of nausea last week for which he took Zofran with good relief. He's tired but had been active with his three son and he mowed the lawn over the weekend. His constipation has improved with the use of Miralax. He continues to eat well and frequently--trying to gain weight before starting radiation. He is struggling to get restorative sleep--able to fall asleep but wakes up after about four hours. He has no fever, chest pain, sob, numbness/tingling in his fingers or toes, chills, or dizziness. |2017-10-23:	Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C2D8    Patient is doing well today. He denies trouble swallowing or pain with swallowing. He thinks his neck mass has decreased in size although he typically does not monitor it. He endorses significant nausea and dry heaves for 2-3 days after receiving IC C2D1. This resolved several days ago and he has been eating very well over the last two days. He c/o insomnia despite taking benadryl at bedtime. Over the last two days he has felt well enough to play sports with his son. Additional sub centimeter scattered cervical LNs without significant FDG uptake. His appetite is way down and he is not interested in food. He was able to take three doses of GCSF without bone pain, and he hasn't had nausea or vomiting lately. Doesn't have much of an appetite--notes that everything "tastes like a big bite of butter" but he tries to drink protein shakes when he doesn't feel like eating. He has stopped taking Miralax as his bowels have normalized and he's still going to work. He didn't take GCSF last week as he wasn't treated, and he is concerned his counts might still be low. Anticipating seeing the psychiatrist at the end of the week. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting but admits to fatigue. |2017-11-20:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 who presents for C3D8 of induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial. Patient states that he feels "okay" but this chemo is making him really tired. His taste has improved a little--less "buttery"--but he still doesn't have that much interest in food and has to push himself to eat (eating a lot of soups and protein shakes). He was able to take 3 doses of GCSF without issue and he continues to work. Has been getting better sleep with the Remeron prescribed by Psychiatry, and he's still taking one ativan daily if he needs it. Thinks the Effexor is helping, too. Denies sob, chest pain, rashes, diarrhea, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting but admits to fatigue. |2017-12-05:	/  HPI 53 y/o male with t1N3 BOT SCCA HPV+ on OPTIMA 2 admitted for cycle 1/3 TFHX |2017-12-06:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2017-12-07:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2017-12-13:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 s/p induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial presents on his off-week after inpatient TFHX. He vomited this morning but hasn't had nausea or vomiting otherwise. Patient notes that he's better than he was a week ago, but he's still feeling impatient that he has not healed faster. He is now working full-time from home--voice is hoarse from talking on the phone so much. He has been eating small portions of solid food--had one episode of vomiting a few days ago from eating an entire submarine sandwich at once. Continues mouth rinses and oxycodone 10mg q4-5h--mouth pain is slowly improving. Oral secretions persist, although he has been using robitussin infrequently. Neck has developed a raw area on the right which is irritated by his shirts--has been putting triple antibiotic ointment and a band-aid on it. Still getting 1 liter of NS at home. Performs ADLs independently--denies recent sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting. |2018-01-30:	He was discharged yesterday (1/30/18) and sent out on a course of doxycycline and augmentin. |2018-01-31:	HPI:  Robert Betlow is a 53Yrs male with BOT/Valleculae p16+ poorly differentiated SCC likely cT1N2a-N2bM0 s/p induction chemotherapy on the OPTIMA II trial who presents for follow up after cycle 3/3 of inpatient THFX--finished on 1/5/18. He notes that when in the hospital, he had 4 episodes of hard vomiting after trying to eat--throat is very sore and he's struggling with oral intake. Continues to get 1 liter of fluids at home. He remains really exhausted--can perform his ADLs but they take all his energy, and he is trying to work from home but tires quickly. He's still struggling with eating, as sometimes has an appetite but food doesn't taste good--trying to consume soups and protein shakes consistently. No more episodes of nausea, but he'll occasionally vomit mucus/oral secretions as they irritate his throat (last episode yesterday). Has been taking 3 oxycodone/day as he thinks he helps with the mucus in his throat--amenable to replacing oxycodone with robitussin. Dermatitis and mouth lesions have fully healed. |

narrative: 2017-07-01:	When she first noted the swelling in July 2017. |2017-09-14:	IL) 9/14/17 with right sided painless neck swelling for about 2 months. |2017-10-10:	JoAnn Marchigiani is a 75Yrs female, never-smoker, with a history of COPD and hypertension who recently presented to Dr. Gal at Century ENT (Crete, IL) 9/14/17 with right sided painless neck swelling for about 2 months. When she first noted the swelling in July 2017, she had a negative strep test but was treated empirically with azithromycin without improvement. She is a never smoker, but has exposure to second-hand smoke. She has limited alcohol intake (1 drink/month). She has no changes in voice and no dysphagia. Dr. Gal obtained CT imaging of the head and neck and a whole-body PET, which showed a polyploid mass at the level of the right vellecula 1.7 x 1.4 x 1.3 cm and a large, centrally necrotic right level 2 LN measuring 3.0 x 2.1 x 2.2 cm. No other hypermetabolic regions were seen on PET. An intrahepatic cyst was not FDG-avid. Fine-needle biopsy of the mass showed moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma, p16 strongly and diffusely positive. Patient had a -55.56% decrease in tumor burden from baseline. She was evaluated for TORS by Dr. Blair but thought not to be candidate for TORS due to needing very extensive surgery. Now on treatment 7/25 of daily radiation. Patient states that she's doing well with radiation. Her taste is starting to disappear, but she continues to have a good appetite with good oral intake (weight is stable). She can eat solid foods (including meats and breads) without trouble, but she does note early satiety. She denies mouth sores or pain but does note the sensation of "thickening" in the back of her tongue. Her energy is much better since finishing chemotherapy and getting a blood transfusion--she is able to perform her ADLs without help or struggle. She is using the mouth rinses, MuGard, and Radiaplex several times a day--hasn't noted any breakdown on skin on her neck. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, or chills. An  intrahepatic cyst was not FDG-avid. S/p 3 cyles on OPTIMA 2. |2018-01-22:	Now on treatment 11/25 of daily radiation. Patient is tolerating radiation therapy very well--has used no pain medication yet. She notes that her throat is beginning to get a little sore and dry, and she is now struggling to get down dry foods like bread. She has been eating pretty much a regular diet but started using supplements this morning--still gets full easily. She still has pretty good energy--needs no help with her ADLs. Still using MuGard and Radiplex--neck skin is still intact. She also complains of a lot of mucus in the back of her throat which interferes with swallowing--feels like she has to swallow really hard and repeatedly to get the food down. narrative: 2018-07-17:	7/17/18: Started C1D1 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol |2018-07-17:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today for C1D1 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. Patient notes that he's doing well. His right neck fullness is still present and sometimes has mild pain in his right ear. Appetite and energy are good--no trouble chewing or swallowing. He continues to work full time and is independent of his ADLs. He denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting. Ready to start treatment. Oncology history  He first presented to his PCP with R neck swelling about 3 months ago, in the setting of a recent URI. Following resolution of the URI, though, the neck remained swollen and mildly tender, prompting consultation with a local otolaryngologist near his home in Portage, IN. FNA of the neck mass revealed metastatic SCC of unknown primary. CT scan in early June showed a cystic, multiloculated level II neck node, measuring 4x2.7cm. PET-CT shortly thereafter showed FDG-avid right tonsil and level II node. He was thus referred to UCMC, where he was seen by Dr. Gooi on 6/25 and underwent laryngoscopic exam that revealed a R tonsillar mass. Pathology was consistent with invasive, nonkeratinizing SCC; IHC was positive for HPV 16. |2018-07-25:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today for follow up after C1D1 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. Patient states that he started developing a mildly itchy rash yesterday morning on his upper arms and trunk, and today the rash is slowly spreading down his lower arms, groin, buttocks, and thighs. He denies associated pain, severe pruritus, presence of vesicles, fever, chills, sob, or body aches, and he hasn't had to take any medication for itching or pain. He did well after his first day of treatment last week--has been taking daily Zofran and Compazine for mild nausea. He has been unusually constipated for the last five days--has had to use bisacodyl and a rectal suppository to move his bowels, and his hemorrhoids have been subsequently irritated (using steroid cream with relief). He also has experienced mild fatigue which is now resolving. He has great appetite and is independent of his ADLs. Next treatment is tomorrow (7/26/18). Pathology was  consistent with invasive, nonkeratinizing SCC; IHC was positive for HPV 16. |2018-07-26:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-08-03:	Patient states that his previous rash disappeared two days after he received a dose of IV solumedrol. He was prescribed a medrol dose pack but ended up not needing to take it. No further episodes of rash. He continues to tolerate treatment well but notes that his energy is overall down--still independent of ADLs, however. Eating well. Right-sided neck mass feels smaller. Noticed an increase in the number of stools last week after treatment (did increase his bowel regimen after being constipated) but has now returned to baseline. Takes Tylenol or Advil for occasional referred right ear pain. Had a SPSW evaluation yesterday and was okayed to continue a regular diet with thin liquids. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, sob, nausea, or vomiting. |2018-08-10:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today for C2D1 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. He continues to tolerate treatment well but notes that his energy is overall down--still independent of ADLs. He continues to eat well. No nausea. Denies neuropathy. Right-sided neck mass continues to decrease in size. Denies fever/chills, new arthralgias or diarrhea    Oncology history  He first presented to his PCP with R neck swelling about 3 months ago, in the setting of a recent URI. |2018-08-17:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today for C2D8 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. Interval history  -No further episodes of rash  -Independent of ADLs but energy is low--has been moving slower  -Complains of a mild intermittent sore throat x 5 days--no associated fever, chills, sneezing, or coughing  -Has daily headaches for which he takes Advil several times a day (has a hx of left-sided cluster headaches which stopped after starting treatment and is now having daily "regular" headaches)--no associated light/sound sensitivity or nausea  -Appetite remains good but sometimes food tastes "off"  -Right-sided neck mass continues to decrease in size  -Rate of hair loss seems to be slowing down    Oncology history  He first presented to his PCP with R neck swelling about 3 months ago, in the setting of a recent URI. |2018-08-24:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today for C2D15 of induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. Interval history  -Energy is slowly fading--takes him longer to do everything  -Still independent of ADLs   -Throat pain from last week has localized to an area around the gum of his last molar on his bottom jaw--area feels swollen and tender but no associated fevers, chills, or body aches  -Daily headaches continue--takes 2-6 tabs of Advil daily--now having some sensitivity to sound with them  -Right-sided neck mass continues to decrease in size  -Constipation earlier int he week relieved with peri-colace  -Still eating well despite change in taste  -Denies sob, chest pain, nausea, or vomiting    Oncology history  He first presented to his PCP with R neck swelling about 3 months ago, in the setting of a recent URI. |2018-08-31:	Mr. Robb is a 60 year-old male with p16 positive cT1N1M0 SCC of the right tonsil presenting today to continue induction therapy on the OPTIMA II protocol. Interval history  -Continues to have low energy but still independent of ADLs  -Saw dentist for pain in bottom jaw gum--wisdom tooth emerging and needs to be pulled, will see an oral surgeon, started a course of amoxicillin (discomfort about the same)  -Saw PCP for headaches--gave him Vimovo to try, continues to have daily headaches, had a left-sided cluster headache this morning  -Right-sided neck mass continues to decrease in size  -No further episodes of constipation--will increased bowel regimen this week in anticipation of constipation from zofran use  -Eating well despite change in taste (gained 5 pounds since last week)  -Denies sob, chest pain, nausea, or vomiting    Oncology history  He first presented to his PCP with R neck swelling about 3 months ago, in the setting of a recent URI. |2018-09-07:	Interval history  -Feels well overall. She is also taking Kefir and some softened cereal in water. She's taking IV fluids every other day, but she's not yet confident she can drink the equivalent so doesn't want to stop. Struggling with taking 40meq of potassium a day--hard to get down. She is complaining of "coughing and choking fits" which happen sometimes during and day but mostly at night--coughing can last for several minutes and sometimes produces mucus. Amenable to trying scheduled robitussin diluted in water (has not taken it yet as it burns her mouth). Again voices frustration and discouragement at her slow recovery. narrative: 2018-04-02:	Sam Tripp is a 53Yrs male with a hx of irritable bowel syndrome, who presents with a newly diagnosed right tonsil cancer, p16+, non-smoker, cT1N2B (AJCC7), who presents for discussion of curative intent therapy. Initially felt to be low risk arm, but has relatively bulky disease (5.8cm per recent measurement). Enrolled on OPTIMA 2 study. Here for C2 D8 today. Patient notes that he's becoming increasingly tired on this regimen. He is still working full-time (half the week at home and half in the office), and by the end of the day he's struggling to function. He's had a headache since before his cancer diagnosis, but he's noticed that it has quieted a little bit in the last week. He also thinks his right neck mass continues to slowly shrink as well with treatment--little easier to swallow now. His nausea is contained on tid Zofran and compazine, and he's eating well and often. He has right hip pain from known arthritis for which he's going to get a cortisone shot on 4/4--has felt very restless from hip pain (difficult to get comfortable when sleeping). He recently finished a 10-day course of amoxicillin for a sinus infection but continues to have congestion and blood clots and bleeding with nose blowing. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, or chills. |2018-04-09:	Here for C2D15 today. Patient states that his fatigue is slowly increasing, but he wants to continue to work as long as possible. His nausea and vomiting is controlled as long as he takes scheduled Zofran and compazine--hasn't yet tried to wean down. Had a cortisone shot in his right hip last week--feel much more comfortable walking around now. Trying to increase his oral intake, but food doesn't taste "right" anymore. Right neck mass continues to feel smaller--hoping he'll end up only getting radiation. Continues to have streaks of blood when he blows his nose--nasal saline spray and moisturizer in his nose has helped. |2018-04-16:	Here for C3D1 today. Patient notes increasing fatigue, but he continues to go to work as he wants to feels a normal as possible for as long as he can. Taking BID Zofran and Compazine with good nausea control--concerned that he will get nauseated if he tries to wean down. Able to tolerate 2 doses of GCSF--less painful now on Claritin. Trying to eat more but doesn't really enjoy it--food doesn't taste "right" anymore, and he isn't drinking water as he doesn't like it. Right neck mass is smaller each week. Still having streaks of blood with blowing his nose despite saline spray and vaseline in nares--doesn't feel like his usual sinus infections (not as bad). Reports that his wife says he's crankier these days. Patient denies sob, chest pain, fever, body aches, headaches, or chills but does endorse mild intermittent tingling in his bilateral fingertip and toes. |2018-04-23:	Here for C3D8 today. Patient complains of increasing fatigue but still going to work and trying to walk around the warehouse for exercise at least daily. Taste and appetite are fading but he's forcing himself to eat (has gained a little weight since last week). Continues to have blood-streaked mucus when blowing his nose--no worse over the last few weeks, and he continues to use saline spray and vaseline in his nares. Hoping to get treated with radiation only. Took 2 doses of GCSF last week--discomfort was minimal. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, body aches, headaches, or chills but still having mild intermittent tingling in his bilateral fingertip and toes. |2018-04-30:	Here for C3D15 today. Patient notes that he struggled last week as he flew to Cleveland to spend time with his family and was exhausted when he returned--could barely make it through the remainder of the week. He continues to work full-time and notes that he's really dragging when he has to go in to the office--feels fatigued and unfocused. The blood-streaked mucus he's having with the blowing of his nose is improving a bit. Continues to have slight tingling in his finger and toes--no worsening since last week. Continues BID Zofran and Compazine--no breakthrough nausea. Continues to eat well, but food tastes muted and sometimes metallic. Notes his right hip pain is starting to return despite his recent steroid shot. He notes anxiety about his upcoming treatment--not interested in seeing psych. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, body aches, headaches, or chills. |2018-05-08:	/  HPI Sam Tripp is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed cT1N2B right tonsil cancer, p16+ admitted for C1/3 of TFHX on OPTIMA 2 17-0104 with BID RT. The history is provided by the patient. |2018-05-09:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-05-10:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-05-15:	Sam Tripp is a 53Yrs male with right tonsil cancer, p16+, non-smoker, cT1N2b (AJCC7), enrolled on OPTIMA 2 study. Relatively bulky disease (5.8cm per recent measurement) --> categorized as high risk. He is now s/p 1/3 cycles of intermediate de-escalation TFHX. He was recently discharged from the hospital after his 1st cycle of TFHX  He is just now starting to have difficulty with swallowing. Takes alkaline mouthwash and Grade 1 MW which help, and he has taken a dose or two of Norco. He is still taking in adequate PO, but has noticed that it is starting to drop off a bit. Minimal neuropathy  Minimal Nausea, no vomiting. |2018-05-22:	/  HPI Sam Tripp is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed cT1N2B right tonsil cancer, p16+ admitted for C2/3 of TFHX on OPTIMA 2 17-0104 with BID RT. |2018-05-23:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-05-24:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-05-29:	He is now s/p 2/3 cycles of intermediate de-escalation TFHX. Patient notes that his throat hurts when he swallows food but feels "okay" if he is not eating. He is using a 25mcg fentanyl patch, takes oxycodone 5mg bid, and uses mouth rinses several times a day with manageable mouth and neck pain. He took 3 days of Zyprexa after discharge and continues to take scheduled zofran and compazine--nausea is totally controlled. He reports increased fatigue--sleeping much more than normal, but he is trying to walk a little every day. He has increased oral secretions along with dry mouth--using robitussin helps to mobilize her oral mucus. He has no taste or appetite (lost 3lbs) but still eating solid foods (hamburgers, hot dogs) along with Ensure. He denies sob, chest pain, fever, body aches, headaches, or chills but does endorse intermittent neuropathy in arms and legs. |2018-06-05:	/  HPI Sam Tripp is a 53Yrs male with newly diagnosed cT1N2B right tonsil cancer, p16+ admitted for C3/3 of TFHX on OPTIMA 2 17-0104 with BID RT. |2018-06-06:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-06-07:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-06-08:	3/3 cycles of intermediate de--escalation TFHX (last day 6/8/18) and now getting adjuvant nivolumab per protocol. |2018-06-08:	Patient notes that he felt fairly well on the day of discharge last week (6/8/18). |2018-06-08:	3/3 cycles of intermediate de--escalation TFHX (last day 6/8/18). |2018-06-11:	He is now s/p 3/3 cycles of intermediate de-escalation TFHX (last day 6/8/18). Patient notes that he felt fairly well on the day of discharge last week (6/8/18), but then he vomited once when he arrived home, three times the next day, and 6 times the following day (yesterday). He had been able to keep down eggs yesterday and this morning, but he has thrown up everything else. Including pills, shakes, and water. He has been trying to take scheduled Zofran, but he has been vomiting up the pills. He is very tired and his throat is very painful from emesis on top of mucositis. He has been having a little diarrhea as well which he attributes to not taking his cholestyramine for his IBS. |2018-06-19:	Patient states that he's feeling better than last week, if only marginally. His nausea has resolved, although he's still taking prophylactic zofran and compazine--no further episodes of vomiting in almost a week. He's trying to eat, although he is limited by his mouth and throat pain--continues a 25mcg fentanyl patch and oxycodone (about 25mg/day). He's been able to get a little food down (creamed corn, mac and cheese, Ensure) but he isn't eating much overall (6lbs down from a week and a half ago). Notes moderate fatigue--sleeping a lot but remains independent of his ADLs and can do some household chores. Taking 1-2L of IV fluids a day. Notes thick secretions in his mouth and throat--amenable to restarting guaifenesin. Still having loose stool--hasn't yet restarted his cholestyramine for his IBS. Denies sob, chest pain, fever, body aches, headaches, or chills but notes his mouth has improved a tiny bit. |2018-06-26:	Patient notes he's slowly improving but feels impatient that he's not improving faster. He feels hungry and has an appetite, but he still can't taste his food and struggles to swallow--down 6lbs from last week. He is trying to consume 1-2 supplements a day but eating feels like a chore--does continue 1L of NS daily. Reports anxiety about his cancer that wakes him up at night--plans to see a counselor at his local cancer center tomorrow. Still having occasional vomiting episodes "out of nowhere"--may be related to taking medications on an empty stomach. Remains on the 25mcg fentanyl patch and only occasionally taking oxycodone before eating--has no pain except when swallowing. Mouth secretions have improved, and he remains independent of his ADLs. |2018-07-03:	Patient notes that he had several days of intermittent vomiting last week despite using scheduled Zofran. He has a persistent right tongue sore which he feels "excretes" a bad taste which interferes with his ability to eat. IV fluids do help--continues to take 1L of normal saline a day. He is on fentanyl 25mcg but he wants to wean down to 12mcg--not having much pain and not using breakthrough meds. He expresses frustration that he's not healing as quickly as he'd like, and he struggles to stay active, especially in the evenings. Remains independent of his ADLs. |2018-08-03:	He is s/p 3/3 cycles of intermediate de-escalation TFHX (last day 6/8/18) and now getting adjuvant nivolumab per protocol. Patient presents for cycle 1 of adjuvant nivolumab. He notes that he's eating solid foods by mouth fairly comfortably--he has to drink a lot of fluid with dry foods, but he can get them all down. His sense of taste is returning slowly, maybe at 20%, but he's trying to be consistent about eating to gain his weight back. Energy is coming back, although he still gets tired easily--was able to keep up with his wife on a traveling vacation last week. Still with a little mucus in the back of his throat which is improving with time. Off all pain medication and anti-emetics now. Does note a swollen mole on his left cheek near his ear--had a similar episode of mole swelling earlier which resolved without intervention. |2018-10-01:	Interval history  -Presents for C3 of adjuvant nivolumab  -Happy with his current weight--has cut out junk food and snacking  -Mouth remains dry but slowly improving--able to taste 60-70% of his food  -Energy continue to increase--back to work, walking the dogs daily, cutting the grass  -Feeling a little stressed and he's in the middle of selling his house and buying a townhome  -Denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, rash, changes in vision, or abdominal pain |2018-10-29:	Interval history  -Presents for C4 of adjuvant nivolumab  -Eating well--taste is almost completely back-->notes that spicy foods now taste intensely hot  -Does feel like there's "something" in his throat--not painful but a bit of a globus sensation-->also mildly increased phlegm and coughing  -Energy is pretty good--has accepted a new job at work which will have him traveling several days a week  -Denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, rash, changes in vision, or abdominal pain |

narrative: 2018-01-01:	January 2018 she noted swelling and discomfort in her left neck. |2018-02-01:	Feb 2018 FNA of left level 2 node showed Squamous cell carcinoma p16 positive. |2018-03-19:	Started C1D1 of OPTIMA2 protocol on 3/19/18. |2018-04-09:	Maria Bonilla is a 66Yrs female, non-smoker with a history of asthma and hypothyroidism newly diagnosed left tonsil HNC, p16-positive, who is being treated with curative intent on the OPTIMA2 protocol. Patient presents with her daughter. She notes that she is tolerating chemotherapy pretty well, and she was able to give herself three injections of GCSF without bone pain. She has occasional nausea for which she takes Zofran (thinks she's taken 4-5 tabs since starting), and her sense of taste is changing (no longer likes the taste of meat). Other than that, she is slightly fatigued but still working (cooks at a family restaurant) and eating as much as she can. She thinks her right-sided neck mass has started to shrink. She denies vomiting, chest pain, fever, chills, trouble swallowing. She occasionally has shortness of breath from her asthma, but she is consistent with her inhaler use. Oncologic Hx:  January 2018 she noted swelling and discomfort in her left neck  ER visit locally, a CT scan was done and showed evidence of cervical lymphadenopathy left level 2 ( 2 nodes: 2.9 x 2.8 cm and 2.1 x1.9cm) as well as a low lying supraclav node borderline enlarged at 1.7cm. 23. Seen  by Dr. Gooi, which showed left neck lymph node conglomerate as well as tonsillar mass. Ms. Bonilla has no weight loss, voice changes, SOB, cough, hemoptysis, or dys/odynophagia. She is a lifelong Non smoker, however does admit to second hand smoke earlier during her life. No alcohol abuse. She and her daughter own a family restaurant. |2018-04-16:	Patient again presents with her daughter. She notes that she struggled a lot more with last week's chemo treatment--had three days of pretty severe nausea without vomiting. Patient took one dose of Zofran a day which did not help much, and her nausea stopped her from eating--lost 3lbs from last week. Her nausea resolved without intervention after several days and her appetite picked up. She is noticing more fatigue now, although she was able to continue working all week. She was able to tolerate 3 injections of GCSF but did not a little mid-back pain, and she's noticed an increase in phlegm production. Right-sided neck mass continues to shrink. She denies vomiting, chest pain, fever, chills, body aches, or trouble swallowing. Still has occasional shortness of breath from her asthma but uses her inhalers. Lifelong non smoker, however does admit to second hand smoke earlier during her life. |2018-04-23:	She presents for C2D15 of induction therapy. Patient notes that last week was much more manageable than the previous week. She has been taking Zofran bid daily with good control over her nausea. She is having a little fatigue, but she is able to do all of her ADLs and work every day at her restaurant. She is now sleeping very soundly at night because of her fatigue. She does note that sometimes her asthma will act up in the spring from pollen, but she's controlling it well now with albuterol and Advair. She does note a red itchy rash on her abdomen which started about two weeks ago, worsened last week, and has now improved a bit (though still present). She's been putting coconut oil and otc anti-itch cream on it with little relief and denies new detergent, perfumes, or products. Aside from that, she denies vomiting, chest pain, fever, chills, body aches, or trouble swallowing and was able to take 3 doses of GCSF without discomfort last week. |2018-04-30:	She presents for C3D1 of induction therapy. Patient notes that she's tired but doing pretty well--she continues to work in her restaurant 6 days a week but it takes her longer to finish her duties. She continues to take Zofran twice a day with good control of her nausea--had a single episode of transient nausea without vomiting earlier in the week. The rash on her stomach has improved with the use of hydrocortisone cream--itching is better. Still eating well but notes that she's losing her taste for savory foods--more interested now in eating sweet things. Tolerated 2 doses of GCSF last week--will take 3 shots of GCSF after this treatment. Feels her neck mass continues to improve. |2018-05-07:	She presents for C3D8 of induction therapy. Patient notes that she struggled this week as she was almost constantly nauseated (had 3 episodes of actual vomiting)--was only able to work a few days because of her discomfort. She was taking zofran intermittently, and she didn't have any compazine at home. When she finally started taking compazine and zofran scheduled, her nausea improved significantly--was able to really eat on Saturday for the first time all week. Her appetite overall is completely gone, but she's still able to get smoothies down. She took 3 doses of GCSF without bone pain. The rash on her abdomen improved but then popped up on her back and legs--now resolving. Subjective This Am Patient's throat pain is present, but much better controlled on the current regimen. Utilized Roxanol 15mg yesterday for pain control. Patient c/o reflux this morning with TF. Rate at 10cc/hr. Increased PPI to BID dosing. Added GI cocktail due to patient's concurrent throat pain and Reglan to help with gastric emptying. Patient experienced a sensation of "burning in her throat" while receiving Taxol infusion today. Had Taxol reaction C1 which consisted of burning sensation in face, throat, flushing, chest pain, and abdominal pain. Vitals stable during this episode without any flushing noted. Provided with 100mg SoluCortef IV with improvement in "burning" sensation. Patient completed Taxol infusion without additional symptoms. |2018-06-05:	She reports feeling improved today. They also discovered "upper respiratory infection" and treated her with antibiotics. Taking a pureed diet by mouth, they put all the food in a  Nutribullet. <5% of food through mouth. Mainly relies on G tube feedings with Kate Farms' Core Essentials formula. Drank her first cup of coffee in 8 months yesterday. No trouble walking or picking things up. -- Bleeding under middle finger nails, stable to slight improvement. -- Has had ongoing challenges with anxiety.
