narrative: 2018-02-19:	2/19/2018 seen by his PCP. |2018-03-08:	3/8/2018 CTs scan -- showed 2.4 x 2.1 x 3.6 cm soft tissue mass located in Level II between the submandibular gland and the SCM superficial to the IJV. |2018-03-13:	3/13/2018 Biopsy at OSF -- ultrasound guided: Infiltrating poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. |2018-04-26:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoked here for follow-up of HPV+ HNC - left tonis T1 N2B. |2018-04-27:	4/27/18: C1D1 Optima 2 Clinical Trial with Carbo/Taxol/Nivo. |2018-05-04:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C1D8 per OPTIMA-2 study (today will receive single agent Abraxane)    Patient feels well today. Felt tired for 1-2 days after his chemotherapy infusion one week ago however energy level quickly returned to baseline. He describes nausea and anorexia which lasted for 2 days following chemotherapy as well. Currently he is eating regular food and drinking liquids without difficulty. He notes "significant shrinkage" of left neck node over the last week. Denies peripheral neuropathy. Denies pain. Denies GI symptoms. He does note a mild, somewhat pruritic rash affecting both arms and forearms onset 4-5 days ago. No fevers. Oncologic History:  Early 2018 noticed lump in his left neck  2/19/2018 seen by his PCP, Dr. Sven Klaus. X-rays normal. 3/8/2018 CTs scan - showed 2.4 x 2.1 x 3.6 cm soft tissue mass located in Level II between the submandibular gland and the SCM superficial to the IJV. No other lymphadenopathy or masses were noted. 3/13/2018 Biopsy at OSF - ultrasound guided: Infiltrating poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. 4/27/18: C1D1 Optima 2 Clinical Trial with Carbo/Taxol/Nivo    Works as a saleperson for swimming pool equipment. ECOG Performance Status: 0 |2018-05-10:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C1D15 per OPTIMA-2 study (today will receive single agent Abraxane)    He is here with his daughter for C1D15. Tolerating treatment well. No N/V. No GI upset. Travels and continues to work without any physical limitations. He does notice taste change (metallic taste) but is maintaining weight. Has some intermittent tingling in hands but not bothersome. His only complaint is persistent rash on his forearms. He is using Zyrtec and topical cortisone and says that these help. His psoriasis lesions (L knee and scalp) seem to actually be doing better. He declined prescription strength topical steroids and will continue current plan. He did take Neupogen injections at home without issues. No fevers, chills, s/sx infection. Ready for treatment. |2018-05-17:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C2D1 per OPTIMA-2 study     He is here with his significant other today. He had a harder time with side effects this past week. He was celebrating a son's graduation and feels fatigued from the weekend. He has also been struggling with maintaining weight due to change in taste. His appetite is also fairly poor. He denies N/V. He has no mechanical issues with eating. He has not found many foods that taste good but is trying to eat as much as he can per encouragement of his friends/family and family member that is an oncology dietician. His other complaint is that he developed diarrhea Wednesday, 3-4 loose stools/day which is not normal for him. No new medications or change in diet that he thinks caused this. Did have a low grade fever Monday 99.8 but nothing since. No foul smell to diarrhea, no blood, no abdominal pain. Has not tried anything yet. He continues to have itching under his arms but overall skin is better the last few weeks. No neuropathy. Is doing Neupogen injections at home. No new issues otherwise. |2018-05-23:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C2D8 per OPTIMA-2 study     He is here with his son for C2D8. Doing well the last week. Played 18 holes of golf. Took Neupogen injections as directed. Was having diarrhea, but then took Pepcid, and became constipation, and then stopped, and loose stools have returned. He states no more than 1 loose stool a day and denies abdominal cramping, blood in stool, or other symptoms. He states his skin itching and rash have resolved. No other toxicities. He continues to struggle with finding foods that taste good but has been eating a lot of ramen and drinking protein shakes and feels he is maintaining a good weight. |2018-05-31:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C2D8 per OPTIMA-2 study     He is here for C2D15. Has noticed some mild fatigue and decrease in exercise tolerance. No significant GI upset. Has loose stools but he thinks this is because his diet is mostly liquids at this point. It is no more than 1 loose stool/day and controlled with Imodium. No abdominal pain. Psoriasis lesions wax and wane but are not bothersome. No rash otherwise. No new issues today. Is taking Granix as directed. No fevers/chills. |2018-06-07:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C2D8 per OPTIMA-2 study     He is here for C3D1. Doing about the same in the last week. He is feeling deconditioned with certain activities but denies dyspnea at rest, walking flat surfaces, or with exertion in particular. He denies chest pain. He has some clear productive sinus drainage sometimes. He has diarrhea which he is able to control with Imodium but then it constipates him for a few days. No abdominal pain or blood. Taking Granix. Still struggling with mild fatigue/anorexia cumulative from chemotherapy but continues most regular activities. Also notes some occasional foot drop when hes tired but no leg weakness, neuropathy, or other symptoms. |2018-06-18:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C3D8 per OPTIMA-2 study     Patient notes that he feels a little fatigued but he just returned from a trip and hasn't caught up on his sleep. He has no taste and has mostly been eating ramen noodles supplemented by proteins (down 6lbs since last week), but he's now trying to consume more supplements to keep up his weight. His right neck mass continues to shrink and he is looking forward to confirming such on his next imaging. Took three gcsf injections last week and is amenable to taking 3 more this week. He is having loose stools at least once daily but gets quite constipated when he takes imodium. Has a rash on his left ankle which he thinks is his chronic psoriasis exacerbated by nivo--continues to use hydrocortisone cream on it. He denies sob, chest pain, fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting. |2018-06-25:	Mark Hines is a 52Yrs male, non-smoker with HPV+ HNC, T1N2b left tonsil SCC presents to clinic for induction chemotherapy C3D15 per OPTIMA-2 study     Patient notes that his appetite is down and he has a constant metallic taste in his mouth--has to force himself to eat but is able to swallow comfortably. He can barely feel his neck mass as it has shrunk so much. Tolerated 3 doses of gcsf without bone pain. Now having a little constipation--amenable to trying prune juice. Mildly tired but still independent of ADLs and able to work. Left ankle rash has improved with hydrocortisone. |

narrative: 2017-12-01:	End of Dec 2017 -- felt like "piece of food" was caught in throat/felt like sore throat when swallowing. |2018-01-01:	Jan 2018 Went to "Quick Care" -- given a round of antibiotics. |2018-01-01:	Jan 2018 Developed a sensation of something stuck in his throat and then progression to a sore throat since the end of December. |2018-03-01:	March 2018 -- saw his PCP Dr. Tahir Rohail. |2018-04-19:	4/19/2018 -- biopsy. |2018-04-27:	4/27/2018 PET--CT done at Hinsdale. |2018-05-04:	5/4/2018 saw Dr. Haraf. |2018-05-10:	5/10/2018: C1D1 Carbo/Abraxane/Nivo induction on IRB 17--0104. |2018-05-10:	Don Koob is a 61Yrs male with OSA, HTN, HL, with newly diagnosed left Tonsil cancer p16+. Smokes 2 cigars a day for past 5 years. Quit in December    ECOG Performance Status: 0    End of Dec 2017 - felt like "piece of food" was caught in throat/felt like sore throat when swallowing    Jan 2018 Went to "Quick Care" - given a round of antibiotics    End of January - swollen left neck LN, another round of antibiotics and steroid, and swelling went down. However did not fully resolved    March 2018 - saw his PCP Dr. Tahir Rohail, another round of Antibiotics, and referral to ENT. Beginning April - Dr. Krasenan (ENT) in Hinsdale  4/19/2018 - biopsy, squamous cell carcinoma. P16+ - felt to be HPV associated. 4/27/2018 PET-CT done at Hinsdale. 5/4/2018 saw Dr. Haraf, now presenting also to Dr. Blair. 5/10/2018: C1D1 Carbo/Abraxane/Nivo induction on IRB 17-0104. HPI: Mr. Koob is a 61Yrs year-old male who presents today for follow up regarding the role of radiotherapy in the management of tonsil cancer. Information pertinent to his oncologic history is as follows:    Developed a sensation of something stuck in his throat and then progression to a sore throat since the end of December. Went to local MD in January. Was place on antibiotics. Has gone through 3 course of antibiotics and one round of steroids without improvement. Went back to PCP and sent to ENT who looked int his noted a tonsilar mass. A biopsy was performed which showed an HPV p16+ squamous cell carcinoma . Today in clinic, Mr. Koob reports that he is feeling well but he dose have significant 4/10 pain with chewing/opening his mouth. This is partially resolved by acetaminophen. He denies any difficulty swallowing. He had  enlarged left neck node but this has since resolved. He does have some trismus. This history was obtained from Mr. Koob. A translator was used during this consultation: no    Interval History:  He is here with his wife to begin C1D1 Carbo/Abraxane/Nivo. He has some discomfort from his procedure yesterday and is taking scheduled pain medication which helps. He went to an urgent care and they removed some tonsilliths. He followed up with a dentist who recommended some rinses. He eventually went to see an ENT and he had a biopsy of the tonsillar mass on 7/14/18 with pathology revealing SCC, p16 positive. He went for 2nd opinion at Rush and had a neck CT on 7/13/18 with a 3.1 x 2.7 x 5 cm enhancing mass in the right palatine tonsil with involvement of right aspect of soft palate, right glossotonsillar sulcus, and right lateral oropharyngeal wall with a mildly enlarged 1.6 x 1.7 cm right level 2 lymph node. He wants to get chemo closer to home. He will get his radiation at Hyde Park. He is now having arthralgias in his ankles, knees, shoulders, and toes. He has lost his hair. He has some mild nausea after he eats and controls this with compazine. He states the throat pain has improved but now it feels like there is a piece of string stuck in his throat after he eats. He also noticed that it sounds different when he swallows water. narrative: 2016-07-01:	The tumor cells are positive for p63 and p16. |2016-07-01:	p16 and p63+. |2018-06-01:	08/16/2018 Lymph node neck. |2018-06-01:	He reports first noticing a sensation of something being stuck in his throat in 6/2018. |2018-08-04:	08/04/2018 CT Neck: LYMPH NODES:A suspicious morphology rounded 1.0 x 1.2 x 1.1 cm level IIa lymph node is present A left level III lymph node measures 1.0 x 1.3 x 2.0 cmA left level V node measuring 1.4 x 1.4 x 1.7 cm demonstrates perinodal fat stranding. |2018-08-16:	NO NEW INFORMATION|2018-08-21:	08/21/2018 PET/CT: Hypermetabolic soft tissue nodularity and fullness. |2018-08-21:	08/21/2018 PET/CT: Hypermetabolic soft tissue nodularity and fullness within the left tongue base extending inferiorly to the level of the epiglottis suspicious. |2018-08-29:	Barry Sherman is a 74 year-od with male with SCC of the skin, HTN, HLD, allergic rhinitis and chronic middle ear effusion, who presents for second opinion regarding a newly diagnosed left BOT SCC. He was seen by a doctor and prescribed a short course of antibiotics without improvement. He then noted swelling in the left neck, starting in July, and so sought medical attention from a local ENT. He was given another course of antibiotics, without improvement, and so a CT was ordered in August. This revealed suspicious lymph nodes left cervical lymph nodes, I nthe level IIa, III, and V chains, as well as a level Vb supraclavicular lymph node. FNA on 8/16 revealed SCC, p16 and p63+. Subsequent PET-CT on 8/21 revealed likely left BOT primary lesion extending from inferiorly to the epiglottis and superiorly to the palatine tonsil. The nodes on prior CT (left IIA, IIB, III, IV, VB, and right IIA and IIB/III were all noted to be hypermetabolic. Finally, there were multiple subcentimeter pulmonary nodules, too small to characterize, but one did show mild FDG-uptake. He is referred to Dr. Pearson's clinic for discussion of chemo as part of combined modality chemo/RT treatment. Oncology History:  1. A left level Vb/supraclavicular lymph node measures 1.6 x 1.9 cm . This also demonstrates surrounding infiltration. A 1.8 x 1.8 x 2.0 cm level III node is seen . 2. 08/16/2018 Lymph node neck, FNA:Left Neck Lymph Node: squamous cell carcinoma. 3. 08/21/2018 PET/CT: Hypermetabolic soft tissue nodularity and fullness within the left tongue base extending inferiorly to the level of the epiglottis suspicious  for primary head and neck malignancy. Additionally there is hypermetabolic uptake which extends superiorly into the level of the left palatine tonsil, which may also represent tumor extension. Hypermetabolic bilateral lymphadenopathy, involving the left parapharyngeal region, left levels 2A, 2B, 3, 4, and 5B and right level 2A and 2B/3. Tiny subcentimeter pulmonary nodules as above, one of which demonstrates mildly increased uptake. Findings are nonspecific, though metastatic lesion cannot be completely excluded. Slightly more linear increased uptake in the posterior nasopharynx at midline, possibly inflammatory      Interval History:  - reports stable swelling of the left neck. - no dysphagia, choking when he eats  - no dyspnea  - no snoring |2018-09-07:	Barry Sherman is a 74 year-od with male with SCC of the skin, HTN, HLD, allergic rhinitis and chronic middle ear effusion, (T2N2cM0) SCC of the left BOT presents for induction chemotherapy C1D1 per OPTIMA-II study    He reports first noticing a sensation of something being stuck in his throat in 6/2018. 08/21/2018 PET/CT: Hypermetabolic soft tissue nodularity and fullness  within the left tongue base extending inferiorly to the level of the epiglottis suspicious  for primary head and neck malignancy. Slightly more linear increased uptake in the posterior nasopharynx at midline, possibly inflammatory      Interval History:  - Patient feels well in general.
